SCENE I <attbytes>20Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767840</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Garibaldi: A Chronicle Play of Italian Freedom in Ten Scenes</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1936</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The headquarters of the Association known as</hi> &ldquo;<hi r="italic">Young Italy</hi>,&rdquo; <hi r="italic">in Marseilles. March</hi> 1834.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">A dark room, with the window heavily curtained, lit by an oil lamp and candles, and heated by a stove. On the walls are a map of Italy, brightly coloured in kingdoms, several crudely printed manifestos, lithographs of Dante and Byron, and a streamer with the words</hi> &ldquo;<hi r="italic">Viva l'Italia</hi>.&rdquo;</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The table is in a disorder of documents, correspondence, newspapers, note&hyphen;books, and writing materials. A shelf of books, a few chairs and a plain bench complete the furniture of the room, which is devoid of comforts but for the stove. Seated on a chair in front of this is Joseph Mazzini, twenty&hyphen;nine years of age, dressed in a seedy but neat high&hyphen;fitting black frock&hyphen;coat, a scarf round his neck, and black trousers. He has great personal beauty. He is filling the room with cigar smoke, and is playing a guitar. Placing his cigar on the stove, he hums the words of a song to his own accompaniment. There is a sharp repeated double knock on the door. Mazzini, recovering his cigar, <pb n="10">rises, turns the key in the lock, and resumes his seat. Two young Italians come in. The last&hyphen;comer turns the key again</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">short and rather fat</hi>).</stage> <p>Look here, Joseph Mazzini, I've done with it. I resign.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, my Beppo. Every week you resign. What is it this time?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>And it isn't funny either. I don't know where my ticket is&mdash;I've lost it, but if I'd got it you could have it there on the table, and that's flat.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">still touching the guitar</hi>).</stage> <p>Very well, Beppo, you resign. I hope you'll have a successful career. Where do you propose to go&mdash;or am I being inquisitive?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">sulky</hi>).</stage> <p>I shall go to America.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ah&mdash;a nice big place. When do you leave us&mdash;this evening?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>I tell you it isn't funny.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Of course it isn't funny. We shall be very sorry to lose you. But, after all, you know best. Let me see&mdash;you can't become President unless you're born in the country. Still, there are lots of other opportunities out there. Have a cigar.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>No. Yes. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Taking one from a box on the <pb n="11">table</hi>.)</stage> I say, Joseph, you might be reasonable about it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Aren't I?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>No. I tell you I'm resigning, and all you can do is to be superior. And can't you stop playing that guitar when I'm talking.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Certainly. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He does so</hi>.)</stage> Well?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>It's serious.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>What is?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>I am. My grievance.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>My good Beppo, you are a very valuable member of our organisation. You are brave and you are intelligent. But once a week you come here with a grievance, and resign. What do you expect me to do? Cry?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's it&mdash;sneer at me. You think I'm nobody.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising&mdash;suddenly serious&mdash;pointing to the streamer</hi>).</stage> <p>Viva l'Italia. What do you mean by nobody? Sometimes I've no patience with you, Beppo. We are Young Italy, aren't we? And what is Young Italy&mdash;what are we? Fugitives from our own land, discredited by failure among our own people, driven into hiding even here in France, where a free government has decreed us outlaws. Three of our printing presses have been destroyed; in this room, here in Marseilles, we are <pb n="12">not safe. Everything has to be begun over again&mdash;our friends scattered&mdash;our money gone&mdash;nothing left but faith. You understand, Beppo, faith? You see that Italy&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">pointing to the map</hi>)</stage> one kingdom, two kingdoms, three kingdoms, the Pope there, and the Austrians there&mdash;black feuds and tyrannies everywhere. This was a fair land. Was it? Eighteen hundred and thirty&hyphen;four years after Christ. That, my friend, is the land of the Italians, and&mdash;you see the fingers of my hand&mdash;are there as many free Italians under Vienna, under Bourbon, under Savoy, under papal Rome? Not so many as the fingers on my hand. That is what we have to do&mdash;to make all Italy one Italy, and free. We have to start again. <stage>(<hi r="italic">A little wearily</hi>)</stage> We must write&mdash;must it be a million letters, in a million years. But, if we keep our faith, it will come. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Flaming</hi>)</stage> It shall come. And now, at this hour of new and resolute dedication, you, Beppo, tell me that I think of any man sworn among us as nobody. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Relaxing</hi>)</stage> What is your trouble now?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Give me a plain answer to a plain question. Is this new Italy to be a Republic?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Then why do you allow this fellow Garibaldi to go about talking as though it didn't matter one way or another?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="13">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>If you get to know him better, you will find that no one can stop Garibaldi saying what he pleases.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Listen. I've been talking to a Piedmontese sailor, who was with Garibaldi when he was at Genoa trying to win over the fleet&mdash;with about as much chance as you had with your volunteers on the Swiss frontier. That's all right&mdash;it was a washout for all of us, and, as you say, we've got to begin all over again. But let us know what we're at. This sailor told me that Garibaldi was saying everywhere that Italy under a Piedmontese king or Italy a republic was all one, so long as we had an Italy free. I know about Piedmontese kings&mdash;I've lived there, and I'ld as soon have the Pope or Bourbon or the white devil from Austria himself, as Charles Albert. And if Garibaldi's word is to have any authority in this show, I'm out of it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Leave Garibaldi alone. It won't be what Garibaldi thinks, but what he does that will matter, when the time comes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, I want a republic, and if I can't get it in Italy, I'll go to America where I can.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>You know, Beppo, you'ld only upset America if you went. I wouldn't. Stay and do your work here, like a good lad. Have a drink. <pb n="14"><stage>(<hi r="italic">He pours out three glasses. They drink</hi>.)</stage> There. Resignation withdrawn?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>What's the good of trying to say anything to you, Joseph? You'ld wheedle the Pope himself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">the third of the party, a lank, hungry young man, who has been sitting on the bench, smoking a clay pipe</hi>).</stage> <p>Now you've done your piece, I'll tell you a bit of news.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not good news, I take it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's as may be. Garibaldi is in Marseilles.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Here? Garibaldi?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Now, what other name could that be mistaken for?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>He's been quick about it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's another thing you may learn about Garibaldi. He has a way of being quick.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">to Zucchi</hi>).</stage> <p>How do you know?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I saw him. On the quay. He was buying chestnuts from a pedlar. I heard him talking. &ldquo;Are these Italian chestnuts?&rdquo; he said, and the pedlar said &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; and Garibaldi said, &ldquo;We'll pull the Italian chestnuts out of the fire yet,&rdquo; and he bought a sou's worth.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Didn't you speak to him?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>What should I do speaking to him? I'm nobody.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="15">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Another nobody? The best poet of us all, and nobody?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>What are poets in this galley?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>They will serve us too.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>They say Garibaldi is a poet.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>But not a very good one. He may lead us to victory, but the horse he rides won't be Pegasus. When he comes, Beppo, none of this Republican business, understand. Sat ad diem diei malum est.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph Mazzini, don't be rhetorical, and give me another drink.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">as Mazzini does so</hi>).</stage> <p>But will he come here?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Why else should he be in Marseilles? To buy chestnuts?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Why the devil didn't you go over the Swiss frontier instead of fluttering about like a winged partridge?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Because at the last moment I knew that we were before our time. Never strike before the time. ...</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The double knock, repeated, at the door</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's too loud. It's Garibaldi.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Beppo turns the key, and Garibaldi comes in. He is twenty&hyphen;seven years of age, with chestnut&hyphen;coloured hair and beard, dressed <pb n="16">in a blouse, bag&hyphen;breeches, high boots, and a slouch hat</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking his hand</hi>).</stage> <p>Good&hyphen;evening, Joseph.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Good&hyphen;evening, Joseph.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">turning the key</hi>).</stage> <p>Have a cigar.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking one from his pocket</hi>).</stage> <p>Thank you&mdash;I have a fancy for my own. Cheap, but strong.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>And so the navy wasn't listening?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>No. I failed; you failed&mdash;all of us. We've been put back ten years. More, perhaps.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Will you drink? <stage>(<hi r="italic">Giving him a glass</hi>.)</stage> Why did you come here?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>To buy chestnuts?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">holding out his glass, which Mazzini fills</hi>).</stage> <p>Thank you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I came to tell you this. Our first cast has failed. You know&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">casting a line</hi>)</stage> you put the fish down. Then you go away, and wait for an hour&mdash;a year&mdash;ten years. Very well; we are all young; we can wait. Only don't let doctrinaire ideas run away with you. We want Italy united. Don't we?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>What then?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Don't be set on a Republic, that's all. <pb n="17">If had my choice, that's it. But Italy united may mean a monarchy yet. A monarchy that Europe will salute. Get that into your heads.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>I told you so.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very well, Joseph.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very well, Joseph. God, I'm tired.</p>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Sinking into a chair</hi>.</stage>
<stanza><l>How many men,</l>
<l>How many men,</l>
<l>Will Italy want to be free, and then</l>
<l>How many more,</l>
<l>How many more,</l>
<l>Will Italy want, want, want, before</l>
<l>She rises out of the dust to stand</l>
<l>In the eyes of the world a fatherland?</l></stanza>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Suddenly rising, he exclaims:</hi></stage>
<p>Friends, I'm exhausted. For thirty days I've been the mouse of a hundred Austrian and French cats. And I've come through the lot of 'em. A little, by your leave. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Mazzini fills his glass</hi>.)</stage> That's better. Drink doesn't make me drunk, it sobers me. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He sits again</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">The repeated double knock on the door. Beppo turns the key. Six young men come in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Young Man</hi>.</speaker> <p>Letters, Mazzini.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He puts them on the table</hi>.</stage>
<pb n="18">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Anything from Genoa?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Young Man</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">picking it out, and reading; icily cold</hi>).</stage> <p>From Genoa. Listen. Jacopo Ruffino, my friend, my friend in whose house I lived, given death or the betrayal of his fellows, hanged himself in his cell. Ten of my townsmen fell before the firing squad. A hundred are in Italian prisons under sentence for life. Viva l'Italia&mdash;do you understand, my friends ~&mdash;Viva l'Italia. When all Italy is bleeding. We have stood, have we not, for an idea. Hear me&mdash;ideas ripen quickly when nourished by the blood of martyrs. Jacopo Ruffino&mdash;Jacopo Ruffino&mdash;teach me to bear this, O Lord.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">reading a newspaper from the post</hi>).</stage> <p>Here, client of the chestnut&hyphen;pedlar, is a paragraph for you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>What is it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">reading</hi>).</stage> <p>&ldquo;By the high court of Piedmont, Whereas Joseph Garibaldi, rebel and menace to the state, has been adjudged guilty of treason, the said Garibaldi is sentenced to death and shall be apprehended dead or alive at the price of a thousand crowns.&rdquo;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>The price is excessive. <stage>(<hi r="italic">General laughter. He rises</hi>.)</stage> Yes, I meant you to laugh. But now stop laughing. We are Young Italy. In a few years we shall be Young Italy no longer. We <pb n="19">shall be Italy with swords sharpened against them all. Republic or monarchy, no matter. Go into the far ends of the earth, all of you. Bide your time. It will come. The seeds are sown, do not be impatient of the harvest. I am going far to the west&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's it&mdash;to America.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>America&mdash;but I shall wait. Presently Italians in Italy will rise and proclaim an Italy free. Wherever I may be I shall hear them, and I shall come back, to strike. I tell you, friends, thus&mdash;</p>
<stanza><l>Whenever the voice of Italia calls,</l>
<l>O'er the sundering seas I shall waken and hear</l>
<l>The word that my vigilant spirit enthralls,</l> <l>Though far from her bidding yet shall I be near. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Applause</hi>.</stage></l></stanza></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>A very fine sentiment, Joseph.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Sentiment? What do you mean by sentiment? What's the matter with the poetry?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, you know, if you ask me, it's pretty bad poetry.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Who is this?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Antonio Zucchi. The best poet in Italy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, he's a damn bad critic. Never mind, Antonio my boy, I daresay you're right. I <pb n="20">only do these things to make the going lighter. Put rhyming aside, and I'll tell you&mdash;I love Italy&mdash;we all love Italy, and some day yet we'll meet again with Italy our own.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Glasses lifted all round, as Mazzini takes up his guitar, and</hi></stage>
<trailer><hi r="smcap">the scene closes</hi></trailer>
</div3>
<pb n="21">
<div3>
<comhd3><idref>Z300767841</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
SCENE II <attbytes>33Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767841</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Garibaldi: A Chronicle Play of Italian Freedom in Ten Scenes</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1936</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">June 30th</hi>, 1849.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">An upper room in the Sparda Villa overlooking the walls of Rome, Garibaldi's headquarters during the siege</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The building is half&hyphen;wrecked after continuous bombardment. There is a hole in the ceiling, debris lies about the floor, the walls are heavily shot&hyphen;marked. Through the broken shutters two young Italian sharpshooters are at work, firing at intervals throughout the scene. Also there is an intermittent sound of gunfire in the distance</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Seated at the dilapidated table is Beppo, one arm in a sling, writing and dealing with papers. Propped up against the wall, lying on the floor, is Zucchi, his head bandaged, semi&hyphen;conscious. The fifteen years since we saw them at Marseilles have taken more than their natural toll. They wear volunteer uniform, with loose blue tunics</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">An intense summer heat pervades the room</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rousing himself</hi>).</stage> <p>What's happened&mdash;have they stopped blowing us up? That isn't like them.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="22">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Only for a minute or two. Don't worry. They'll be at it again.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Three perishing weeks shut up in a box to be shot at. You know, it wasn't so bad when we were trailing about after the General outside the walls. You could do something then&mdash;have a go at somebody. I'ld rather be on the Corsini itself than in this hole. God&mdash;the Corsini. I don't see how any of us came away alive. Masina, Menara, Mameli, Dandalo&mdash;what boys. Makes us feel old men, eh, Beppo? But that was fighting&mdash;not being shot at in a box. One of 'em has pretty near shot my head off, I think. Where's old Ugo Bassi?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>He came in again just now&mdash;you were asleep. He said you'ld pull through all right.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Is there any water? <stage>(<hi r="italic">Beppo gives him a tin from the table</hi>.)</stage> A great fellow, old Ugo, isn't he? You don't find many priests like that. He's told the Pope what he thinks about the church and its ways. As bad as the Austrians themselves, so that no man can call his life his own, let alone his soul. That's what he told the Pope. I believe that man really is a Christian. And as brave&mdash;shall you ever forget him up on the Corsini, just a saint of tenderness in all that filth, in the thick of it, as though he wanted to be killed.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Perhaps he does. We're done for, you <pb n="23">know. Our friends the French have done for us. We may last out a day or two more&mdash;it can't be longer. And then Italy will be delivered to the Bourbon again, and the Austrians, and the mercies of a temporal church. And what will happen to the likes of Ugo Bassi then? Small wonder if he wants to die. It's probably the best thing that could happen to any of us.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Do you remember that night fifteen years ago in Marseilles&mdash;when Garibaldi came in? Funny&mdash;how it comes back&mdash;I'd seen him buying chestnuts on the quay. It was after the fiasco on the Swiss frontier. Both he and Mazzini told us&mdash;you remember?&mdash;that we should have to begin all over again&mdash;that we might have to wait ten years, perhaps more. We've waited fifteen, and now, when the day has come, we are smothered by the Frenchmen. What the devil did they want to interfere for?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>They call it diplomacy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>To oblige a Bourbon king in Naples, an imperial fa&ccedil;ade in Vienna, a political Vatican&mdash;to do this, Louis Napoleon and the Republic of France, save the mark, have suffocated our free Italy at birth. Curse their diplomacy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">As he is speaking, Garibaldi comes in. His red&hyphen;shirt uniform shows the marks <pb n="24">of several weeks' continuous fighting, a wound in the side still causes him occasional inconvenience. He is smoking a cigar</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not suffocated&mdash;you mustn't say that, Zucchi. We breathe yet. How's the pain?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>It might be worse.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>We shall have the doctor here directly. He'll soon put you right.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ugo Bassi has been looking after me. He's as good as a Doctor.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>He's a lovely man. He'll get himself shot though. Sometimes I want to place him under arrest. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Going to the shuttered window, looking through the breach</hi>.)</stage> I wonder what they're up to out there. We shall pay for our five minutes' quiet if I know them.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>You don't think there's any hope of holding out, do you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not any longer in Rome. But if I can get that pig&hyphen;head Mazzini to let me get out with the men into the open, I'll lead these Frenchmen dancing till they've worn the boots off their feet. By the way, you needn't mention to anyone that I called Mazzini a pig&hyphen;head. But he is.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>When you've danced their boots off, what then? You know we can't beat France.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Italy could, fighting for her own.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="25">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Italy&mdash;yes. But we're not Italy. If the French hadn't come we might have persuaded Italy to send the Bourbon and the Austrian packing with the Pope. But the French have come, and they've made our bright little Roman Republic a flash in the pan. What shall we be now but a few voices crying in the Italian wilderness? Who's going to take any notice of us when we've got the French army at our heels? No. It's all up with us.</p></speech></pdiv>
<monologue><monospkr>Garibaldi</monospkr><monogend>M</monogend>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p><monostart>xxdummykwxx</monostart>You are not to say that&mdash;even your wound can't excuse that, Zucchi. For twelve years I have been fighting over the plains of Rio Grande and Monte Video with a handful of Italian exiles, in preparation for this day. We feared nothing, spared ourselves nothing, asked for nothing from the people we served. We were dedicated, waiting on a call. Beppo here can tell you. Best of all, Anita could tell you. You haven't seen Anita, Zucchi. No man in the world has a wife like Anita. That was a day&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">laughing at the recollection</hi>)</stage> you know, Zucchi, I saw her through a telescope from a ship. &ldquo;That's the girl for me,&rdquo; I said, and I went ashore, and, by God, she was the girl for me. At first sight, both of us&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">snapping his fingers</hi>)</stage> like that. And then she faced everything with me, endured everything. Danger, <pb n="26">death, love&mdash;you should see her ride&mdash;eh, Beppo? She, too, dedicated herself to Italy, for my sake. She could tell you how patiently we kept the flame alive.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Where is she now?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>At Nice&mdash;or I think so. But you never know where Anita is. She'll be watching. Defeat or exile, she will come. But I tell you, Zucchi, if we have to wait another ten years, the end is not yet. If I live, I shall come back. If I die here in Rome, like Mameli, like Dandalo, others will wait and come again. The French may break us now, but that is not the end. There can be but one end. I know it as surely as though the Maker had spoken it to me face to face. The faith of those boys who died on the Corsini is too strong. It is a faith in Italy free and united, and in this hour of our extremity I swear it shall prevail.</p></speech></pdiv></monologue>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Ugo Bassi comes in. His dress is a compromise between his priestly vocation and the exercise of war</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">to Zucchi</hi>).</stage> <p>How is it? Easier?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Just tiresome&mdash;you know.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>The doctor's on the way up. <stage>(<hi r="italic">To Garibaldi</hi>)</stage> There's a movement up by the guns. I expect they're going to start again.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>There's a detachment of Bersaglieri <pb n="27">down by the Pancrazio gate, waiting my word to attack outside the walls.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>What good can that do?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>They may get at those guns&mdash;they nearly managed it yesterday. And perhaps you wouldn't mind telling me who's in command at this place?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>All right. Only&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Only nothing. Ugo, tell Serini or Paolo to take the order down, will you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'll take it myself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh yes, I know&mdash;so that you can go and have a little diversion up by the guns yourself. You do as I tell you, and stay here where I can see what you're up to.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">The French artillery reopens from the height beyond; a shot takes away another portion of the shutters</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>You know it's a cruel place to attack&mdash;I ought to be with them&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ugo Bassi, I don't like argumentative priests. If it comes to that, I don't like priests at all. Except one. And I happen to like him well enough to watch that he doesn't get into mischief. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Pointing down through the broken shutters</hi>.)</stage> If I see you go out of that door I'll have you arrested. Now get along.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="28">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>All right. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Going</hi>.)</stage> There's a back door.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Here&mdash;you sit down. You know, you aren't to be trusted. Beppo, you take that message&mdash;Paolo or Serini.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Beppo goes out, as Bassi sits reluctantly by Zucchi</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph, we're beaten, aren't we?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>We shall be beaten out of Rome, yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>My wretched Italy. O miserable Church of God. What things you do in His holy name. Will the hand of oppression never be lifted from the people of this land? If to die for Italy were all&mdash;how easy. But in life to make Italy rise and know herself, to bring her out of shame and servitude and death, to see her proud and free&mdash;what a forlorn dream is that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ugo Bassi in despair? Then these Frenchmen have broken us indeed.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'm sorry, Joseph. May God forgive me. They say down in the city that Mazzini means to be on the wall when the last breach is made.</p></speech></pdiv>
<monologue><monospkr>Garibaldi</monospkr><monogend>M</monogend>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p><monostart>xxdummykwxx</monostart>Well. If he chooses that way out. He and I haven't got on very well together. He is too full of political theories for me. He can see everything but the obvious. I may be able to see nothing else, but I can see that. What most pleases him about this Roman Republic that is <pb n="29">dying after three months of life, is that it has been a Republic, with Joseph Mazzini Triumvir. He has for ever been harping on it&mdash;Republic&mdash;Republic&mdash;the Italian Republic. I don't question his motives&mdash;no man can question Mazzini's motives. But I question his gumption, which is something I picked up on the plains of Brazil. When he called me to Rome I came because I had sworn that when there should be action in Italy I would be there. But I knew that he had seen it wrong&mdash;had missed the one plain truth of it all. He thought he could rouse Italy by doctrine, his own pure example. He can't. I see it clearly enough. Italy will not rise at the bidding of this man or that, Mazzini or another. It will rise by some native power generated in the people. And I'll tell you, Ugo, where that power is. It is in Piedmont. Piedmont for the moment may have been humiliated by the Austrians at Novara. But in Piedmont there is a young king, and there is brooding, even in defeat, the spirit of a free people. That is where we shall find the example yet that will rouse Italy&mdash;not in the devoted dreams of a political philosopher. Mazzini knows much that I don't, but he doesn't know this simple thing as I know it. Victor Emmanuel, king of a liberated Piedmont, that is the name of our salvation. I don't know how it <pb n="30">will come, or when, but when it comes it will be in that name. There's a sermon for you, preacher. And now, to make as good an end as we may of this. <stage>(<hi r="italic">A sound of cheering comes up from the distance</hi>.)</stage> That's the Bersaglieri going out. There's nothing for me to do here. I'll go up and see how they get on.</p></speech></pdiv></monologue>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Your death won't help us.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>What's the use of telling him that? Every day for a month he has been showing himself off to any French rifle that had wit enough to know its chance. If I'd been in command he'd have been court&hyphen;martialled for it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>If you had been in command we should all have been in the Adriatic Sea by now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>All right. Go out&mdash;stand up on the wall&mdash;a nice high part of it, in your red shirt, wave a flag at them, shout it out, &ldquo;I'm Garibaldi, three shots a penny, viva l'Italia.&rdquo;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'll tell you, Beppo&mdash;you ought to have been in a circus, going through a hoop&mdash;a little hoop, like a funny little fat monkey. And, by the way, they've come. They're in there.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Who's come?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>The shirts.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising</hi>).</stage> <p>What&mdash;the red shirts&mdash;for us?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes. It's a bit late, but let us take <pb n="31">our last Roman chance in them together. And some day, perhaps, they'll be seen again.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'll make sure of getting my size.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>They stretch. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Beppo goes</hi>.</stage></p>
<p>Ugo&mdash;I should like you to wear one&mdash;would you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>If you say so, Joseph.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I want mine too.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He gets up as the Doctor comes in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Doctor</hi>.</speaker> <p>What's this&mdash;who's walking about?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>It's my head, you know, Doctor&mdash;I don't walk on my head.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Doctor</hi>.</speaker> <p>Sit down. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Zucchi does so</hi>.)</stage> Let me see.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He examines the wound</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">to the Doctor</hi>).</stage> <p>I did what I could.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">to the sharpshooters</hi>).</stage> <p>You'd better get yours. You can leave the window for a minute.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The two Young Men go out</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Doctor</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">dressing Zucchi's wound</hi>).</stage> <p>Not so bad. <stage>(<hi r="italic">To Garibaldi</hi>)</stage> Mazzini is coming.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>What, now?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Doctor</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes. I saw him down the road. <stage>(<hi r="italic">To Zucchi</hi>)</stage> There&mdash;you needn't be alarmed. A quarter of an inch would have done it, but it's all right.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Then could I go and get my shirt? I know I should feel better in a red shirt.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="32">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Doctor</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very well&mdash;come along.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He helps Zucchi out</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The firing has been continuous. Now another piece of the shutter is blown away, and the shot strikes the wall a foot or two away from Garibaldi. He moves to the spot, and places his fingers on it. Then he picks up the shot from the floor, contemplates it for a moment, and tosses it on to the table</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">An Aide comes in. He salutes, and turns again towards the door</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The Aide</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph Mazzini, Triumvir of Rome.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Indeed?</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Mazzini, still in his frock&hyphen;coat, comes in. He is aged and worn</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Good afternoon, Joseph.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Good afternoon, Joseph.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking Beppo's chair at the table</hi>).</stage> <p>Very warm.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Devilish hot. <stage>(<hi r="italic">To the Aide</hi>)</stage> You'll find a red shirt in there.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The Aide</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, sir. Thank you, sir. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>How long can we hold out?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>As long as they let us. They may make the last assault to&hyphen;night. When they make it we can die on the walls, but we can't keep them out of Rome.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Then it's the end.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="33">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>The end of your Republic, Joseph.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Is there nothing we can do? I'll call upon the people&mdash;they will defend their walls.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Don't be absurd. I'll have no mob meddling with war. You should have let me do as I wanted five days ago. I could have taken the army out of the city, and your government with it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>And abandon Rome.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, what of it? We're losing Rome in any case. We could have gone out five days ago with the army and the executive intact. Now we shall be driven out, and if any of my men&mdash;our men&mdash;come with me, we shall go as fugitives.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>We had to wait here for the end. If we can do nothing else, we must make a story for Italy. The Roman Republic will be a name.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I tell you, Joseph, there's got to be more than a story and a name. There's got to be a practical use of realities. We've missed our chance now, but the next time we or those after us take the sword for Italy, it will be in answer to a call from Piedmont. I know that Piedmont is going to be a free kingdom, and if I'm here when the call comes, I shall fight for Italy and Victor Emmanuel.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">The bombardment suddenly increases in intensity. The two Young Men, with three <pb n="34">or four others, come in and take their places at the window. They are followed by Bassi, Beppo, Zucchi, the Doctor, and the Aide all wearing their new red shirts</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>I like your shirts better than I like your politics, Joseph.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I have no politics. But I can read plain writing when I see it, and that's what is written on the future of Italy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>I don't agree. And Piedmont would mean Cavour. That man is dangerous. He can think of Piedmont and nothing else.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's good. Let him make Piedmont free, and then we shall have our example. Because Cavour won't lose himself in your dreams, you call him dangerous. But he's the one practical statesman in Italy to&hyphen;day. Let him build your dreams into reality for you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's not my way.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>No&mdash;your way is to bring us here to Rome before our time, without moorings, without Italy prepared. And what is the result? We are not Italy risen, but a little corner of revolt in an Italy still enslaved. I don't want to use hard words, Joseph, but that's the truth. Your dream is a noble one, but it has lost touch with reality&mdash;the reality of those French guns, of our dead on <pb n="35">the Corsini, of our flight now and again into the wilderness. Once more I ask you&mdash;there may be time yet&mdash;will you let me take the army out of Rome now, to&hyphen;night, if I can? I can do nothing now for your Roman Republic, but I may be able to save the army.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>When the last assault is made on the Roman walls, the army must be there to meet it. You will stay by your command. That is the order of the Assembly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Then I resign my command.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">There is a movement of protest from them all</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>What are you talking about, man? You are under orders.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'm under no orders. I'm a volunteer and a free man.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph Garibaldi, you are a pig&hyphen;head.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>A pig&hyphen;head! Me! I like that&mdash;a pig&hyphen;head. <stage>(<hi r="italic">In almost childish temper</hi>)</stage> If you want to know, that's what I called you, and I said it first. You can ask Beppo and Zucchi&mdash;didn't I?</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Another furious burst of firing. In the midst of it Anita comes in. She is twenty&hyphen;eight years old, of smallish stature, but with a brilliant Amazonian beauty. She throws herself into Garibaldi's arms</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Anita, my darling&mdash;we thought you <pb n="36">were at Nice&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">To Beppo and the others</hi>)</stage> I told you she would come&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>I could stay away no longer&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>But how did you get here&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>You know&mdash;just came&mdash;used my wits&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph Mazzini there says I'm a pig&hyphen;head.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh, but he's quite right, Peppino. Don't I know it. But what's the matter?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Your husband, madam, doesn't agree with me as to what is to be done when the Frenchmen break through the walls. And so he proposes to resign.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Resign, Peppino? Of course you can't resign.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I have resigned.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Italy can't afford to have your honour questioned. And, whatever the motive, it would be. You can't do this thing.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>But I know Mazzini is wrong.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's as may be&mdash;you can't do it. It would be said that you deserted&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>No one would dare to say that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>It would be said.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>And whose fault would it be?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Mine, if you like. But it must never be said.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="37">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Then listen to reason. I know that my way is the right way.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>I know it is the wrong way. As Triumvir of Rome I tell you that your duty is plain.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>It is. My duty is to save every life I can for the day that I know is not yet. You deny that duty&mdash;well, do as you please&mdash;but I'll have none of it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph, in the name of God&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I want no name of God&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Zucchi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Master of your red&hyphen;shirts, you can't&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">sharply</hi>).</stage> <p>Don't tell me what I can or can't&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Struck by a shot that crashes through the shutters, Zucchi reels and falls dead at Garibaldi's feet</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Doctor</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">kneeling, with Bassi at his side</hi>).</stage> <p>That is the end for him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Zucchi&mdash;Zucchi&mdash;I didn't mean that&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>He believed in you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very well. Have it your own way. Let luck do as it will. We'll stand at the walls. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Offering his hand, which Mazzini takes</hi>.)</stage> No grudges, Joseph. Time is wiser than we are.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The bombardment bursts out in fury</hi>.</stage>
<pb n="38">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">One of the Men at the window</hi>.</speaker> <p>The Bersaglieri are retreating&mdash;they're at the gate.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Another</hi>.</speaker> <p>The French are coming down the hill.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">at the window</hi>).</stage> <p>It is the last assault. Now is the time for the story to be made.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Go, Peppino.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">kissing her, and drawing his sword</hi>).</stage> <p>Viva l'Italia! <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He rushes out</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi, Beppo, Doctor, and the Young Red&hyphen;shirts</hi>.</speaker> <p>Viva l'Italia! <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">They follow him</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">at the window</hi>).</stage> <p>Viva l'Italia! Garibaldi! Garibaldi!</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">flinging open the shutters and standing up on the sill of the window</hi>).</stage> <p>Viva l'Italia! Garibaldi! Garibaldi!</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">To a crescendo of conflict outside</hi></stage>
<trailer><hi r="smcap">the scene closes</hi></trailer>
</div3>
<pb n="39">
<div3>
<comhd3><idref>Z300767842</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
SCENE III <attbytes>14Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767842</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Garibaldi: A Chronicle Play of Italian Freedom in Ten Scenes</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1936</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The same room, after nightfall on the following day</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">An outer wall and part of the roof have been blown away. From the gap could be seen the Trastevere Quarter, lying towards the centre of Rome. A glow from the city lights feebly illuminates the ruins of the Sparda Villa. The firing has ceased. The subdued murmur of a crowd comes up from below. The silence is broken otherwise only by the sound of a distant trumpet</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Several figures of fallen red&hyphen;shirts, slain in the last defence of the villa, lie in the dim light. By the shattered window Anita is sitting with a rifle across her knees. After a few moments Ugo Bassi comes in and stands by her side. Part of his shirt is torn away, showing a rough bandage</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">quietly</hi>).</stage> <p>Where is Peppino?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I think he is alive. He was like a man possessed. He sang a hymn as he rode, or shouted it. He must have ridden into the arms of death a dozen times, but death wouldn't take him. Death hasn't been generous to some of us.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="40">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Are you badly hurt?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not badly enough. Nothing would give me greater joy than to die for Garibaldi.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">touching his hand, very gently</hi>).</stage> <p>Ugo, my dear.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Mazzini comes in. He is grey with anguish</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Is Joseph here?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not yet.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not yet.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">He walks two or three times to and fro across the room, in cold, half&hyphen;abstracted control of his feelings. He is brought up by the figure of Garibaldi in the doorway. Anita runs to her husband. He is stained with blood and mud and smoke, and his sword is broken in his hand</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>So. You surrendered after all.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>I didn't surrender. The Assembly did. I resigned.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">smiling</hi>).</stage> <p>You too. But you were right. What is it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">reading a paper from his pocket</hi>).</stage> <p>This resolution was passed: &ldquo;In the name of God and the People. The Constituent Assembly of Rome ceases from a defence that has become impossible, and remains at its post.&rdquo;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>In the name of God and the People. And the terms?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="41">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>The French are to occupy Rome in forty&hyphen;eight hours. The Republican Government will then be disbanded.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>And the army?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Anyone who chooses can leave Rome before the occupation is made. They don't fear the army any more.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I shall go. How many do you reckon our men to be?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Fifteen thousand. Less.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>A few may come with me. My own Legion, the Lombard Bersaglieri perhaps, some who think that I may bring them luck yet. Well&mdash;who knows?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>What shall you do?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Watch for chances. They no longer fear us, you say. Maybe we can worry them a little longer. They may be sorry yet they thought us not worth stopping.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>They must be too much for you in the end.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I know. But in the meantime we can make them pay a little more, out in the open and among the hills. I learnt something about that in Brazil. And then, if we're spared, we'll slip away into exile again, and wait for the next call.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph, I should like to go with you. I <pb n="42">need such danger now for the peace of my soul. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Wryly</hi>)</stage> Othello's occupation's gone. But, my friend, it's better we should part. Italy, I think, is using us to the same end, but we weren't made to work together. If I came, I should only be a hindrance. So I'll slip away again into exile too. I shall keep my dream&mdash;it's all I have left now. And some day we may meet again.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I suppose you're right. We cramp each other. But if we don't even agree how Italy should be loved, we both love her. That is enough. When Italy is her own, may we both be with her and our differences forgotten.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Mazzini</hi>.</speaker> <p>Good&hyphen;bye, Joseph.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking his hand</hi>).</stage> <p>Good&hyphen;bye, Joseph.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Mazzini goes out</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">looking after him</hi>).</stage> <p>Poor saint.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>And now, Ugo, will you tell them down there that I wish to speak to them. It is the last time. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Bassi goes</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>God is good.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Good? Doubtless. But it's not so easy to believe just now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>He has not taken you from me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking her in his arms</hi>).</stage> <p>Dear one&mdash;my dear, dear wife. And so soon to part again.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Part? What do you mean, Peppino?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="43">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well&mdash;I can't take you with me on this fool's errand.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Haven't I been with you on fools' errands before? Why do you suppose I came here? Do you think I didn't know Rome would fall? I came to be with you when it fell, and to follow wherever you should go.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Dear, you can't. This means hardship, beyond endurance perhaps. When it is known we are out there in arms, we shall be hunted like wolves.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The sound of the crowd is coming nearer</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>What endurance have I not shared with you before?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>There were no children then. And now&mdash;Anita, beloved, you must be at Nice&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anito</hi>.</speaker> <p>No&mdash;no&mdash;no. I have considered everything. Whatever happens, my children will never think the less of me for this. Where you go now, I go.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Then I must go to Nice too.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>No. You know you don't mean that. You are going out there, with them, and I am going with you. Now speak to them.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">The crowd is now below outside the villa. Garibaldi takes Anita again in his arms, and moves up on to the breach in the <pb n="44">wall. A roar of cheering greets him. He checks it</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Friends, Rome has fallen. <stage>(<hi r="italic">There is a deathly silence</hi>.)</stage> But fortune, who betrays us to&hyphen;day, will reward us on some to&hyphen;morrow. There is here no more to be done. I am going out from Rome. Let those who wish to defy the stranger still, come with me. I offer neither pay, nor quarters, nor provisions. I offer hunger, thirst, vigil, forced marches, battles and death, but never terms with the enemy. Let him who loves his country without fear, follow me. To&hyphen;morrow at noon I shall be at the Lateran, ready to meet those of you that have a heart for this forlorn service. And now, to the rest of you, farewell. Viva l'Italia!</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">The cry is taken up by the crowd, as it moves away</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Bassi comes in, carrying a loaf, a bottle of wine, some glasses, and a lighted candle, which he places on the table</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Beppo is coming up. He has made arrangements for Anita.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>What arrangements for Anita?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>An escort to Nice.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>She refuses to go. She is coming with me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="45">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">coming in</hi>).</stage> <p>Anita, you should start to&hyphen;night. It will be safer.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>You're a dear, Beppo. But I too shall be at the Lateran to&hyphen;morrow.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>You ought not&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>It is settled. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Dividing the bread</hi>.)</stage> Pour the wine out, Peppino.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">doing so</hi>).</stage> <p>Ugo Bassi&mdash;may we meet again. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Drinking</hi>.)</stage> Beppo.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>You know better than that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bassi</hi>.</speaker> <p>What place is there for me anywhere now, but with you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, Beppo, I know better than that. To&hyphen;morrow, then.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">as they eat and drink</hi>).</stage> <p>Do you remember, Peppino, the night when we went out from Rio Grande?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes&mdash;that was one of my best&mdash;</p>
<stanza><l>When we went out from Rio Grande</l>
<l>I took my fair one by the hand,</l>
<l>I bade her bid the moon at sea</l>
<l>Speak to the moon of Italy:</l></stanza>
<stanza><l>I bade her tell that we should wait</l>
<l>The day come soon, the day come late,</l>
<l>When moon and stars and sun should rise</l>
<l>Rejoicing on Italian skies.</l></stanza>
<pb n="46">
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The distant trumpet is heard again. He goes to the breach, and looks out over the city</hi>.</stage>
<p>There's death in Rome to&hyphen;night. Below&mdash;my friends, in the name of our dead&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">quietly</hi>)</stage> Viva l'Italia! <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He drinks</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The Others</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">drinking</hi>).</stage> <p>Viva l'Italia!</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The trumpet sounds yet again as</hi></stage>
<trailer><hi r="smcap">the scene closes</hi></trailer>
</div3>
<pb n="47">
<div3>
<comhd3><idref>Z300767843</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
SCENE IV <attbytes>25Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767843</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Garibaldi: A Chronicle Play of Italian Freedom in Ten Scenes</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1936</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Six weeks later. In the Ravenna Marshes</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The public room of a small Italian Inn. It is evening and the room is lit only by an oil lamp which stands on a table. There are benches and a sofa</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">On the wall, side by side, are three copies of a printed proclamation, at the head of which the name of Garibaldi appears in large type</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Two white&hyphen;coated Austrian Soldiers are seated at the table, drinking wine and smoking. A third stands reading the proclamation</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Third Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ten thousand crowns. That's a good fat sum. Set a poor fellow like me up for life.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Soldier</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">a Sergeant</hi>).</stage> <p>You won't catch him, son. The Frenchmen have been at his heels for six weeks. You might as well try to catch the swallow that comes in the spring, tra&hyphen;la&hyphen;la.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Third Soldier</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">joining the others</hi>).</stage> <p>Well, you never know your luck.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>If you ask me, I'ld as soon <pb n="48">have nothing to do with him. They say he's a devil.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Sergeant</hi>.</speaker> <p>He must be crazy though, going off from Rome like that with a bit of an army that had no more than it stood up in. They've got cleaned up all right.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>Even at that, he was never beaten. His lot just faded out&mdash;melted&mdash;that's all.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Sergeant</hi>.</speaker> <p>They say he hasn't above a score with him now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Third Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>If as many. More likely he's alone. I shouldn't mind having a go at him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>Should you know him if you saw him?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Third Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>Maybe. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Knowing</hi>)</stage> If you see a fellow wandering about, in a red shirt and a beard, that's him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Sergeant</hi>.</speaker> <p>You ought to be in the intelligence corps. Well, come on, lads. Five miles to go to&hyphen;night. Where's that girl? What'd she say her name was?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Soldier</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">calling from the inner door</hi>).</stage> <p>Teresa!</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Teresa comes in, twenty, very pretty</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Sergeant</hi>.</speaker> <p>How much?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Twelve lira.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Sergeant</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's a lot. We needn't pay at all, you know.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="49">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>No.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Sergeant</hi>.</speaker> <p>But twelve lira. What about something extra for that&mdash;just a kiss, eh?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Thank you&mdash;I'd rather not.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Sergeant</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking her by the wrist</hi>).</stage> <p>Ho! It's like that, is it? Proud, aren't we? <stage>(<hi r="italic">He kisses her and throws the money on the table</hi>.)</stage> Italian misses shouldn't put on airs&mdash;not with Austrian gentlemen. <stage>(<hi r="italic">As they gather their kit together</hi>)</stage> It'll do you no harm to remember that. And if more of my men come in, you can tell 'em we've gone on.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">The three soldiers go out. Teresa, genuinely displeased, takes up the money and clears the things from the table</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">as she is going out&mdash;calling</hi>).</stage> <p>Ferdinando, put some more oil in the lamp. I've told you twice already.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">A boy comes in with an oil&hyphen;can. He is refilling the lamp on the table as Teresa returns</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Here&mdash;let me do it, clumsy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Boy</hi>.</speaker> <p>All right&mdash;you needn't be so snappy about it. Kissed you, didn't he? I saw.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Get along with you&mdash;fetch that corn in, and be quick about it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Boy</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">going</hi>).</stage> <p>I suppose you wouldn't let me kiss you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="50">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Be off. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<stage>[<hi r="italic">As Teresa is turning up the wick of the re&hyphen;lighted lamp, the outer door opens and Garibaldi appears, supporting Anita. They are wearing peasant dress. Anita, desperately ill, is at the point of prostration; her husband is far worn with fatigue and anxiety</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">unkempt and muffled</hi>).</stage> <p>Can we stay here to&hyphen;night?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>We've no accommodation of that kind.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">helping Anita to the sofa, where she sinks exhausted</hi>).</stage> <p>There. <stage>(<hi r="italic">To Teresa, apprehensively</hi>)</stage> Shut the door. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Teresa does so</hi>.)</stage> We shall have to stay in here then. This woman is ill. Some cognac, please.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Teresa fetches it, while Garibaldi arranges a cushion for Anita, and stands with his hand on her forehead. He places the brandy to her lips</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Looks like fever.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ssh! Is there a doctor anywhere hereabouts?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>No. My mother knows about these things, but she's away.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">hardly audible</hi>).</stage> <p>Peppino&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, darling?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="51">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>I must go to sleep.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, my dear. But you need food&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not yet&mdash;presently.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">She turns over towards the wall and he covers her with a rug from the back of the sofa which is in shadow. He kisses her and goes to the far side of the table, and sits down wearily, facing the outer door</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Some wine please&mdash;and cheese&mdash;anything you have.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">looking at him across the table</hi>).</stage> <p>Wine, did you say?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, wine. What are you staring at?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">not moving</hi>).</stage> <p>I'm sorry.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>What is it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Aren't you&mdash;Joseph Garibaldi?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>No.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes you are.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>How do you know?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>I saw you once in Rome.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Viva l'Italia! You can trust me. But you aren't safe here.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'm safe nowhere.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>The Austrians are looking for you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh yes, they're looking for me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>There were some of them here just now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="52">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I watched them go.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">pointing to the proclamation</hi>).</stage> <p>Ten thousand crowns.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I've seen it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph Garibaldi. And she?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>She is my wife.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>I wish I could help.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Bless you, child. Get that, will you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">She goes out. He rises, goes to Anita, finds that she is asleep, and returns to his seat. After a moment or two he nods forward over the table and falls asleep also, his head on his arms</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Teresa comes back, looks at him, and quietly places the wine and a plate of food in front of him. She then rearranges Anita's rug, and is crossing to go, when the outer door opens and two more White&hyphen;coats come in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>Seen any of our men here?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes&mdash;they left word&mdash;they've gone along the road, that way.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>How long ago?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Only a few minutes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>We'll soon catch them up, then?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh yes&mdash;they can't be far.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very well. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Moving to go</hi>.)</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>What's the hurry? We'll get there <pb n="53">as soon as they do. I'm dry. Come on. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He sits at the table facing Garibaldi</hi>.)</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's all right for me. Bring a bottle, miss. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He sits also</hi>.)</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">hesitating</hi>).</stage> <p>There's one here. He's gone to sleep. I can get him another. <stage>(<hi r="italic">She takes glasses from a shelf and fills them</hi>.)</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">the one nearer to Garibaldi</hi>).</stage> <p>Come and sit down, my dear. A pretty girl's good company on a halt.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>You're very obliging.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">She goes to the back of the table, and sits on the bench between him and Garibaldi</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>What's the matter with a soldier's knee? Better than hard wood.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'm quite near enough.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">putting his arm round her</hi>).</stage> <p>Can't be too near for my liking.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">As they talk and drink she watches Garibaldi steadily</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>You've got the proclamation up, I see. That's right. Always do what the Austrians tell you, and you'll come to no harm.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's it. Always do as the Austrians tell you&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">he kisses her</hi>.)</stage> and you'll come to no more harm than is good for you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>Have you ever seen this Garibaldi?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="54">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>I? No. Shouldn't be likely to in a quiet place like this.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>A quiet place is exactly what he wants just now, my dear. You never know where that fellow may be. We shall nab him though. The Italians may love him, but you won't find an Italian who wouldn't love ten thousand crowns better. Eh, my dear?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ten thousand crowns is a lot of money.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>It would buy the handsomest husband in Italy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's right. You keep your eyes open, my dear. Your friend seems to sleep well.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>That was his fourth bottle. He does that every night. We call him Tipsy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>Tipsy what?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Just Tipsy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, there's no harm in good drinking. Fill up. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He does so for both</hi>.)</stage> I tell you what it is, mate, the only thing I'll be sorry to get out of Italy for is the drink. You can't get it like that in Austria.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's true. Doesn't do you so much good at home somehow.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Garibaldi moves. Teresa's hand is instantly on his arm in warning. He sees at a glance what has happened</hi>.</stage>
<pb n="55">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>Hullo, Rip van Winkle. Awake?</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Garibaldi yawns, his hand over his face. Then he stretches his arms, turning round from the table as he does so</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Soldier</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">to Teresa</hi>).</stage> <p>Get him his bottle. We'll join you, friend. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Teresa goes</hi>.)</stage> Eat your grub.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">thickly</hi>).</stage> <p>No stomach.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He takes a cigar from his pocket, and without turning his head, takes the lamp from the table and lights up. He then places the lamp on a shelf behind him, and sits again at the table, his face now in deep shadow</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Teresa returns with a bottle and fills the three glasses</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>Your fourth bottle, eh?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>I was telling them about you, and how we all call you Tipsy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking her at once. Drinking and refilling his glass</hi>).</stage> <p>Tha' so. Can't keep off it. Spen' all got on it. Here's health gel'men. Sh' like much more money buy more wine.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>You should catch Garibaldi, and then you'ld have plenty.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Gabbleald&mdash;whasat? I've never caught gabblealdi. I've caught the itch&mdash;the i&hyphen;itch, and I've caught dipseria, but I've never caught <pb n="56">gabblealdi. Don&hyphen;know 'bout it. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Drinking</hi>.)</stage> Hope you'll never have any these things, gel'men.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Emptying his glass, he falls forward again as if asleep</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Soldier</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's the sort of man Italy wants to make her free as they talk so much about. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Collecting his kit. To Teresa</hi>)</stage> Keep your eyes open. Garibaldi may be caught yet. They've caught one of 'em&mdash;that priest, Ugo Bassi. They've shot him all right. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Garibaldi suppresses a movement</hi>.)</stage> Serve him right. What's a priest want to meddle with fighting for? <stage>(<hi r="italic">Rising</hi>)</stage> Come on.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Putting a coin on the table</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Soldier</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">following</hi>).</stage> <p>So long, my dear. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He kisses Teresa again</hi>.)</stage> Wish I could stay the night with you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">The two men go out, singing down the road. As soon as the door is closed, Garibaldi rises and crosses to listen as they go</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>They've shot Ugo Bassi.</p>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">He stands by Anita, who lies still asleep, as, unseen by the soldiers, she has been. He kneels at her side</hi>.</stage>
<p><stage>(<hi r="italic">Very quietly</hi>)</stage> Ugo Bassi. My dear, they've shot Ugo Bassi. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He rises, and speaks to Teresa</hi>.)</stage> What's your name?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Teresa.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="57">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Teresa what?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>Teresa Baldini.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I owe you my life. It may not be worth much. But you could have sold it for ten thousand crowns. Thank you, Teresa Baldini. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Taking a little gold chain from his pocket</hi>.)</stage> Will you keep this for me?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">accepting it</hi>).</stage> <p>Yes. Thank you. I will keep it always.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">by Anita</hi>).</stage> <p>She sleeps so quietly. Perhaps it is all she needs?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresa</hi>.</speaker> <p>God grant it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">She takes the things from the table, while Garibaldi moves a chair to the sofa and sits watching beside his wife. Teresa goes out</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">turning in her sleep</hi>).</stage> <p>Peppino&mdash;Peppino&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, darling&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Don't go away from me, Peppino.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I am here.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">suddenly rising and clinging to him</hi>).</stage> <p>I am afraid&mdash;don't leave me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking her in his arms</hi>).</stage> <p>There&mdash;there&mdash;of course I shan't leave you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>I can't go any farther. It's too hard. I think&mdash;I am dying.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="58">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>No, my darling&mdash;you mustn't think that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'm sorry&mdash;so very sorry&mdash;to fail you like this. I love you so much.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I know&mdash;I know. Courage. It is nothing. You are tired.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>So tired. My head burns. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Placing her hand over her heart</hi>.)</stage> And here&mdash;here. I shouldn't have come. I&mdash;I&mdash;it was foolish of me. Why haven't&mdash;where's your red shirt, Peppino?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>We had to&mdash;you know&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Beaten&mdash;were we beaten? But you mustn't be beaten&mdash;you must go on.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes. We must go on. Beppo is arranging to get us down to the coast.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi>.</speaker> <p>No&mdash;I can't. Without me. When we&mdash;went out&mdash;from Rio Grande&mdash;darling&mdash;darling&mdash;bless you always. ... I was strong for a long time, wasn't I?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Always.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Anita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">very faintly</hi>).</stage> <p>Viva&mdash;viva l'Italia!</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">She falls back dead in his arms</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Anita&mdash;Anita&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Beppo comes in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>I've managed it. At daybreak&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising</hi>).</stage> <p>She is dead.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>She?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="59">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ugo Bassi is dead too. They shot him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>So.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I shall come with you, Beppo. They shall be redeemed yet. At daybreak&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c">[<hi r="italic">He throws himself passionately across Anita's body, and sobs without constraint as</hi></stage>
<trailer><hi r="smcap">the scene closes</hi></trailer>
</div3>
<pb n="60">
<div3>
<comhd3><idref>Z300767844</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
SCENE V <attbytes>13Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767844</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Garibaldi: A Chronicle Play of Italian Freedom in Ten Scenes</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1936</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l">1854.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The workshop of a small Candle&hyphen;factory in New York. A number of work&hyphen;men of various nationalities are employed, at small vats, a growing heap of candles beside each. One of them is Garibaldi. They work in silence. After a few moments a young Italian comes to the door</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Young Man</hi>.</speaker> <p>Is Joseph Garibaldi here?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>What is it, Antonio?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Antonio</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">going up to him</hi>).</stage> <p>You're wanted down at the club. It's someone just off the boat.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Now?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Antonio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>All right. I'll come.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Antonio</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'll tell them. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking off his workman's blouse and putting on a coat</hi>).</stage> <p>If the boss asks, say I'll be back soon. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He follows</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">A Young New Yorker</hi>.</speaker> <p>He's getting mighty mysterious.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">An Older Man</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">a big Scandinavian</hi>).</stage> <p>Always has been, ever since I know him&mdash;best part of two years.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="61">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">An Unkempt Little Pole</hi>.</speaker> <p>Zay say he was a beeg man in 'is Italy, five or seex years ago.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Another New Yorker</hi>.</speaker> <p>No bigger than you or me. He got kicked out of his country&mdash;that's all that happened to him, same as a good many more in this fit&hyphen;out. America for the Americans&mdash;that's the stuff we want, I say.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Pole</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ve shall all be Americans, von't ve?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">New Yorker</hi>.</speaker> <p>No son&mdash;you can't be an American.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Pole</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh yes&mdash;I 'ave my papers very soon.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Another Worker</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">a rather decrepit but well&hyphen;bred Englishman</hi>).</stage> <p>That Garibaldi's a fine fellow though. Laski's right&mdash;there's something big about him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">New Yorker</hi>.</speaker> <p>You don't say. You make me tired. What did you get pushed out of England for anyway?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Englishman</hi>.</speaker> <p>I quarrelled with my bank.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Scandinavian</hi>.</speaker> <p>There now, my friends&mdash;let us be agreeable with each other, is it not so? We sing together&mdash;yes?</p>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">He gives the lead, and they sing while they work</hi>.</stage>
<stanza><l>When I was a bach'lor, I lived by myself,</l>
<l>I worked at the weaver's trade;</l>
<l>The only, only thing I did that was wrong</l>
<l>Was to woo a fair young maid.</l>
<pb n="62">
<l>I wooed her in the winter&hyphen;time,</l>
<l>And in the summer, too;</l>
<l>And the only, only thing I did that was wrong,</l>
<l>Was to keep her from the foggy, foggy dew.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l>O, I am a bach'lor, I live with my son;</l>
<l>We work at the weaver's trade;</l>
<l>And ev'ry single time I look into his eyes</l>
<l>He reminds me of the fair young maid.</l>
<l>He reminds me of the winter&hyphen;time,</l>
<l>And of the summer too;</l>
<l>And the many, many times that I held her in my arms,</l>
<l>Just to keep her from the foggy, foggy dew.</l></stanza></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">They are beginning to repeat the song as the Proprietor of the factory, an eager, fat little Jew, comes in. They stop at once. He carries a note&hyphen;book in which he makes entries as he checks the count of candles from vat to vat. He comes to Garibaldi's place</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>Where is Garibaldi?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">New Yorker</hi>.</speaker> <p>He's gone out.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>Gone out? He's always going out. Where's he gone?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First New Yorker</hi>.</speaker> <p>Someone from the Italian club came for him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="63">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Scandinavian</hi>.</speaker> <p>It's only next door.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Pole</hi>.</speaker> <p>'E said 'e vould be back very soon.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh, did he? I don't know what's coming to that man. He's the best hand I've got&mdash;he does as much as any two of you ginks, and something's come over him lately. Well, I'll teach him this is a workshop, not a peach&hyphen;orchard.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Garibaldi returns</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>Here, what's the matter with you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">changing his coat, and resuming his work</hi>).</stage> <p>I'm sorry, boss. It was very important.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>What do you think I pay you seven dollars a week for?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Don't I earn it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>I don't say as you don't. Cut that out. I've been very considerate to you, Garibaldi. You came here five years ago and I gave you a good job, and then you sloped off after six months without giving me warning. Then you came back two years ago, and I took you on again, and ever since you've been as restless as a wild cat. How do you think I can carry on if I have people about like that?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I shan't trouble you any longer.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>What's that? What d'you mean?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I've got to go.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>Go? When do you mean, go?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="64">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>To&hyphen;day.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>You can't do that. It ain't reasonable.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I must. I've just had word. I've waited for it every day for two years. I knew it would come. Things are beginning to move in Piedmont.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>What the hell's Piedmont? You've got to stay here and work your time out&mdash;get that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Sorry, boss, but I'll have to go. You've been good enough to me, but I knew this was coming.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>Then why didn't you say so? I tell you you can't go now&mdash;it's the busy season coming on in the candle trade.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I know. But it's the busy season coming on in another trade&mdash;one I was bred up to.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'll tell you what I'll do. I'll be handsome about this. I'll raise yer. I'll make it eight dollars a week&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">to the others generally</hi>)</stage> and I don't care who knows it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>It's not your dollars, boss.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>You've been glad enough of 'em, haven't you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh yes, I've been glad of them. But there's enough waiting for me when I get back. I've only been marking time over here, boss&mdash;there, don't be hot about it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="65">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>Hot! Who wouldn't be hot? Do you refuse my offer?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'm afraid so.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>Then get out! Go on&mdash;you double&hyphen;crosser. I'll know how to be good&hyphen;natured another time. 'Ere&mdash;it's Thursday, to&hyphen;day don't count&mdash;it ain't half gone yet&mdash;there's three dollars and fifty cents&mdash;and go where you're wanted.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking up the money from a bench</hi>).</stage> <p>Yes, boss, that's where I'll go.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, you ain't wanted here.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Sorry you're like that about it. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Changing his coat</hi>.)</stage> If ever you come to Italy, let me know. Good&hyphen;bye, friends.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes out as they return the civility</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">collecting a handful of candles from Garibaldi's vat</hi>).</stage> <p>And take your lousy candles with you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">He throws them down the stairs after him, and then takes a large card from under a bench. It bears the words</hi>: &ldquo;Wanted full&hyphen;time Candle Jobber. Apply within.&rdquo;</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Pole</hi>.</speaker> <p>Shall I steek that up, boss?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Proprietor</hi>.</speaker> <p>No, you won't. I'll stick it up myself. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Goes out</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Englishman</hi>.</speaker> <p>Fancy that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">New Yorker</hi>.</speaker> <p>Thinks he's somebody, I'll say.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="66">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Scandinavian</hi>.</speaker> <p>It's a pity he's gone.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Pole</hi>.</speaker> <p>He vould never 'ave made a good American.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">New Yorker</hi>.</speaker> <p>Let's forget it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><lyric><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Scandinavian</hi>.</speaker> <p>You sing that better this time&mdash;</p>
<stanza><l>When I was a bach'lor, I lived by myself,</l>
<l>I worked at&mdash;</l></stanza></speech></lyric></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">As they are singing at their work</hi></stage>
<trailer><hi r="smcap">the scene closes</hi></trailer>
</div3>
<div3>
<pb n="67">
<comhd3><idref>Z300767845</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
SCENE VI <attbytes>35Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767845</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Garibaldi: A Chronicle Play of Italian Freedom in Ten Scenes</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1936</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">March</hi> 1859.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Garibaldi's house on the island of Caprera, off the northern coast of Sardinia. A veranda overlooking the sea</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Out of the house, from the noon meal, come: Beppo; Menotti Garibaldi, Joseph's son, a maturely upstanding young man of nineteen; Teresita, his sister, and very worthily Anita's daughter, two years younger; Nino Bixio, one of the young veterans of the siege of Rome, full of dynamic energy and authority; and Mr Renshaw, an English visitor, a young Liberal of the Gladstonian school</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">They take chairs, and Papaleo, a Calabrian servant, brings them coffee and cigars. He also places a carafe of wine and glasses on the table</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi>.</speaker> <p>You mustn't mind my father, Mr Renshaw. He's often like that. Suddenly, when he's occupied with quite other things, he will remember those bad days in Rome ten years ago, and all the dreary waiting since, and then he just goes away from everyone like that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="68">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>I quite understand. I sympathise, I can assure you. There's been a very strong sentiment in England for your cause&mdash;ever since Mr Gladstone published his letters about the Neapolitan prisoners.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Nino Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Mr Gladstone didn't see the worst. I have a friend, as pure and high&hyphen;minded a patriot as ever breathed. For nine years he has been chained, day and night, to a common felon, in a dungeon that reeks and crawls with filth. And he's one of hundreds. You can't describe these things, Mr Renshaw; you can hardly imagine them. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Excitedly</hi>)</stage> But the day will come yet.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>Of course, I can't speak for Her Majesty's Government. But I know Lord John Russell&mdash;he's a kinsman of mine in fact&mdash;and it's my opinion that if he's still Foreign Secretary when the time comes for which you're waiting, you can count on our help.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Papa has promised to take me to England one day. It must be very nice there.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>I shall be enchanted to show you the sights, Miss Teresita.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi>.</speaker> <p>How funny that sounds. I've never been called Miss Teresita before.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>If I may be allowed the privilege then&mdash;Teresita.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="69">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">looking through a spy&hyphen;glass</hi>).</stage> <p>I wish I could make out what that yacht's up to. She's been lying there over an hour now. It can't be for nothing.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'm afraid we haven't very much to show you on this island, Mr Renshaw. It's only a sort of farmyard, and not much of a one at that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>I came because I wanted to see your father&mdash;the great General Garibaldi.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not so great yet as he will be.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>By the way, General is the right&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes. When the Roman Republic broke up ten years ago, the last act of its Assembly was to confer that rank on him. We regard the decree as binding still.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>How long have you been here in Caprera?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Three years.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>He was in America before that, wasn't he?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes. That was five years ago.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>What made him come back?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">pointing</hi>).</stage> <p>If you could see far enough up there, you'd see Piedmont. That was what made him come back.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>It was before the time, though.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="70">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi>.</speaker> <p>But you see it was all right. Papa got some money when Uncle Felice died, and so we were able to build this house. Don't you think it's a nice house?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>Charming.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi>.</speaker> <p>You come and dig on these rocks for a month or two and see how charming it is.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>You seem to have made a very good job of it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Don't take any notice of Menotti, Mr Renshaw. He loves it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>An excellent cigar this.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Garibaldi comes out of the house. He is in the full vigour of his fifty&hyphen;two years, but an air of deep abstraction clouds at frequent intervals his natural high spirits. As he appears, they all make to rise</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking a chair</hi>).</stage> <p>Please, don't move. You must forgive me, Mr Renshaw; I fear I do less than I should to keep my moods in order.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>Please, General&mdash;not a word. I was congratulating myself on my cigar.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking one</hi>).</stage> <p>The cigars are all right. But one of your countrymen, Mr Renshaw, is a neighbour of mine here. And a very troublesome neighbour too.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>Indeed?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="71">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Menotti, will you please convey my compliments to Mr Collins, and inform him that his pigs are at my potatoes again?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising</hi>).</stage> <p>Yes, papa.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>You needn't go now. Send Papaleo. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Calling</hi>)</stage> Papaleo!</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Papaleo</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">coming from house</hi>).</stage> <p>Yes, General?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Go down and ask Mr Collins to take his pigs away from my potatoes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Papaleo</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">going</hi>).</stage> <p>Yes, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>And you can tell him that if he wants his goats, he'll find them among my cabbages.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Papaleo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, sir. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Mr Renshaw was saying that the English Government is well disposed to us.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>The English Government isn't always right, but it's more often right than wrong.</p>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">There is a silence, during which he takes up the spy&hyphen;glass and looks out to sea</hi>.</stage>
<p>Menotti, have you looked at that yacht carefully?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, papa.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">handing him the glass</hi>).</stage> <p>Well, look now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">doing so</hi>).</stage> <p>What's that&mdash;they're running a flag up&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Give it me. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Taking the glass again. After a moment</hi>.)</stage> They are. It's the flag of Piedmont.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Beppo, Bixio, Menotti and Teresita rise</hi>.</stage>
<pb n="72">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>Piedmont?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Beppo&mdash;Bixio&mdash;do you know what this means? Cavour is on that yacht.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo and Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Cavour?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Cavour! At last. I knew it would come. Viva l'Italia!</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">All</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">except Renshaw</hi>).</stage> <p>Viva l'Italia!</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">suddenly letting himself go</hi>).</stage> <p>Viva l'Italia! By God, sir, I don't know what it's all about, but Viva l'Italia!</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Look&mdash;they're putting a boat off.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Go and meet it&mdash;all of you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Beppo, Bixio and Menotti hurry off. Garibaldi and Renshaw sit</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>Do you really mean that Count Cavour is coming here?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Cavour&mdash;to tell me that the dream of twenty&hyphen;five years is coming true.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Does it mean more fighting, Papa?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking her on his knee</hi>).</stage> <p>Yes, my child. The last fight of all. When your mother died, ten years ago, she told me that I must go on, and on&mdash;till Italy was free. You are the dearest thing of your mother that I have left, my little Teresita. You will see it with me in her blessed name.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi>.</speaker> <p>I understand. But I am frightened.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Your mother was never frightened&mdash;<pb n="73">or but once only. At that inn, with the girl&mdash;she was called Teresa too. There, there; courage, my dear. Forgive us, Mr Renshaw.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not at all&mdash;not at all.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">controlling herself</hi>).</stage> <p>Mr Renshaw says that when you take me to England he'll show me all the fine things there. Can I see Queen Victoria, Mr Renshaw?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>I think it could be arranged.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Papaleo comes back</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Papaleo</hi>.</speaker> <p>I met Mr Collins down at the gate, sir. He says he's very sorry, but if you won't keep your fences repaired he can't help his goats and pigs&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Tell Mr Collins his goats and pigs can do as they damn well please&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Papaleo</hi>.</speaker> <p>I beg your pardon, sir?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Tell him my cabbages and potatoes are at his service. I shan't be wanting them at present.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Papaleo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not wanting them, sir?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>And get my sword out, Papaleo, and the musket, and the red shirt. Everything.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Papaleo</hi>.</speaker> <p>They're all ready, sir. I always keep them ready.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">kissing Teresita and rising, eager for <pb n="74">action</hi>).</stage> <p>Tell Mr Collins the island's his till Garibaldi comes again.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Papaleo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, sir. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>If your Government wants to help us, Mr Renshaw, it may soon have the chance. There is going to be no mistake this time.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>You seem very confident.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Because I know Cavour. Three years ago, after I came back from New York, he sent for me. It was as I had always told Joseph Mazzini. Piedmont under this man was becoming a free kingdom. There, in the name of Victor Emmanuel, the new Italy was being conceived, liberated, one from coast to coast. It was precisely as I had foreseen. Cavour told me to go on waiting patiently, as I had waited at Rio, in Rome, tramping the seas, making tallow candles in New York. I knew then that he was right. Not like Mazzini.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>Mazzini is very highly thought of in England.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>He is very highly thought of by me. The trouble with Mazzini is that he's always known the right thing to do, and never the right time to do it. That's why Cavour will have nothing to do with him. When Cavour said wait, I knew he said it with a purpose. I have waited here for three years, scraping bread out of the rocks, <pb n="75">wrangling about pigs and goats, ready for Piedmont when I was wanted. Now the flag of Piedmont is out there, and I know that the time has come.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>It's a great privilege to be here, General&mdash;on such a day especially. I feel that I ought now to take my leave&mdash;but I fear that Captain Hogarth won't be here to take me off till the morning&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>You're very welcome, sir. Teresita, my dear, show Mr Renshaw something of our island. A little obligation against the treat in London.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, papa. Look, the boat is running in.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Don't be away long, Mr Renshaw. You will like to be presented to Count Cavour.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, indeed, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes, ushered out by Teresita</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Garibaldi stands for a moment lost in the silence of his thought. Then he lights another cigar, and looks down to the shore path</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>This way, Menotti. Bring the Count this way.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Menotti and the others come up in front of the veranda, escorting Camillo Cavour. He is just under fifty years of age, square&hyphen;cut in build and features, wearing heavy spectacles, rather stiff and slow in his <pb n="76">carriage; an aristocrat with none of the external gloss of aristocracy. The contact between him and Garibaldi is primarily one of equal merit, but there is always a subconscious strain of deference given and taken between the son of the people and the patrician. There is no trace of servility on the one hand or of condescension on the other. The ideal of Mazzini, gone beyond the dreamer's control, is approaching reality in the ordained conjunction of the practical statesman and the perfect man of action</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>We salute your flag, sir. It is pleasanter here than inside the house. A cigar?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking one</hi>).</stage> <p>Thank you. Very attractive quarters.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>We have done what we could to make them so. Will you take some coffee?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>That is a particular weakness of mine. Though I can't teach my people in Turin to make it. In Leri, now, we know the secret.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Menotti, ask them to send out some coffee. I think we can do as well as Leri. Beppo&mdash;Nino&mdash;see that Menotti does not disgrace us.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Beppo, Bixio, and Menotti go out</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>A fine boy, that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="77">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>He had a fine mother.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>You were expecting me?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Every day for three years.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Why didn't you send for me?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Because I wanted no gossip. I told them in Turin that I was tired, and needed a cruise. You are very secluded here.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Secluded, but not inaccessible.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>No. It was a very shrewd choice. You have an Englishman with you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>A friend of authority, I understand.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>His letter was from Mr Gladstone.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes. That too will be useful. You know the situation in Piedmont?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Generally. Not in detail.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ah&mdash;in statesmanship the detail is everything. That is what your friend Mazzini has not understood.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I have never quite understood what Mazzini understood.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Mazzini's abstractions make it impossible to work with him. That is what keeps him out of Italy, where now something has to be done. No matter. Are you willing to listen to my advice?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Why, Count&mdash;to listen to it&mdash;yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="78">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>I think you will follow it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>It wouldn't surprise me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>No. I have made a compact with Louis Napoleon. We met at Plombi&egrave;res.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Indeed?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>I need not tell you the details&mdash;those very necessary details&mdash;now. It amounts to this. The French will support us in an attempt to overthrow Austrian influence and power in Italy. Between ourselves, France hopes in return to substitute her influence and power for Austria's. I don't think that, with Italy exalted by the spectacle of a defeated Austria, she will be able to do it. In any case I am prepared to take the risk. If my belief is justified, I shall take the Piedmontese army into the Papal States, and this time it will be a real occupation of Rome, not a republican dream.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>You wish me to join in the enterprise?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>No.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Menotti brings the coffee, serves it, and goes</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I should be willing.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>That is not my design. There is Naples to consider. Sicily is uneasy. There may be insurrection against Naples there at any moment. It is not for Piedmont to interfere in the affairs of any other Italian sovereignty. You understand?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="79">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>But if some Italian patriot should go to the assistance of the Sicilian revolution&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>You would not disapprove? Is that your meaning?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>As Prime Minister of Piedmont, I can express no opinion. The question is not within my jurisdiction.</p>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He rises and walks to and fro as he speaks</hi>.</stage> <p>But as an Italian, as a citizen of the state that I know is about to be born, I should not be surprised if one of my countrymen were to venture so much.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising also, and pacing the veranda</hi>).</stage> <p>You ask me to do this?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>I ask nothing. But if such a one were found, I might&mdash;in my private capacity, you understand&mdash;find means to facilitate his enterprise.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>How many men would it need?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>More than could be raised. Sicily has a garrison of over twenty thousand. It can be reinforced from Naples by another fifty.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Seventy thousand. No. We cannot compete with that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not in numbers.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>In short, you have come to Caprera looking for a madman.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I see. Well, Count, you've found him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="80">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>I was assured of that. Otherwise I shouldn't have come. What do you propose?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I have a fancy for round figures. Let us say a thousand. Let me raise a thousand men, and at the first sign from Sicily I will sail.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>You understand that if you fail I accept no responsibility?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Prime Ministers cannot be responsible for the actions of madmen&mdash;eh?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Precisely. If you fail others must be found who won't.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>The conditions are agreed. I shall find my men on the Genoese coast. Can you take me back with you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>To&hyphen;night.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Do you know the habits of pigs and goats, Count?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ask my tenants at Leri.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I have a neighbour whose pigs and goats&mdash;<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Teresita comes in</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi>.</speaker> <p>I beg your pardon, papa, but Menotti says has Count Cavour had dinner?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>How stupid of me&mdash;my daughter&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">kissing her hand</hi>).</stage> <p>Yes, my dear, an excellent dinner.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">shyly</hi>).</stage> <p>Then I'll tell Menotti. <stage>(<hi r="italic">As she is going</hi>.)</stage> Will the Count be staying the night?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="81">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>No, my dear. Ask the others to come here, will you. <stage>(<hi r="italic">She goes</hi>.)</stage> They'll have to know about it. Do you mind if I tell them now?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Anything you like. But remember, I'm here on a private visit only.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Quite. By the way, why are you flying the Piedmontese flag?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'm not. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Pointing out</hi>.)</stage> You see&mdash;it's down. I took the liberty of running it up for a moment to let you know I was here, that's all.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Beppo, Bixio, Menotti, Teresita, and Renshaw come in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>You met at the boat&mdash;but may I present my friends&mdash;Mr Renshaw, an Englishman who tells us that we are well liked there. Beppo Castiglioni&mdash;I have never been in action without him. Nino Bixio, one of the heroes of the Corsini. My son, Menotti. A good boy&mdash;yes. Gentlemen, this is Count Cavour.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">He hands cigars round, which they light, as Cavour sits</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">sitting beside him</hi>).</stage> <p>I believe Mr Gladstone called on you recently, on his return from Greece?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes. You breed remarkable statesmen in England, Mr Renshaw.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="82">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">sitting</hi>).</stage> <p>The Count brings me news, which I wish you to hear.</p>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Beppo and Bixio sit, Menotti standing behind his father's chair, and Teresita sitting on a stool beside him</hi>.</stage>
<p>We can rely on your discretion, Mr Renshaw?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>Entirely.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>The French defeated us at Rome. Now the French are going to support Piedmont against Austria. And Piedmont is going to do what Mazzini and the rest of us failed to do at Rome ten years ago. That is the news.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>And we are to join Piedmont?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>We have nothing to do with Piedmont. Count Cavour merely thought that the news would interest me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">wisely</hi>).</stage> <p>I see.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>The Count also tells me that insurrection is brewing in Sicily.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">excitedly</hi>).</stage> <p>Sicily?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Sicily, of course, does not concern Piedmont. It concerns us.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>A very pretty campaign. Sicily&mdash;Naples&mdash;Rome&mdash;Piedmont&mdash;that's Italy, isn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>That is going to be Italy, my friends. We are going to be busy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>When?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="83">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Now. I am going to raise a thousand volunteers. I go to&hyphen;night with Count Cavour to Genoa. The Count kindly offers me a passage on his private yacht&mdash;you understand. Nino, you will come with me. I offer you my second command&mdash;I need not ask whether you will take it. Beppo, you will go down to Sicily&mdash;learn all you can, report to me at Genoa as soon as possible. Menotti, you must find your way along the coast and into Rome. You know our friends&mdash;bring as many as you can to Genoa also. I rely on you for two hundred men. Teresita, darling, see that Papaleo has my stuff ready.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi>.</speaker> <p>He has. And what am I to do?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Look after things here while we are away. We shall return.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi>.</speaker> <p>But my mother always went with you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I lost her because I allowed it. I cannot lose you. There&mdash;there&mdash;say no more about it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising</hi>).</stage> <p>Gentlemen, may I be per mitted to give you a toast? <stage>(<hi r="italic">He fills the glasse with wine</hi>.)</stage> Garibaldi and the Thousand.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo, Bixio and Menotti</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising and drinking</hi>).</stage> <p>Garibaldi and the Thousand.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising also, with his glass</hi>).</stage> <p>As a private citizen, you understand&mdash;Garibaldi and the Thousand.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="84">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising</hi>).</stage> <p>Gentlemen, I give you Italy, in the name of Victor Emmanuel.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">They all drink</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Teresita</hi>.</speaker> <p>All the same, I think you might let me come with you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Sh&mdash;sh!</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">The sound of a peasant pipe is heard approaching, and a young herdsman comes in playing, crossing the land in front of the veranda. Seeing the company, he stops playing, touches his cap, and passes on, playing again as soon as he is out of sight</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>I should like to make a proposal, General. It may be irregular&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Everything we're doing is irregular, Mr Renshaw. What is it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Renshaw</hi>.</speaker> <p>If I might be allowed to make a small contribution to the cost of your expedition&mdash;it would afford me great satisfaction&mdash;say five hundred guineas&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Now that's uncommonly generous of you. I'll undertake to spend them well.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The pipe is still heard as</hi></stage>
<trailer><hi r="smcap">the scene closes</hi></trailer>
</div3>
<pb n="85">
<div3>
<comhd3><idref>Z300767846</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
SCENE VII <attbytes>8Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767846</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Garibaldi: A Chronicle Play of Italian Freedom in Ten Scenes</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1936</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">May</hi> 15<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1860.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The hill&hyphen;side of Pianto dei Romani, outside Calatafima in Sicily</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The sound of an action in progress can be heard from a not far distant point on the hill&hyphen;side</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Three young armed Red&hyphen;shirts, not wounded, but in a state of extreme exhaustion from hours of continuous fighting, stagger on in retreat</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>Here&mdash;where are we&mdash;what are we doing?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>Out of that inferno. Flesh and blood can't stand it for ever. Three bloody hours of it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Third Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>Like trying to climb the side of a house. If one of those Neapolitan devils could have got me, I'd have thanked him for it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>But&mdash;my God&mdash;we're retreating&mdash;we can't do that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>Don't be a fool. I tell you there's a limit&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>We must go back&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Third Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>What's the use&mdash;those blasted <pb n="86">terraces&mdash;always another one to get up&mdash;there's no chance&mdash;we're done for.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Nino Bixio comes on from the opposite direction. He is blazing with ferocious energy and excitement, but the hours of action in the sweltering heat have left him hardly recognisable. He carries his drawn sword</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>What the devil are you doing here!</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>It's no good, Colonel&mdash;we can't&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>No good! What's no good? You're no good&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Third Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>I couldn't drag myself another yard up those terraces, Colonel&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Who wants you to drag yourself&mdash;you've got to charge&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>But, Colonel&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Charge&mdash;you understand&mdash;and go on charging till doomsday. What the hell do you suppose you're doing here? You deserve to be shot, the lot of you. Get back, go on&mdash;get back and behave yourselves&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Second Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>How can&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Don't you speak to me. Get back. Do you know who I am? I'm Czar, Sultan, Pope! I'm Nino Bixio! I'm to be obeyed like God! <pb n="87">Don't you speak to me&mdash;get back&mdash;or I'll cut you to pieces&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, cut me to pieces&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking him by the ear</hi>).</stage> <p>No, my lad, go and let the Neapolitan do that. Here, have a drop of this. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He gives them his flask, from which they drink</hi>.)</stage> There now&mdash;back with you&mdash;and don't let's have any more of this damn nonsense.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Red&hyphen;shirt</hi>.</speaker> <p>Come on. Sorry, Colonel&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Don't be sorry. Fight.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">They go back, and as they disappear Garibaldi comes on with Beppo, Menotti who is wounded in the hand, and two other staff officers. All are battle&hyphen;stained</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Who were those?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Three young men who thought they'd had enough of it. I persuaded them they were wrong.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>I see.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>All the same, I think they were about right.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Bixio! Will you say that again?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>I know&mdash;I know. But no one else dare tell you. You can't accuse me of ever having had enough. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Pointing across the hill</hi>.)</stage> But see there. When we came up here to look an hour ago, we were just where we are now. We haven't got one terrace farther. The Neapolitans are as firmly on the ridge as ever&mdash;and there they're likely to be.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="88">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>He's right, General.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Being right has nothing to do with it. What is possible doesn't matter to&hyphen;day. Once and for all, Nino&mdash;and the rest of you&mdash;understand this. We have got into Sicily with a thousand men. If we win this battle to&hyphen;day, we can take Palermo, we can cross to the mainland, we can enter Naples, and we can give Italy to Victor Emmanuel. I tell you that what is possible doesn't matter. We shall have done the impossible&mdash;we shall have conquered twenty thousand regulars with a thousand volunteers. How many men have we lost?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Two hundred&mdash;perhaps three.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>That leaves seven hundred. There is the height of Pianto dei Romani. With our seven hundred we go on attacking till there is not one of us left to attack. Here, in this place, to&hyphen;day, we make Italy or die. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He looks across the hill through his glasses</hi>.)</stage> Bixio! Do you see what the Neapolitans are doing? By God&mdash;they're throwing stones. They've run out of powder and shot. Come on&mdash;we've been away too long.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He leads them out. A bugle sounds as</hi></stage>
<trailer><hi r="smcap">the scene closes</hi></trailer>
</div3>
<pb n="89">
<div3>
<comhd3><idref>Z300767847</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
SCENE VIII <attbytes>11Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767847</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Garibaldi: A Chronicle Play of Italian Freedom in Ten Scenes</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1936</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Evening of the same day</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The top of the Pianto dei Romani</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Beppo, Bixio, Menotti, and several other officers and men of the red shirts are seated or lying on the ground, their rifles and swords beside them. They are still breathless and exhausted from the fury of their last and victorious assault upon the height. Three or four bodies are laid out in a row, covered with cloaks</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">On a piece of rising ground Garibaldi is standing, looking out across the plain through his glasses</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">lying on his back</hi>).</stage> <p>General. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Garibaldi grunts, without looking at him</hi>.)</stage> Do you know you've been on your feet or in the saddle since sunrise, and it's now nearly sunset?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Have I?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Hark at him. Can't you sit down and rest?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes&mdash;there's no doubt about it. They've gone for good. Here. Look. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Handing his glasses to Bixio, who scrambles slowly up to take them</hi>.)</stage> Pretty sight, isn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="90">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes. Let them go home and tell Naples about that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">He returns the glasses to Garibaldi, and lies down again</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>And now for Palermo.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes&mdash;but not to&hyphen;night?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">laughing</hi>).</stage> <p>No, Beppo, my boy. We can sleep to&hyphen;night. <stage>[<hi r="italic">He sits down where he stands</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Do you know where I think we should sleep, General?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Where?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Just here. Just exactly here. No other place at all, but just here.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very well, Nino. There's no better spot in Europe to&hyphen;day. The Thousand have made it immortal.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Three or four Peasant Girls come in with baskets of fruit and bread, and wine&hyphen;skins, which they distribute among the men</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">to one of them</hi>).</stage> <p>You got up here quicker than we did.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Girl</hi>.</speaker> <p>We were waiting.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Waiting?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Another Girl</hi>.</speaker> <p>We knew that Garibaldi would win.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Another</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">handing her basket to Garibaldi</hi>).</stage> <p>They say that Garibaldi always wins.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>No, my dear, not always.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="91">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Another</hi>.</speaker> <p>They say he's a devil when he's fighting.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh&mdash;they say that, do they?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Another</hi>.</speaker> <p>They say he can't be hurt in battle. He's protected by a saint.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Is that so, General?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Girl</hi>.</speaker> <p>General? Are you Garibaldi?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The Others</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh&mdash;Garibaldi&mdash;we didn't know that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">First Girl</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">putting her basket on the ground by Garibaldi</hi>).</stage> <p>I say&mdash;let us leave these here. <stage>(<hi r="italic">The others put their baskets down by the soldiers</hi>.)</stage> A little bit extra for your friends, General&mdash;we've plenty more for the others. There were fifty of us waiting, you know. We shall have something to tell them. Garibaldi. Come on. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The Girls go out</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The daylight is fading</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Menotti.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Go down and see that the guards are properly set. Our Neapolitan friends won't interfere with us again to&hyphen;night, but see that proper precautions are taken.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, sir. <stage align="r">[He goes out.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>General.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Do you remember Marseilles&mdash;twenty&hyphen;six years ago?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="92">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes. Zucchi saw me buying chestnuts.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Zucchi. Yes. The Villa Sparda. Poor fellow.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well&mdash;here we are at last.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes&mdash;it's the beginning of the end. Palermo&mdash;we shall manage that all right. And then if nobody stops us from getting across to the mainland, we'll have Naples.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>I think England will see that nobody will stop us.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>And then we'll go back to Caprera.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>But they'll do something better for you than that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Doubtless. Piedmont, King of Italy, will offer me, who knows&mdash;a castle maybe, titles, dowries for my girl. They are not for me. One thing I will take, though.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>What's that?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>A sack of the best seed&hyphen;corn. I've never been able to get the best on Caprera. And they shall give me the best, or I'll know the reason why.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">drowsily</hi>).</stage> <p>General Garibaldi, liberator of Italy, awarded one sack of seed&hyphen;corn, the best quality. Viva l'Italia!</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Nino, you're intoxicated.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="93">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>,</speaker> <p>And who wouldn't be after a day like this? <stage>(<hi r="italic">To one of the boys whom he turned back earlier in the day, now lying beside him</hi>.)</stage> You know, young man, you very nearly got yourself cut to pieces this afternoon by Nino Bixio.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Boy</hi>.</speaker> <p>But we did as you said, Colonel. We beat them up those top terraces&mdash;you saw for yourself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>You did well enough for young 'uns. You can go to sleep like good children.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>There's one man who should be here.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Who's that?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph Mazzini. He was the first to dream of this. Italy must not forget that. <stage align="r">(<hi r="italic">He
 rises</hi>.)</stage> Friends, drink with me to Joseph Mazzini.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">They all rise and drink to the name. Menotti comes back</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Son of Garibaldi, remember that name.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Menotti</hi>.</speaker> <p>I shall, Joseph Mazzini. Papa&mdash;sir&mdash;the guards are all set.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Good. And now we can rest.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Folding his cloak round him, he lies down. The others, too, prepare for sleep</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph Mazzini. And when they tell the story, years, and years, and years to come, no man shall forget&mdash;the name&mdash;of our master&mdash;Joseph Garibaldi.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph Garibaldi.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="94">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">A murmur from the others</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph Garibaldi.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi> <stage>(<hi r="italic">singing&mdash;followed by the rest, and the song is taken up along the hillside</hi>).</stage>
<lyric><stanza><l>Va fuora d'Italia, va fuora ch' &egrave; l'ora,</l>
<l>Va fuora d'Italia, va fuora, O stranier.</l></stanza></lyric></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The song rises in the deepening night as</hi></stage>
<trailer><hi r="smcap">the scene closes</hi></trailer>
</div3>
<pb n="95">
<div3>
<comhd3><idref>Z300767848</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
SCENE IX <attbytes>18Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767848</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Garibaldi: A Chronicle Play of Italian Freedom in Ten Scenes</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1936</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">July</hi> 24<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1860.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Lord John Russell's London house in Chesham Place</hi>.</stage> <stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The Foreign Secretary of Palmerston's Ministry, sixty&hyphen;eight years of age, is sitting at the table of his library, working at official documents, a Foreign Office box beside him. The windows are open to a London summer afternoon</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">A Manservant</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">coming in</hi>).</stage> <p>His Excellency the French Ambassador wishes to see you, my Lord.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>You mean he's here?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, my Lord.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Show him in.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, my Lord.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">He goes out. Russell arranges his papers, placing some in the box</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>.</speaker> <p>His Excellency the French Ambassador.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising</hi>).</stage> <p>Ah, Persigny.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">shaking hands</hi>).</stage> <p>Good afternoon, Russell. I trust that her ladyship is better.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh, thank you&mdash;yes. Much. Sit down. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He does so</hi>.)</stage> A glass of sherry?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="96">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>Thank you. But you should allow me to send you a few bottles. <stage>(<hi r="italic">As Russell fills the glasses</hi>.)</stage> I am a specialist in sherry. This is not too bad, you understand&mdash;but if you would allow me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>I should be enchanted.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>I will see to it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>And now?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>It is this Italian business.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Quite so.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>You know the situation?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>That Garibaldi has taken Palermo and is waiting with his army to cross the straits at Messina. Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>I am instructed to place the views of my Government clearly before you. Garibaldi with his thousand has acquired remarkable prestige by his Sicilian exploit. If he is allowed to cross to the mainland, it is probable that Naples will fall into his power. That, in the long run, is to say into the power of Piedmont and Victor Emmanuel. His Imperial Majesty Louis Napoleon conceives that this would be prejudicial to French interests.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>On what grounds?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>His Majesty desires that Naples should remain a Bourbon monarchy under French influence.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>I see.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>We think, therefore, that Garibaldi <pb n="97">should not be allowed to leave Sicily. The French fleet is under orders to intercept him if the word is given.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>I see.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>At the same time His Imperial Majesty wishes it to be clearly understood that he would on no account allow his Italian policy to impair his friendly relations with the British Government. That he esteems above all other considerations.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>You know that our cordiality is no less than your own.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>We are assured of that. In short, then, we should wish to take no action in the straits unless it were in co&hyphen;operation with your own fleet.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>That should not be impossible. Let me be frank with you. My colleagues and I regard the Italian ambition for a free and united kingdom with sympathy. In this matter, however, I am informed that Count Cavour doesn't wish to associate Piedmont with the irregular designs of Garibaldi on Naples. We should respect the Count's wishes. In the circumstances, it is likely that our fleet could act with yours.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>In that case we should not fear the opinion of Europe. May I communicate this to Paris?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="98">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>I must consult my colleagues. But&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The Manservant comes in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">impatiently</hi>).</stage> <p>Yes&mdash;what is it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">handing him a note</hi>).</stage> <p>From her ladyship, my Lord.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">reading</hi>).</stage> <p>Sir J&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">He stops short</hi>.)</stage> Tell her ladyship that I will attend to it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, my Lord. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>When may I&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Do I understand that without us you would take no action?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>Undoubtedly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>You shall know our decision to&hyphen;night.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>And you think&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>You shall know to&hyphen;night.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising</hi>).</stage> <p>Thank you, my dear Russell. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Russell rings a bell</hi>.)</stage> The sherry shall be sent to&hyphen;morrow. You will find its bouquet very unusual.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The Servant comes in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>His Excellency's carriage.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, my Lord.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Persigny</hi>.</speaker> <p>Good afternoon.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">shaking hands</hi>).</stage> <p>Good afternoon.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The Servant shows Persigny out</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Russell re&hyphen;reads the note, and rings the bell. The Servant comes back</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, my Lord?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="99">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ask Sir James Lacaita to see me here.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, my Lord. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Russell stands, taking rapid stock of a new situation that has arisen. A street&hyphen;cry is heard passing in the Square outside. After a moment the Servant returns, announcing</hi>&mdash;</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>.</speaker> <p>Sir James Lacaita, my Lord.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">He goes. Lacaita, forty&hyphen;seven years of age, is in a state of high excitement. He is also suffering from a severe cold, and ought to be in bed</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi>.</speaker> <p>My dear John&mdash;has he left?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Can't you see he has? What's the matter?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi>.</speaker> <p>When I arrived I was told that you could see no one. I insisted that I should see madame. I was told that she was ill, but I insisted. You have her note?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes. What's it all about?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi>.</speaker> <p>I, too, am ill. I was in bed when the Piedmontese Minister called to see me. I defied my doctor and came to you at once.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>But&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Do not interrupt me, I beg. Every moment is precious. When I was turned out of Italy ten years ago for communicating the truth <pb n="100">about my country to Mr Gladstone, I found you my best friend here in London. I have not forfeited that friendship&mdash;eh?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>No, James. We have shown that we are sensible&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes&mdash;you have rewarded my modest services with many honours. Very well. Now is the moment for something more serious.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes&mdash;what is it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi>.</speaker> <p>The Frenchman wishes you to join him in preventing Garibaldi from crossing the straits&mdash;is it not so?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Something like that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi>.</speaker> <p>You have not promised?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>No.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">speaking in great excitement and with difficulty</hi>).</stage> <p>You must not do so. Before I leave this room you must undertake not to do so&mdash;you must. I know&mdash;you believe that Cavour's policy is not to interfere in this Neapolitan business. He has said so. How, as Prime Minister of Piedmont, could he say otherwise? But this is no time for diplomatic pretence. Cavour all along has prayed for Garibaldi's success in Sicily, knowing that then he would be irresistible in Naples. Garibaldi has succeeded in Sicily. At the moment Austria is not dangerous, and the Piedmontese army is mobilised <pb n="101">against the Papal States. Let Garibaldi occupy Naples, and Italy is made. Stop him, and French influence in Naples will shatter the dreams of a united Italy, shatter it perhaps beyond recovery. Sir James Hudson, your own minister in Turin, knows it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The Servant comes in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>.</speaker> <p>From the Foreign Office, my Lord.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">He gives an envelope to Russell, and goes. A police constable passes the window</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">reading</hi>).</stage> <p>Curious. It's a telegram from Hudson. He appears to know of your instructions.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi>.</speaker> <p>You see&mdash;Cavour must have told him. Inform Persigny that you cannot intervene&mdash;I implore you. France will do nothing without you. Let me wire to Cavour that Garibaldi can be told that the straits are open. The life of a nation in its birth agony depends on your decision. Will you make us know again the despair of Mazzini's failure at Rome eleven years ago? You cannot. The future of Italy is in your hands, now, at this minute.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He chokes with exhaustion</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>You ought to be in bed, you know.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi>.</speaker> <p>In bed! How should I be in bed when I am told to plead for the life of my country?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="102">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>I think you may go to bed and sleep in peace.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi>.</speaker> <p>I may wire? When? Now?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>No, not now, my dear James. Palmerston has a prejudice in favour of being consulted by his ministers. But I think you may go to bed without misgiving.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">Lady Russell comes in, wearing a dressing&hyphen;gown</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi>.</speaker> <p>My dear Lady&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>My dear&mdash;what is the meaning of this?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lady John</hi>.</speaker> <p>I had to come down to see what you two were doing. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Her husband takes her to a chair</hi>.)</stage> Thank you, John. James has told me what it's all about. You must see, John, how reasonable it is&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Must I? You are not aware, perhaps, that Her Britannic Majesty's Government is not susceptible to feminine intrigue?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lady John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Then you are going to do the right thing?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Her Majesty's Government always does the right thing. That, my dear, is universally understood.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lady John</hi>.</speaker> <p>I think I should like a glass of sherry.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Would your doctor&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lady John</hi>.</speaker> <p>No. But my doctor has already <pb n="103">kept me in bed three days longer than was necessary. A glass of sherry please.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">giving it to her</hi>).</stage> <p>You're a very wilful woman.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lady John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Fortunately, yes. James would like a glass too. And yourself, John. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Russell fills the glasses</hi>.)</stage> The Sicilian weather may be relied on in July. A quiet crossing to Garibaldi. <stage>[<hi r="italic">She drinks</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">drinking</hi>).</stage> <p>My dear lady.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lady John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, John?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">drinking</hi>).</stage> <p>Oh&mdash;your very good health, my dear. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He rings the bell</hi>.)</stage> Now, James, you must go home. And if you think your telegram would give you a more comfortable night, I shouldn't wish to discourage you. Officially, you understand, I can say nothing for the moment.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lady John</hi>.</speaker> <p>I should send it, James.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The Servant comes in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lord John</hi>.</speaker> <p>Call a cab for Sir James.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The Servant</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, my Lord. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lacaita</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">kissing Lady John's hand</hi>).</stage> <p>I am recovered already. Italy will remember you, John.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes out. The street&hyphen;cry passes again as</hi></stage>
<trailer><hi r="smcap">the scene closes</hi></trailer>
</div3>
<div3>
<pb n="104">
<comhd3><idref>Z300767849</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
SCENE X <attbytes>14Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767849</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Garibaldi: A Chronicle Play of Italian Freedom in Ten Scenes</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1936</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">October</hi> 26<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1860. <hi r="italic">Morning</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Outside the Tollbar Tavern, standing at cross&hyphen;roads, ten miles north of Capua in Naples. The garden is above the road, which runs beyond and below a thick hedge of vines</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">At a garden table, with a bottle of wine before them, and smoking cigars, are seated General Fanti, commander&hyphen;in&hyphen;chief of the Piedmontese army under Victor Emmanuel, and one of his Staff Officers. An Aide comes in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Aide</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">saluting</hi>).</stage> <p>Both columns are approaching the cross&hyphen;roads simultaneously, sir. His Majesty expects to meet General Garibaldi here, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very good. And you might understand that the army of Piedmont does not recognise the rank of irregulars.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Aide</hi>.</speaker> <p>I beg your pardon, sir. And Count Cavour is coming along the road.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi>.</speaker> <p>The devil he is! Go, and keep your eyes open.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Aide</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, sir. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="105">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi>.</speaker> <p>General Garibaldi. These fellows are being spoiled.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Officer</hi>.</speaker> <p>I suppose they've done a pretty good job in Sicily and Naples, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Never mind that. Haven't we done a good job, too? We've proclaimed Victor Emmanuel in the Papal States&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Officer</hi>.</speaker> <p>And Garibaldi has proclaimed him in Naples.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very well&mdash;and now we take charge of Naples as well. Garibaldi and his fancy men can take a back seat.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Cavour, appearing with a Secretary, overhears this</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>What's that about Garibaldi, General?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising&mdash;the Officer also</hi>).</stage> <p>Will you take some wine, Count?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">sitting</hi>).</stage> <p>No thank you. Pray be seated. <stage>(<hi r="italic">The others sit</hi>.)</stage> What's this about Garibaldi?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi>.</speaker> <p>I was saying that he has done all that we require of him, and may now gracefully retire into the background.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Why is it that you professional soldiers are always so infernally jealous?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Jealous? What do you mean?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's plain enough, isn't it? In any case, General Garibaldi&mdash;you understand? General <pb n="106">Garibaldi&mdash;and his men are to be treated with every consideration and honour. It's true, his great work is ended&mdash;His Majesty King Victor Emmanuel now has Piedmont, the States, Naples&mdash;he is to be King of Italy. But it was Garibaldi and his Thousand who, against all the odds, made this possible. Italy will never forget it in the future, and we mustn't forget it now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi>.</speaker> <p>All right. But you can't expect regular troops to treat a lot of amateurs as equals&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Amateurs be damned. Garibaldi has seen more fighting, Fanti, than you'll ever hear of.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well&mdash;I won't be responsible for discipline if&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Fanti, you forget yourself. We have now to take over from Garibaldi. If we do it gracelessly, we shall be disowned by Italy&mdash;be clear about that. And Europe will condemn us&mdash;very properly. We have to behave greatly to a great man, and let's have no nonsense about it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi>.</speaker> <p>I tell you, military requirements&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Are secondary to State requirements. This is a civilised country, and in civilised countries the army obeys the State. <stage>(<hi r="italic">They rise, as he does</hi>)</stage> It was to tell you this that I came. Don't let there be any mistake.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He goes, with his Secretary</hi>.</stage>
<pb n="107">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">walking up and down</hi>).</stage> <p>Why the hell does he want to upset me like that to&hyphen;day? Let him make Garibaldi commander&hyphen;in&hyphen;chief&mdash;I don't care.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Officer</hi>.</speaker> <p>I shouldn't take it like that, sir. We can just be civil, and let things go their way.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi>.</speaker> <p>I won't be civil&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Garibaldi, with Beppo, Bixio, Menotti, and others of his staff and men, come in. They all salute</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>General Fanti, I congratulate you on your Roman campaign.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">adjusting himself with difficulty to an unpleasant situation</hi>).</stage> <p>I thank you&mdash;sir. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He salutes</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>If I may speak as one soldier to another, I shouldn't be put out about it. After all, we have done part of the work, and you're going to take most of the glory. You're welcome. Why worry?</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">The Aide comes in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Aide</hi>.</speaker> <p>They are here, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">The Piedmontese march is heard. Above the hedge a platoon of bayonet&hyphen;tops passes by</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>We may as well be reasonable about it, you know. Italy is all that matters now, isn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fanti</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">coldly</hi>).</stage> <p>I have my instructions from Count Cavour. I have the honour to be your ally, General. You will excuse me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="108">
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">He salutes, with his Officer, and goes out. Another platoon passes</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">imitating him</hi>).</stage> <p>I have the honour to be&mdash;damn fool.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Beppo</hi>.</speaker> <p>That gentleman needs&mdash;educating.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Bixio</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">exploding</hi>).</stage> <p>He needs&mdash;but it would shock you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Another platoon comes to a halt beyond the hedge as the march reaches a crescendo and suddenly stops</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Victor Emmanuel, with Cavour, Fanti, and his Staff come in. The King, forty years of age, is in full field uniform, a magnificent figure of the florid Italian genius. Brusque and undemonstrative by nature, he is transfigured by the occasion</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">removing his hat, plumed with black cocks' feathers</hi>).</stage> <p>I salute the first King of Italy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The King</hi>.</speaker> <p>How are you, my dear Garibaldi?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well. And your Majesty?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The King</hi>.</speaker> <p>What is it our friend Lord John Russell would say?&mdash;all the better for seeing you. Joseph Garibaldi&mdash;when I was a child I heard a story. It was that on the quay at Marseilles you told a chestnut&hyphen;seller that you would pull the Italian chestnuts out of the fire yet. You remember?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="109">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes, your Majesty.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The King</hi>.</speaker> <p>And so you have pulled them out. Our friend Cavour here has ideas as to how they should be eaten. But my son, and my son's son, will remember that Garibaldi and his men achieved by genius what we by opportunity, and the grace of God, shall improve. We now proceed to Naples, a gift of your heroism, my dear Garibaldi, that we do not undervalue. As King of Italy, an Italy that now belongs to the commonwealth of Europe, we offer you anything that you may choose to ask.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>The blood of my friends, sir, has no price. We are content to give you an Italian kingdom.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The King</hi>.</speaker> <p>But something you must accept.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Then, sir, when you no longer need us in the settlement of your affairs, may I ask&mdash;with General Fanti's leave&mdash;for a sack of the best seed&hyphen;corn that your dominion can provide for my use on Caprera?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The King</hi>.</speaker> <p>Seed&hyphen;corn&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Believe me, sir, I ask nothing more.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The King</hi>.</speaker> <p>On one condition then.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>But of course, your Majesty.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The King</hi>.</speaker> <p>We shall attend you on Caprera to see it sown.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Your Majesty.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="110">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The King</hi>.</speaker> <p>We shall bring General Fanti with us.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Nevertheless, your Majesty will receive a royal welcome.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The King</hi>.</speaker> <p>We shall expect you in Naples the day after to&hyphen;morrow. Cavour, you will remain to escort the General and his friends.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">The Piedmontese march strikes up again as the bayonets move on, and Victor Emmanuel and his Officers go</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Joseph, we have had our differences. History will make sport of them, I suppose. But we know better, don't we?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>We know better.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Italy. It was our dream. It has come true.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Our dream. And another's. Will you take one word on trust from me, Cavour?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>Any.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not a word, but a name.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Cavour</hi>.</speaker> <p>A name?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Garibaldi</hi>.</speaker> <p>Victor Emmanuel; Camillo Cavour; I am vain enough to add, Joseph Garibaldi. And then a fourth, and you have the Italy that is to be&mdash;Joseph Mazzini. I'm no statesman, but sometimes I have the gift of prophecy. My Anita used to say that. Italy is now given to the world, and the names are&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="111">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The Red&hyphen;shirts</hi>.</speaker> <p>Victor Emmanuel&mdash;Camillo Cavour&mdash;Joseph Mazzini&mdash;Joseph Garibaldi&mdash;Viva l'Italia!</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">They all kneel round Garibaldi and Cavour, crying &ldquo;Viva l'Italia!&rdquo; and singing the refrain of Garibaldi's hymn as</hi></stage>
</div3>
