<pb n="7">
<div2>
<comhd2><idref>Z200766986</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
Main text <attbytes>45Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z200766986</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>John Bull Calling: A Political Parable in One Act</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1928</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd2>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">A bedroom in John Bull's castle. It is not really much of a castle; being, in fact, merely his home. The apartment is a reasonably spacious one, and furnished in middling taste</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">John Bull is lying in bed, propped up on pillows. His night&hyphen;cap has a curious resemblance to a top hat, and his night&hyphen;shirt is made from a Union Jack</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">At the bedside, Britannia, appropriately seated on a shield, is in attendance. Her garment, it seems, has some association with the Red Cross. She has at hand a table, on which are medicine bottles, and other appurtenances of the sick&hyphen;room</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">This group is secluded from the rest of the apartment by a large folding&hyphen;screen, decorated with highly coloured presentments of the crowned heads of England from</hi> 1066. <hi r="italic">It throws a shadow over the patient and his nurse</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">On the far side of the room, at an open window through which the spring sun shines brightly, three doctors are seated round a table in consultation. Sir Victor Torian, sixty&hyphen;five years of age, is a comfortable, extremely well&hyphen;groomed Englishman, characteristic rather of the higher squirearchy than of medicine. An easy manner, is nevertheless <pb n="8">a touch pontifical. The Welshman, Dacellew Lloyd, is ten years younger, very professional, but with moments of abstraction and a roving eye that might perhaps be seeking about for the main chance. Hector MacIlp, forty&hyphen;five, is an eager and somewhat worried Scot, with an air of struggling against odds that have, however, not impaired his confidence</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Torian and Lloyd wear regulation professional clothes. MacIlp favours a tweed suit, but it is well tailored and in good taste</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>It's all very well, Torian. You call me to consultation, but so far as I can make out you take not the slightest notice of anything I say.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>My dear Dacellew, I should be charmed to listen if you said anything to the purpose. I tell you the man has nothing organically wrong with him. I've looked after him for several years, and I know his constitution. He has a sluggish liver and low blood pressure, that's all. He wants complete quiet and rest, and a continued course of my extremely reliable sleeping&hyphen;draughts. I only called you in because the family were anxious. And all you can do is to talk nonsense about glands and toxins.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Your methods are wholly unscientific and <pb n="9">out&hyphen;of&hyphen;date. Of course he needs rest. He's likely to go on needing it so long as you are content to let his blood be full of poisons. What he wants is a thorough regeneration of the system, and you can think of nothing but a sleeping draught. I warn you, Torian, you'll sleep him to death if you aren't careful.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>And may I ask, Sir Victor, what he is expected to rest on? I mean the wherewithal? He's got to earn his living, hasn't he?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>My patient, Mr MacIlp, is a man of considerable wealth.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>It may be an unprofessional observation, but if what I'm told about your bills is correct, it's a wonder he has sixpence to bless himself with.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>It is unprofessional, and most improper. You were invited here, MacIlp, to give your opinion as a surgeon, not to make personal reflections. I don't myself think your attendance was necessary, but the family desired that too.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, you have my opinion. I think you and Mr Lloyd here are both talking beside the point. It's plain to me that Mr Bull has a duodenal ulcer, and that nothing can save him but an operation.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Ulcer&mdash;stuff! I may be old&hyphen;fashioned, but I've no patience with this medi&aelig;val partiality <pb n="10">for the knife. I see no symptoms of an ulcer. I tell you he needs no operation; he needs quiet, building up.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>He doesn't. He needs injections. You ought to have a blood test made. Then you'ld know what he wants.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'm not concerned with what he wants, but with what's good for him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>The trouble being that you don't know what it is. While I do.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>I know perfectly well.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>How can you, when you're incapable of taking the most elementary steps to ascertain? Though let me tell you, MacIlp, your notion about an operation is as mischievous as Torian's about sleep gentle sleep.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, I don't believe in panic violence, and I don't believe in quackery.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>No&mdash;you believe in dope.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>And if you think that calling me names disposes of a physical condition in Mr Bull, you are mistaken. And, if I may say so, as usual.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>When you've lived as long as I have, perhaps you will perceive the virtue of good manners. On the other hand, perhaps you won't.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>To judge by your example, Sir Victor, presumably I won't.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="11">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>When you've done abusing each other, suppose we return to the point. If you like, I will arrange for the test to be made.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>I don't like. You're not safe, Dacellew, not safe at all. You'll be taking up with osteopathy next.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, osteopathy is an idea, anyway. It's better than mesmerism.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Are you suggesting that I'm a mesmerist?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Certainly you are <stage>(<hi r="italic">making passes with his fingers</hi>).</stage> A nice long sleep, Mr Bull. Very calm and deep, Mr Bull. I'm little Bo Peep, Mr Bull. I'll mind your sheep, Mr Bull. And you talk to me of quackery, to me, who am in the scientific van.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Say the scientific cart, and I agree.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Another twenty&hyphen;four hours, and it may be too late. You are both vapouring about theories. I stick to a crucial fact, operate, or take the responsibility yourselves.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>There'll be no operation with my consent. An entirely unnecessary shock to the system. He needs injections.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">thumping the table, and raising his voice to a shout</hi>).</stage> <p>Injections be damned! What the patient wants is perfect quiet.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="12">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">who has been drowsing, waking with a start</hi>).</stage> <p>What's the matter? Haven't those fellows finished yet?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi>.</speaker> <p>No. They're still in consultation.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>I say, Britty, give me a little bicarbonate of soda. Don't let old Torian see.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Britannia produces a small tin of bicarbonate and mixes him a dose. He takes it furtively</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's all I want, you know. Pigheaded lot, these doctors&mdash;won't let a fellow use his common&hyphen;sense.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He retires under the bedclothes, and can be seen moving slightly at spasmodic intervals. Torian rises and moves across the room. He speaks round the screen to Britannia</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>I beg your pardon. I trust I didn't disturb him. These gentlemen provoked me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi>.</speaker> <p>It's all right, sir. Really, you know, I don't think there's much the matter with him at all.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Quite&mdash;quite. But I did not understand that your duties as a nurse embraced the expression of opinions.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">slightly ogling him</hi>).</stage> <p>Embraced?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Don't be pert, young woman. And mind your business.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="13">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'm sorry, sir. No offence meant, I'm sure.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very well. Only I'm the doctor, you know. We mustn't forget that, must we? No.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">appearing from his retirement</hi>).</stage> <p>That's better. Does me no end of good, Britty, just a little dose like that. Oh&mdash;I didn't see you, Sir Victor. What's the verdict?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>I have to speak very seriously to you, Bull. I've been your doctor now for, what is it, five years? Have I done anything to forfeit your belief in me?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh, no, Sir Victor. Why&mdash;has anybody been saying things? Of course, since you're asking me, I do feel sometimes that those sleeping draughts of yours&mdash;I mean&mdash;well, they don't encourage enterprise, do they? You know&mdash;high o'er the fence leaps Sunny Jim. My mind gets&mdash;how shall I say?&mdash;fumy&mdash;can't seem to think.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>You mustn't worry about thinking, Bull. Relax.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">rising impatiently and crossing the room</hi>).</stage> <p>You are requested not to think, Mr Bull&mdash;only pay.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>MacIlp, you're intolerable.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, if you think I'm going to stand by and watch this lunacy without doing anything, you're wrong. I'm going to speak out. Mr Bull, <pb n="14">I think you ought to know that Sir Victor is withholding grave information from you. As he won't tell you, I must. You have a duodenal ulcer, and the only hope for you is immediate operation.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>What's that&mdash;an operation&mdash;but, Sir Victor&mdash;what does it mean&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>My dear Bull&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Take my advice and don't listen to him, Mr Bull. He'll only throw dust in your eyes&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">joining the others</hi>).</stage> <p>Sleepy dust&mdash;it's his only panacea. A nice long sleep, Mr Bull. Very calm and very deep, Mr Bull&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>You know, Sir Victor, I <hi r="italic">was</hi> saying that you seemed to be overdoing the sleep business a bit.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh, of course, if you are dissatisfied with my services&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not at all, not at all, Sir Victor, but&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Never before in my professional career&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>No&mdash;please don't take it like that&mdash;&hyphen;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>And if now I have ceased to enjoy your confidence, I shall embrace the opportunity&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi>.</speaker> <p>Embrace?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">exploding</hi>).</stage> <p>Will you kindly not speak to me like that. I shall report you to headquarters.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="15">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">aside to Britannia</hi>).</stage> <p>It's all right, my dear, don't mind him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>As I was saying, I shall embrace the opportunity to relinquish a case that has caused me continual anxiety.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>No, you mustn't do that. I'm sure no one meant to be offensive.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd and MacIlp</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">in unison</hi>).</stage> <p>I certainly did mean to be offensive.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>It's the only way to bring some people to their senses.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Though I must tell you, Mr Bull, that Mr MacIlp is as mistaken as Sir Victor. You don't need to relax, you need rousing. And you don't need an operation, you need injections. Now if you will allow me&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>But really, gentlemen, what am I to do? I'm sure you all mean it for the best, but&mdash;dear me&mdash;it is rather confusing.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Let me speak, Bull, and if you wish it to be so, for the last time. When you first placed yourself in my hands, you were in a state of extreme exhaustion. I took such measures as I thought best to restore your impaired vitality. I kept disquieting truths from your knowledge. I put the most cheerful complexion upon your affairs, and I prescribed a mild and harmless narcotic. I have <pb n="16">been unremitting in my attentions, and for these I have required fees that at no time exceeded one fourth of your net annual income, from which I agreed that reasonable deductions might be made under headings A.B.C.D. and X.Y.Z., see notes on back page and kiss the book. When your friends have enquired, somewhat impatiently, as I thought, how long it would be before your recovery was complete, I have told them that time was necessary&mdash;time, I said, with classical authority, is the essence of the contract.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Essence of eyewash&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Hold your tongue, Lloyd. I will not endure these insults&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Please go on, Sir Victor.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>I have nothing to add. Under my treatment you are progressing favourably. In time, as I say, in time I should have you on your legs again, I trust robust.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>You'll not help the case by making poetry of it. By to&hyphen;morrow night you'll have him on his back for good and all if you don't operate.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>MacIlp, you've only got one idea in your head. That's one more than Torian, but it's only one. And don't be irreverent about poetry. I have myself been frequently moved by the spectacle of the sunset on the everlasting hills. But that's <pb n="17">no matter now. Mr Bull, whose advice do you propose to take?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>All you gentlemen are so kind, it's really very hard. Of course, Mr MacIlp, I can't honestly say I fancy the idea of being cut open&mdash;you can never tell what may happen afterwards, can you? I can't say that I'm very much for Sir Victor's sleep and the world sleeps with you either. But then at least you're likely to wake up the same man, more or less. Whereas after your carpentry, Mr MacIlp, I might be something quite different, and not be very sure how to conduct myself, if you get me. Pardon the Americanism&mdash;I'm picking up quite a lot of slick words from Sam lately. As for your injections, Mr Lloyd, what precisely is your line of country?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>There's something wrong with your blood, Mr Bull. I can't say precisely what it is without analysis. But for every toxin there is an anti&hyphen;toxin&mdash;that's science. If I may borrow a metaphor from my political friends, demand creates supply. Ascertain what the demand is, and our laboratories will meet it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Quackery&mdash;pure quackery. Take my word for it, Bull, he'll keep you dependent on his injections for the rest of your days, once you begin. And Mr MacIlp might permanently upset your <pb n="18">constitution, if no worse. Believe me, Bull, and I know best, your malady is one for rest.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>There you go again. Do you think you're Rudyard Kipling?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>I beg you at least not to profane that great name.</p>
<stanza><l>The shouting and the tumult dies,</l>
<l>The captains and the kings depart&mdash;</l>
<l>Er&mdash;</l>
<l>Drink to me only with thine eyes&mdash;</l>
<l>But&mdash;er&mdash;give, oh, give me back my heart.</l></stanza></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Rubbish. Nothing like it. Besides, what kind of a poet is he, whatever?</p>
<stanza><l>Cambria, beloved of my soul,</l>
<l>Upon thy bosom let me fall,</l>
<l>Where I can hear thy torrents roll,</l>
<l>And I can hear thy voices call.</l></stanza></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very soothing, no doubt. But this isn't an estethfod or whatever you call it. I've no further time to waste. What's it going to be?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>I forbid an operation.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very well, I'm sorry for your patient.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>And I forbid injections.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Torian, you'ld be ridiculous if you weren't tragic. Have you no sense of responsibility at all?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>None. Nor have you, if it comes to that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="19">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>All right, MacIlp, I'll see you don't get into my golf club. You understand?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Damn your golf club.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Do you both realise that you are in a sick room?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd and MacIlp</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">simultaneously in a shout</hi>).</stage> <p>Mind your own business.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking up their note</hi>).</stage> <p>What do you suppose I am doing? <stage>(<hi r="italic">Beating John Bull's pillow</hi>.)</stage> Don't I tell you my patient needs quiet. And you come here making disturbance enough to undo all the good I've done.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>All right, domes of silence.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi>.</speaker> <p>Look here, I don't mind telling you I'm fed up with the whole lot of you. I'm brought in to nurse this case, and what do I find? I could see the moment I set eyes on him there was nothing the matter with Mr Bull. A bit nervy, and his stomach a bit out of order, perhaps, but what he wants is to get out and about and be allowed to look after his own affairs. And I find Sir Victor treating him as though the most he could look forward to was superannuation in a bath&hyphen;chair on rusks and arrowroot.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's quite right, my dear&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh, you're no better. I know you&mdash;taking up with any new hokey&hyphen;pokey that comes <pb n="20">along, and wanting to try it on someone to see if it works. Well, you needn't come trying it on him. Who knows what stuff you'll put into him? Might give him fits or anything.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's the way to talk, Miss. Now surgery is scientific&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi>.</speaker> <p>As for you, Mr MacIlp, I wouldn't trust him with you two minutes. Another little stitch wouldn't do us any harm. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Lapsing into vernacular</hi>)</stage> Any'ow, 'e don't want no doctors.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Really&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi>.</speaker> <p>I beg your pardon, Sir Victor <stage>(<hi r="italic">mincing</hi>),</stage> he does not require any doctors. And what's more, I don't think any of you are doing the square thing by him. You all have your pet notions, and you think a sight more of them than you do of him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Come now, Britty, I wouldn't say that&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Really, I protest&mdash;young woman&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's going a bit far, my dear. In fact, if you have the impudence to say that of Dacellew Lloyd, I'm afraid you're a hussy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>For the first time in my experience I find myself in agreement with Mr Lloyd.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>I associate myself with that sentiment, MacIlp. I'm relieved to hear, Bull, that you realise how base is this&mdash;er&mdash;minx's imputation.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="21">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Honest to goodness, John, I'm truly anxious for your good. I've given great study to injections&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'ld have you know, Mr Bull, that in my anxiety I'ld be very willing to perform the operation without any fee.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's very handsome of you, Mr MacIlp.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>If it comes to that, I'll say the same. And I'll provide the serum into the bargain.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>These are personal matters. But, as we all seem to be in the confessional, Mr Bull would tell you that I have given him the first call on my time for a considerable period at four hundred pounds a year. And, I will add, I have made even that sum over annually to the College of Sedative Physiology.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Of course, we haven't all got eight thousand a year private income.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Dacellew!</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Cries of Withdraw! Very well, Torian, I withdraw the eight thousand a year.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Stick to the point. This lady has taken liberties with my character&mdash;with our characters.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>I do think you ought to apologise, Britty. I'm sure these gentlemen wish me well, whatever their views.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="22">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi>.</speaker> <p>I'll apologise fast enough if they show it. But you can't expect me&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">There is suddenly a sound of altercation outside, and a revolver shot; the door is burst open and Vesuvius Blag, a dark, wiry man, in a demoniac frenzy, smoking revolver in hand, rushes into the room. He wears a red blouse&hyphen;coat</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">with a slight foreign accent</hi>).</stage> <p>Where is Bull, John Bull, Citizen Bull that should be, Bureaucrat Bull that is?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Who the devil are you, sir?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's nothing to do with you, plum&hyphen;pudding face. I'm Blag, Vesuvius Blag, mine&hyphen;layer&hyphen;in&hyphen;chief to Old Nick, and I want to see John Bull.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>What is your business, man?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not yours. Savvy&mdash;comprenez&mdash;verstehen sie?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Mr Bull is resting.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>He is expecting an operation.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>John Bull, and who are you for such familiarities, is about to be inoculated.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>Resting? Operations? Inoculations? Hell! Where is the blighter?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Britty&mdash;carbonate of soda&mdash;quick!</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi>.</speaker> <p>Don't worry, old bean. Here it is <pb n="23"><stage>(<hi r="italic">she gives him his glass</hi>).</stage> Get out of here&mdash;see&mdash;get out: or I'll bash you one.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">restraining her</hi>).</stage> <p>What is your business with Mr Bull?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">flourishing his revolver</hi>).</stage> <p>Get your ugly carcass out of my way, and I'll show you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Put that thing away, man, or you'll do somebody an injury.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">who is still concealed from Vesuvius by the screen</hi>).</stage> <p>How did he get in here? What is my butler doing?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>I shot him. You'll find him outside. That'll teach him to be a butler. Are you ginks going to get out of my way, or have I got to put daylight through the lot of you first?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Be reasonable, man.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>I didn't come here for conversation. Get out, I tell you, while you're safe, the bunch of you, and take Britannia rules the Waves with you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Don't be ridiculous&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>There's nothing ridiculous about me. This gun shoots&mdash;get that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>If what you say is true, you've committed one crime already. Perhaps you'll allow me to go and see this poor man whom you say you've shot.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>He's only winged. But don't let me detain you. I've told you to get out twice already.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="24">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>But what is your purpose with Mr Bull?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>I don't like his face, I don't like his ways, and I don't like him. He's too fat, he's too contented, he's too sweet on himself, and his number's up. For the last time, are you going to buzz off before I begin?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">jumping out of bed, and throwing the screen aside</hi>).</stage> <p>What's that you're saying about me?</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Vesuvius' revolver arm goes up. Torian in a flash places himself in front of John Bull, flanked by Lloyd and MacIlp</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Put that confounded thing down.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>Get out of the way, you perishing fools.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Let me get at him&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Torian and the others hold him back, still covering him from Vesuvius</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>Get clear before I count three, or I shoot. One&mdash;two&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Britannia without warning makes a dive for his legs, and brings him down with a crash. Torian and MacIlp each seize an arm, while Lloyd wrenches the revolver from his hand. After a brief struggle they get him under control</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">to Britannia</hi>).</stage> <p>Go for the police, at once.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not at all&mdash;where's my stick?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="25">
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">He finds it by the bedside, and advances towards Vesuvius</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>I wouldn't bother, John&mdash;he's not worth it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Worth it! Shooting about the place like that&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>I've got his gun&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Suppose we just drop him gently out of the window?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>If you do me any violence I'll have the British law on you. That vixen has bitten my leg as it is.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>What shall we do with him, Sir Victor?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>I should give him in charge.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Put him through the window.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>It's only a few feet&mdash;it won't hurt him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very well&mdash;go ahead.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Together they take the struggling Vesuvius towards the window</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>Here, let me go&mdash;what do you call yourselves&mdash;police! police!</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Carefully they drop him out, holding on to his coat end until he disappears. As he does so a large part of the garment comes away in Torian's hand</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">outside</hi>).</stage> <p>Here, give me back my coat. <pb n="26">Thieves&mdash;thieves! You've gone and ruined my coat, that's what you've done.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">going to the window, taking a bank&hyphen;note from his pocket</hi>).</stage> <p>Here you are <stage>(<hi r="italic">dropping the note to him</hi>),</stage> my good fellow&mdash;get a new one. And try another tailor.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">from below</hi>).</stage> <p>A fiver! Strike me pink.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Anything but red. Take my advice. Good day. <stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He moves back into the room</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>And now, Bull, back to bed.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Oh no, Sir Victor, not now I'm once out of it. Come, Britty, give me my things.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">He puts on his clothes&mdash;breeches, top boots, tail coat, and hat, Britannia helping. The conversation proceeds as he does so</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>It's very rash, my dear Bull, very rash.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not a bit of it, I'm right as the bank.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Really, Torian, you'ld do no good by keeping him in bed.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Well, understand, this injection business must be dropped.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>I can't honestly say he appears to need it now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">MacIlp has been studying an X&hyphen;ray negative from his pocket. He takes off his glasses, scrutinises them and cleans one <pb n="27">lens with his handkerchief, replaces the glasses and renews his study of the negative</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>Curious, very curious. I'm not sure that it is an ulcer after all. It seems to have disappeared. I think it must have been something on my glasses. Very extraordinary.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Then I take it, gentlemen, there's to be no more soothing syrup, no injection, and no operation. Splendid.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>I think, Sir Victor, it would be no bad thing if we let him go his own way for a time.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>A very sensible proposal, MacIlp.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Perhaps you're right. I shall be sorry to sever my connection&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not at all&mdash;not at all, Sir Victor. Nor you other gentlemen. I should miss you all very much, I should indeed. All those disputes of yours&mdash;I enjoy them&mdash;and then the new discoveries you are so often making&mdash;most entertaining. In any little trouble I shall always be most grateful for your help, gentlemen. But if I may say so without offence, would you remember that, after all, my interests are not wholly medical. I enjoy, I am glad to say, long periods of comparative health and vigour, when I find my thoughts hardly occupied by doctors at all. No offence, as I say. I shall <pb n="28">esteem your attentions, when I require them, Sir Victor, I shall be honoured if you will continue to accept the very inadequate honorarium of four hundred a year&mdash;and I should like to make the same arrangement with you other gentlemen&mdash;no, I will take no refusal. The events of this morning have shown me that in a crisis you are prepared to stay at no sacrifice in my defence. Believe me, I am sensible of the devotion.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi>.</speaker> <p>That's true. Sir Victor, I'ld like to apologise for what I said&mdash;and to you other gents. The way you faced that guy with the gun was fine.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Not guy&mdash;I beg you, Britannia; not guy from you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">John Bull</hi>.</speaker> <p>Very well, then. Now I'll bid you good morning. I think I shall take a stroll in Hyde Park&mdash;in the security of the sunshine. Join me, Britty?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Britannia</hi>.</speaker> <p>You bet.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">John Bull and Britannia move to the door</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>One moment, Bull, please. I feel strangely uplifted by the occasion. I have an unwonted impulse to sing something. My voice is a trifle rusty, I fear&mdash;but, Dacellew, you're good at that sort of thing&mdash;could you oblige us with a lead?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>Something Welsh?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>No, not Welsh. I think&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">trying the pitch</hi>)</stage> &ldquo;Rule&mdash;&rdquo;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="29">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>All right&mdash;wait a moment&mdash;you'll get the wrong note&mdash;take it from me&mdash;are you ready, MacIlp?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian, Lloyd and MacIlp</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">singing together</hi>).</stage>
<lyric><stanza><l>Rule Britannia,</l>
<l>Britannia rules the waves,</l>
<l>Britons never,</l>
<l>Never, never</l>
<l>Shall be slaves.</l></stanza></lyric></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">As they sing John Bull goes out in full sail, followed by Britannia. The three are left a little at a loss</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Yes&mdash;er&mdash;quite a demonstration, to be sure. However, once in a while&mdash;Dacellew, MacIlp, are you engaged for lunch?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>No, Torian.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>No, Sir Victor.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Then, will you join me at my club?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd and MacIlp</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">together</hi>).</stage> <p>Delighted.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>My car is outside. Or what do you say to walking? It might create a good impression if we were seen together.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Lloyd</hi>.</speaker> <p>A very good idea, Torian.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi>.</speaker> <p>I've no objection.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l">[<hi r="italic">Hands appear on the window&hyphen;sill, followed by the head of Vesuvius</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>Can I have my gun back?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="30">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Certainly not. Go away.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>It cost me half a quid.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>You're lucky it didn't cost you your neck.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>Of course&mdash;if you look at it that way. Mug's game, after all, isn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Decidedly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>I don't mind telling you I'm a bit fed up with it myself really. Think I shall give it the go by. And he's a toff, that fellow, I can't deny. That was a fiver he gave me. So long.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r">[<hi r="italic">He disappears</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Torian</hi>.</speaker> <p>Come along then. <stage>[<hi r="italic">They take their hats</hi>.</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The voice of Vesuvius</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">from below</hi>).</stage> <p>I say, you ginks.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">MacIlp</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">at the window</hi>).</stage> <p>What is it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Vesuvius</hi>.</speaker> <p>Listen,</p>
<stage align="l">(<hi r="italic">Singing</hi>)</stage>
<lyric><stanza><l>For he's a jolly good fellow,</l>
<l>For he's a jolly good fellow,</l>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The Three</hi> (<hi r="italic">taking up the refrain as they go out together</hi>).</stage>
<l>For he's a jolly good fellow</l>
<l>And so say all of us.</l></stanza></lyric></speech></pdiv>
</div2>
