ACT I <attbytes>62Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767001</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Laying the Devil. A Play in Three Acts</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1933</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">A comfortably furnished library</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l">A <hi r="smcap">Manservant</hi> <hi r="italic">brings in a tray with coffee, liqueurs, cigars and cigarettes, places it on a small table standing before the fire, and goes out again</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">A few moments later three men, wearing dinner jackets, come in. They are</hi> <hi r="smcap">Roland Benson</hi>, <hi r="italic">a fresh&hyphen;coloured, ample and cheerful man of forty&hyphen;two or so; he is a prosperous city merchant, on the livery of his company, and within sight of his mastership</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Louis Constantine</hi> <hi r="italic">and</hi> <hi r="smcap">George Fleming</hi> <hi r="italic">are his guests</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi>, <hi r="italic">aged forty, is a European who has adopted England with a perfect manner; his charm is a good deal more than skin deep</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Fleming, Hilda Benson's</hi> <hi r="italic">brother, with an engaging appearance, is robustly stupid, comfortably guided by sufficiently flexible rules. He is thirty&hyphen;five</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Help yourselves, will you. Hilda prefers it this way.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Shall we join the gentlemen, eh?</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">They supply themselves from the tray</hi>.</stage>
<pb n="10">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">offering</hi> <hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi> <hi r="italic">a choice of cigars</hi>):</stage> <p>No?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking a cigarette</hi>):</stage> <p>Thank you&mdash;I think not.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">They seat themselves</hi>, <hi r="smcap">Benson</hi> <hi r="italic">and</hi> <hi r="smcap">Fleming</hi> <hi r="italic">with their cigars</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking up a book from the couch on which he is sitting</hi>):</stage> <p>You admire Proust?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I? no&mdash;I mean that's Hilda's.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Queer fellow that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You read him, Mr. Fleming?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, hardly. But I like a book for ten minutes before going to sleep&mdash;something good, you know. Edgar Wallace or Conan Doyle. Down at Weyland Court last week the only blessed book in my room was one of that fellow's. A bit hard, wasn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I find him rather tedious myself. Excellent brandy this, Benson.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm glad you like it. A special lot I found last week.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Nothing is so consoling as good brandy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>What does a tough like you want with consolation, George?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>That's just where you're wrong. I have a great many troubles.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Nonsense.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>What's the good of saying nonsense? I lost two hundred yesterday on that infernal colt.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Surely that was easy to avoid.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>That's all very well, but Louise made a devil of a row about it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="11">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Louise&mdash;? Mrs. Fleming&mdash;ah, yes, charming.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not so jolly charming either if you want to know.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I thought decidedly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, if it comes to that, she is.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>She's been on the stage, she tells me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes&mdash;not properly&mdash;only at one of those repertory places. I only saw her act once&mdash;&lsquo;The Wild Goose,&rsquo; I think it was. Dismal affair.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Doesn't she miss it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not on your life&mdash;she has much too good a time.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>It's a poor game for a woman anyway.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>But how original of you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Original&mdash;what do you mean?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>To be original is merely to be out of the fashion. What you say is not fashionable. That is all.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>By Jove, yes&mdash;no&mdash;could you say that again?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Benson favours the caves&mdash;but why not?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Ha&mdash;ha&mdash;yes, I get you. Quite right. I always said you were a cave man, Rolly. But it doesn't go nowadays, you know. Oh no. You ask Louise. By Gad.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Louise is a darling. But an annual discipline in a cave would do her no harm.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not with me, Rolly my boy. No, sir. <stage>(<hi r="italic">To</hi> <hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi>.)</stage> That's American.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Remarkable people. Ruled by their <pb n="12">women, and full of delightful surprises in consequence.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You think women surprising?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Which means that you do not?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Hardly surprising. Difficult, yes&mdash;but the difficulties can be foreseen.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>An agreeable view. But&mdash;a secure one?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>A business man can afford to indulge no insecurities.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Rolly always backs the winner&mdash;don't you, my son?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Do not you English say it takes all sorts to make a world, Mr. Fleming?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, you needn't rub it in. The bally horse was two to one on.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Hilda&mdash;Mrs. Benson tells me she has bought two Paul Nash's. A very admirable artist. You English are so generous to foreigners&mdash;so apt to miss your own merit.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Please don't be apologetic, Constantine. Why not Hilda?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Indeed, why not? These compunctions are so stupid a veneer, are they not? I esteem your courtesy, Benson.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Louise is charming, and Hilda is&mdash;Hilda. By Jove, Mr. Constantine, you do see things, don't you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You flatter me, Mr. Fleming. I have been so many things, that I am sure in so few. Manners are so various, are they not?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Which are the manners that maketh man, Constantine?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="13">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>How nice of you. Constantine. It may be Fleming?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, George if you like. But which are they?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>They&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>The manners that maketh man?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Christ Church of Oxford, I believe&mdash;a European standard, of course. The manners, shall we say, that&mdash;that subdue women.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not bad for you. Subdue is good.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Do not misunderstand me. To subdue is to captivate.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>To control.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Ah, you mistake. We cannot control women. We can but give them value for&mdash;our money.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking another brandy</hi>):</stage> <p>Value for&mdash;? No,&mdash;gone to earth.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Your sporting idiom is enchanting. I mean that since most women are kept, most women desire to be reassured that they are not.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Why have you never married, Constantine?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Because I am so clumsy. I have been on the point of marrying three&mdash;no, four times, and always I have told too much.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, but never tell. Take it from me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I know. You are very wise, Fleming. But I respect women. So much, that I cherish a hope that one day I shall find a chaste one. So chaste that my errors will seem to her but something to be redeemed.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="14">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Do you call that controlling them?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>That would be their value for my money.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>What's this about money?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>We suppose that a woman takes our money as&mdash;you call it&mdash;a matter of course. She doesn't. She asks to be paid for taking it. It is right that she should ask it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You belittle the whole contract. A woman gives full value for every penny she receives.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I am your guest, my dear Benson. You give me a perfect dinner&mdash;your cook is a model, if I may say so&mdash;you embellish it with vintages that would honour a palate even more experienced than my own&mdash;you place me in most amusing company. I come as suitably dressed as I can contrive&mdash;I have bathed&mdash;I keep myself fresh in my conversation. But if you tell me that I have paid for my entertainment, shall I not be insulted?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>By Jove&mdash;a parable. I should have made a rotten disciple&mdash;always missing the point, you know.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You are indulgent to me, Fleming.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You mean that women don't wish to be reminded that they have been bought.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>More than that. They wish to be assured that they have not. Only the assurance must be given and taken subtly&mdash;by insinuation&mdash;without words.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't believe they think about it half as much as that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="15">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Many do not. But the finer ones.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, I'm not for bottling things up, agreeable or otherwise. Have it out, I always say.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Most intimacies are ruined by a disregard for reticence.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>There I can't agree. Once you keep things back, confidence is undermined.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Ah, you remind me of a board meeting, my dear Benson. But you mistake. Reticence does not necessarily imply secrecy. On the contrary, the more delicate the understanding, the more expressive does reticence become.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>A good point&mdash;for a debating society. But you haven't been married. Life isn't like that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Rolly's right. Marriage is a wrangle at best.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>And the most we can do is to keep the wrangling civil. It's no good looking on marriage as a trapeze act&mdash;it lasts too long.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>After all, as you say, I am so inexperienced.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The sound of women's voices outside precedes the entrance of</hi> <hi r="smcap">Hilda Benson, Louise Fleming</hi>, <hi r="italic">and</hi> <hi r="smcap">Betty Lingard</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi> <hi r="italic">is rather less than thirty, softer in manner than character, handsome and on level terms with life. If she has been careful not to outrun her husband, she does not esteem him the less for that</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Louise Fleming</hi> <hi r="italic">has had mild intellectual ambitions, which she has discarded in favour of</hi> <hi r="smcap">George Fleming's</hi> <hi r="italic">substantial income. She is never sure whether his somewhat <pb n="16">erratic good&hyphen;fellowship is value for a lost and, as she is convinced, distinguished career. But membership of several Sunday play societies is in fact a suitable outlet for her capacities, and she enjoys her money. She is twenty&hyphen;seven, dark, not notably good&hyphen;looking, but with some distinction</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Betty Lingard</hi>, <hi r="italic">of the same age, has vindicated her emancipation as a woman by not getting married, and spends most of her time in maintaining, to herself and in the public prints, that men aren't worth thinking about. She is fair, very pretty, and makes the most of her looks</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Louise</hi> <hi r="italic">and</hi> <hi r="smcap">Betty</hi> <hi r="italic">are smoking</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The men rise, and the party re&hyphen;groups itself within range of the fire</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>What's this Hilda tells me about China, Roily?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>It's only a possibility. I don't think I shall have to go.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>If Hilda goes, what about me as secretary?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm afraid it wouldn't run to that, anyway.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>It wouldn't even run to me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>China? How delightful!</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Delightful in the porcelain and bronzes of your cabinets, Constantine. Not so pleasant out there to&hyphen;day.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Bally old business rocky?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>No&mdash;our fellow out there has been letting us down, that's all. We shall be able to put it right from home though.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Risky thing, business.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not like the turf.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="17">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I say, cheese it, Louise.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>George, I wish you wouldn't.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I've got my Sung bottle after all, Hilda.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You mean to say you persuaded Sir James to sell?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. It came yesterday.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>What's that&mdash;something special?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>In my opinion, the finest to be found in Europe.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You had to pay, if I know the old man.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Eight hundred and fifty. I would have given double.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>A bottle? What is it&mdash;a gold one?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Porcelain, stupid.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>But eight hundred and fifty what? Francs?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Guineas.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I say, that's awful, isn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>It really is a beautiful thing, George.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>But eight hundred and fifty guineas. Old Penteridge only gave eight hundred for Brimstone, and it won the Derby.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>You do keep on coming to the 'osses, don't you, George?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>There are other things, you know, my dear.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>You can't tell me a bottle is worth more than a good horse. It isn't reason.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't quite follow your argument in this week's <hi r="italic">Ploughshare</hi>, Betty.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh&mdash;why not? It's plain enough.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="18">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I read Miss Lingard's article. Admirable, if I may say so.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Your point seems to be that with the economic independence of women, jealousy must become a discredited passion.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not only discredited, but obsolete.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>So I gathered. I don't agree.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>But surely Miss Lingard is right. It cannot survive an advancing intelligence.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>If I have something, and you take it away, what has intelligence got to do with it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>It may, for example, suggest to you that it was not so securely, so indisputably yours after all.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, suppose I pinched your bally old bottle, Constantine?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>If you can do so, my dear Fleming, you are welcome to keep it. I take ingenious precautions against such calamities.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You assert your right of property there, then?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>For so long as I can keep it, no longer. I should, shall I say, disdain to call in the police.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Don't put such things into George's head, Mr. Constantine.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Your husband would be ill&hyphen;advised to be tempted by such immunity, Mrs. Fleming. I am so much more competent than the police.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Because I backed a loser, do I qualify for burglary? And you bet Constantine would run for the police like anyone else.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="19">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't bet.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>All right.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Of course, I know, Rolly, your sort will go on holding out to what you call the last ditch. But the last ditch is nearer than you think.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't read or think much, I know. I'm too busy&mdash;I haven't the time. But all your thinking and reading covers only a fragment of our being. I can breathe, and walk, and digest my food and renew my tissues, and sleep and use my five senses as well as Ibsen or Einstein. Perhaps better. That has taken us all millions of years to learn, not a few terms in honours schools or a month in Fleet Street. You clever people think your intelligence so terribly advanced. You don't realise that all it amounts to is that we have all come together a good many thousand miles, and that on the way now and again someone steps out a yard or so in advance of the rest. Your intelligence distinguishes you for a moment like that. But we all go on breathing, walking, digesting, and so forth. And jealousy belongs to that mass activity, and all your fine little theories can no more control it than they can my balance when I stand up on my legs.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Three rousing cheers. That's as good as Bernard Shaw any day.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>George, don't be impious. You don't allow much for ambition, do you, Rolly?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>We're all ambitious, the whole race. Marvellously. Think what our ambition has led us to from the mud or whatever it was. I'm content with that&mdash;proud of it. Betty's article isn't inspired <pb n="20">by ambition, but by a wish to assert herself. The main stream always throws up these little eddies of&mdash;well, eccentricity.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Thank you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't mean it uncivilly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>But how drab a view of life, Benson. A sleek, unenterprising monotony. The artists all defy you. And your mass activity&mdash;how little you understand even that. Every commonplace soul of them all continually plumes itself on its own distinction. The new democracy, in teaching every man that he is as good as the others, has persuaded him that he is rather better. Have you observed mass activity on a dancing floor? Each incompetent performer shamelessly displaying his physical infirmities, in the conviction that all admiration is fixed on him. Does not each man in the street believe that he is <hi r="italic">the</hi> man in the street to whose judgment the daily press so constantly and touchingly defers? You are content, you say, with those cumulative achievements of the mob&mdash;proud to associate yourself with them, and asking no more. And yet your satisfaction, my dear Benson, in the assurance that you can deal with your defaulting manager in China from your ooffice in Lombard Street. You experience all the sensations of a Napoleon, you delight in them,</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Three more rousing cheers. The bottle is with you, Rolly&mdash;I mean the&mdash;the other old bottle.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>You must admit, Rolly, that's a real dig in your comfortable ribs. May I use that, Mr. Constantine?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="21">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>To be of the smallest service to an observer so enlightened&mdash;I should be honoured.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>You needn't be honoured. Thanks all the same.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>I can't see myself being jealous about anyone.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I can though, and don't you forget it, light of my life.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>George would have me watched on half a hint, wouldn't you, George?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'd do the watching myself&mdash;you bet.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>The tight rein snaps.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>It's the loose line that loses the fish. Not so bad that, eh, Rolly?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Nearer the mark than Constantine, at least.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You strong men can afford such doctrine. But so few are strong. Most of us have to practise diplomacy, even in our attachments.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>He's laughing at you, George.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Mrs. Fleming&mdash;I assure you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I say, Constantine, are you laughing at me?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>My dear Fleming, I would not be so indiscreet.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>All the same, that's just the trouble. You intellectual people think it's all something to laugh at. And half the decencies of life are discounted in consequence.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But are they?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Of course they are&mdash;look round you, everywhere.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="22">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I haven't noticed it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>There's the night clubs, and all that, you know.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Do most people spend their nights at night clubs? There must be several who don't.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Spirit of the age&mdash;you can't get away from it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Can't I?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>You know what I mean. There is a darn sight too much looseness about.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>More than there has generally been?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, rather.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>How do you know?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I mean to say&mdash;just look.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You mean just listen. It is so easy to be deceived by the advancement of professional gossip. We all know that life between two people must sometimes be difficult. But it is so seldom all difficulty, or even difficult at any point beyond solution. We make too much of the spectacular exceptions.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>But you don't suggest that they should be considered lightly, my dear?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Why consider them at all, if they do not concern us?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Isn't that rather ostrich&hyphen;like?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>The ostrich refuses to face a danger that he sees. I see none.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>You know, Hilda, you can't be as innocent as all that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What has innocence got to do with it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="23">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, what has it, George?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, to say there's no danger.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But is there?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Of course there's danger.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>For me?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, you know I don't mean that. Generally.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But what has generally got to do with me, or you, or George, or any of us? Generally means nothing. Nearly all the scares and scandals of the world are about things that are supposed, on no evidence, to be happening to other people. Just as nobody objects to anything but takes it for granted that everyone else does. &lsquo;Of course, I don't mind that sort of thing myself, but what will other people think?&rsquo;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>That's just where you're wrong, you see. I do object to that sort of thing myself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Don't be ridiculous, George. Hilda doesn't mean that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I was short&hyphen;circuiting, George.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, if we aren't to take any notice of these things, what is there left to talk about?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, talk by all means. But don't let us all assume when we talk that we are persons in the play ourselves.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Hilda's philosophy is exemplary.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>But you'll admit that ideas are advancing?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. Or changing. I read your article too. I liked it. I liked what Rolly said about it just now. I liked what Mr. Constantine&mdash;Louis&mdash;said. I think all of you are wrong.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="24">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Now that's something like. Another brandy&mdash;thank you. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He helps himself</hi>.)</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You say that jealousy must become obsolete, under the example of growing enlightenment. Rolly says that enlightenment will not affect it, that it belongs to a stable mass activity. Louis denies that mass activity is stable, attributing the desire for distinction not to exceptional minds, but to all. An amusing symposium. But I think that in theorising about jealousy you have all committed an essential oversight&mdash;to define what jealousy is.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Jealousy is&mdash;well, you know it as well as you know St. Paul's Cathedral if you see it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm inclined to think with you, George, that I should know it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I am not inclined to think. But I do know. There are two kinds of jealousy. One is tragic: the other is contemptible.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Might she not seduce the Athenian senators&mdash;or the officials of Ellis Island?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Seducing is not a pretty word, Constantine.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>George!</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>All right. Seducing.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Go on, Hilda.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You really want to know?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Indeed. The revelations of the divine&mdash;no, I mean it&mdash;the divine.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>In plain prose then?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Jealousy respects no persons. We had a butler who was jealous about a waitress in a Tottenham Court Road A.B.C. He is in penal <pb n="25">servitude. And Shakespeare was jealous also. We might, as a third example, suppose Rolly to be jealous about me. You gave me leave to speak, Rolly, in plain prose. And it is an example only. Wilkins&mdash;in penal servitude&mdash;and Shakespeare are tragic figures. Rolly, granted our supposition, would be contemptible.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes&mdash;do explain.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Wilkins loved his waitress. He neglected his duties here because of her, he bought all the gramophone records that he could find in a minor key. She walked out with him, and then he discovered that she was walking more ardently with a plumber from Walham Green. He caught them one night outside the Fulham Empire, and knocked the plumber headlong against a lamp&hyphen;post. Fortunately the plumber recovered, and Rolly's testimony to Wilkins's character induced a humane judge to make it three years only. Shakespeare was similarly deserted, it seems, for a rival poet. He worked off his feelings not in assault but sonnets. Wilkins and Shakespeare both lost something that was immeasurably precious to them, they were jealous with reason, they compel our pity. But if Rolly were jealous on account of me, he would be jealous out of some caprice in himself, without cause. No one else might know it, but I should know it. And I should despise him for it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>But why this, Hilda? Is it necessary?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm sorry.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="26">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>You haven't been playing green&hyphen;eyed, have you, Rolly?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I am not aware of it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>But if your husband incurred such displeasure, would you not seek to redeem him from his error?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I might.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Then it's all a matter of instinct, you believe?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Entirely. I think that Wilkins with his assault was mistaken, and Shakespeare with his sonnets right. But they are alike to be pitied. They knew they were wronged&mdash;they were, in fact, wronged, though it is futile to blame either the plumber or the rival poet. But to imagine yourself wronged when, in fact, there is no wrong done is to betray some natural vice in yourself that deserves no quarter. And if you get quarter it is due to uncommon luck or uncommon charity.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>And if your luck is&mdash;you call it&mdash;out, and the charity is witheld, you have but yourself to thank for any misfortune that may befall you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I think that is a just account.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>What the devil&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">quietly</hi>):</stage> <p>Rolly! Is your Sung piece as fine as Murato's, Louis?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Finer. It has a purer line at the base.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I beg your pardon. It was stupid of me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You should see it, Benson.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Such things aren't much in my line. Do have some more brandy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="27">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Thank you, no. I am still convalescing&mdash;one is my allowance.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Thank you, yes. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He fills his glass</hi>.)</stage> Really excellent for convalescence, you know.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>You had rather a bad time, hadn't you, Mr. Constantine? Pneumonia, wasn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Double. And the second time.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Tough fellow.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>But I hope you will allow me to show off my treasure to you, Hilda.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm longing to see it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>When may we say? Would a cup of tea to&hyphen;morrow be convenient?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Tuesday&mdash;yes, I'm free then.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Four&hyphen;thirty?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>That will be charming. Now if you will excuse me&mdash;no late nights at present.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Your car is here?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Thank you, yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Benson</hi> <hi r="italic">rings the bell</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi> <hi r="italic">takes his leave of the</hi> <hi r="smcap">Flemings</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">to</hi> <hi r="smcap">Benson</hi>):</stage> <p>An enchanting evening.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">comes in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Mr. Constantine's car.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>I think I must be going too. I promised to see Esther Clayton at the club. She wants me to go over her election address.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>May I drop you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="28">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>That's very kind of you. Albemarle Street.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi> <hi r="italic">goes out with her</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You are a lucky man, Benson. Hilda is a remarkable woman.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Indeed.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Ah, do not take it amiss. So few men are able to count on such intelligence to help them if they should blunder. I was congratulating you, sincerely.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Thank you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>My compliment is displeasing to you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>By the way, my wife must have overlooked it. I think she has an appointment to&hyphen;morrow.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh? I am sorry.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi> <hi r="italic">returns with</hi> <hi r="smcap">Betty</hi>, <hi r="italic">who has put on her cloak</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Your husband tells me that you have overlooked an engagement for to&hyphen;morrow afternoon. It is a great disappointment.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">after a glance at</hi> <hi r="smcap">Benson</hi>):</stage> <p>No&mdash;I think not. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Looking at a tablet on her desk</hi>)</stage> No, I'm quite free. What was it, Rolly?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I thought you told me there was something.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Then I may expect you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, four&hyphen;thirty.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">shaking hands</hi>):</stage> <p>Good&hyphen;night, Benson. You should not have alarmed me like that&mdash;it was too bad of you. Good&hyphen;night, Hilda.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="29">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Good&hyphen;night, Rolly. So long, George. See you on Thursday, Louise. Good&hyphen;night, Hilda.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">She goes out</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>If you should have to go to China after all, Benson, you must let me know. I have influential connections there myself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He follows her</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Damn his impertinence.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What's the matter, Rolly?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>The matter? Everything's the matter.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But I don't understand.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Our friend has just remarked on your uncommon intelligence.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">to</hi> <hi r="smcap">Louise</hi>):</stage> <p>You're going to the matin&eacute;e on Thursday?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. Are you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I hope so.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>What is it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>&lsquo;The Seagull.&rsquo; By Tchekov.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I say, look here, Louise old thing, I don't have to go, do I?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>You needn't.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Gee, Rolly, you should have seen the thing she took me to the other day. A jolly old cherry orchard or something. I thought my mind had given way.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Had it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, my pretty sister. It gave up the unequal contest and retired to sleep.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Who are you taking?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't know. I may ask Louis.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Why don't you come along, Rolly?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="30">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I happen to have a business to look after. Besides, I haven't been asked.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Don't be ridiculous, Rolly. I've asked you twenty times. Will you come?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, thank you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I can't make out what you women see in that fellow Constantine.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>He has brains.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Which Rolly and I haven't, you mean.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, Rolly has brains all right.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Thank you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What did you mean about my having an engagement?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>If you don't know I can't tell you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I shouldn't encourage a chap like that, Hilda.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What are you talking about, George?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, I know it's all right and all that. Still, there's something not too safe about him, if you ask me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Did anyone ask you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>George is right, the man's no use. I don't know what you want to ask him here for.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You're unreasonable, Rolly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, I've done my best to be civil to him, but after to&hyphen;night I'm through with it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But what did he do?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>If you must know, he was damned offensive.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I say, Rolly, not offensive.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, I don't care to be reminded of my wife's merits. I don't need reminding.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="31">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>I thought he put it rather shrewdly. I saw nothing offensive in what he said.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I did. Perhaps you don't understand, Louise.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>I see. I'm sorry. May I get my cloak, Hilda?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't know what Rolly means.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The two women go out together</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Fleming</hi> <hi r="italic">takes a whiskey and soda from a side table</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I say, don't get on edge about it, old son. There's no harm in it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I daresay not. But there's no good in it either. Good skating doesn't make thin ice thick. I give Hilda everything I can, and I do anything she wants me to in reason. I've been married to her five years, and I've never allowed myself to think of any other woman since. And I won't have any nonsense about this sort of thing, that's all.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Of course, I agree about Constantine, up to a point. But don't take too strong a line about it. It won't do to be suspicious about Hilda, you know.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm not so sure about that. I'm not blaming her, but I don't mean to let her make any mistakes. You've only got to look at Constantine&mdash;it's marked all over him. Do you mean to tell me that any woman doesn't know that perfectly well?</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi> <hi r="italic">and</hi> <hi r="smcap">Louise</hi> <hi r="italic">return</hi>, <hi r="smcap">Louise</hi> <hi r="italic">ready to go</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Good&hyphen;night, Rolly. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Shaking hands</hi>.)</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Good&hyphen;night. I didn't mean to be short.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="32">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Don't worry about me, Rolly. <stage>(<hi r="italic">At the door, as she kisses</hi> <hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi>)</stage> Good&hyphen;night, my dear.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">She goes out</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">with</hi> <hi r="smcap">Benson</hi>, <hi r="italic">at the fireplace</hi>):</stage> <p>Come to think of it, that was a rum thing he said about a chaste woman, wasn't it? Well, good&hyphen;night, old thing. Go easy. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He crosses to the door, and kisses</hi> <hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi>.)</stage> Good&hyphen;night, old girl.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He goes out</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi> <hi r="italic">goes to the desk, and opens a couple of letters</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Benson</hi> <hi r="italic">takes a whiskey and soda, and returns to the fireplace</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, Rolly, what is it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You know perfectly well.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You don't really object to my going to&hyphen;morrow.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I do.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But, Rolly, you've been like this two or three times before. If you go on, you'll make things very difficult.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I've set my face against your playing with fire. I shall continue to do so.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Don't you see that if I wanted to deceive you I could do it quite easily, and that I shouldn't go this way about it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't say you mean to deceive me. But a man like Constantine is dangerous, and you know it. You've seen too much of him. You may be content with small talk about your arts, but if you think he is you are mistaken.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="33">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I am content with it. And it means a good deal to me. I've never asked you for it, Rolly; I don't expect it from you, and after five years I love you none the less because I don't get it. But I like it. And for the rest, to put it plainly, I'm very well able to look after myself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>No woman is sure of that. Constantine knows that no woman is sure of it. He has probably proved it a score of times.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You seem to know a good deal about it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>No more than you do.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>My knowledge makes me secure, yours fills you with uncertainty&mdash;that's the difference.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Look here, Hilda, I adore you. You know that. If I can't share all your enthusiasms, I'm not jealous of them. But I am jealous of&mdash;of the power in a man like that&mdash;oh yes, it's there right enough; his life is guided by it. He lives for conquest, and if he were candid he would boast that he seldom lives in vain. Why, his rooms are enough to tell you&mdash;with their paraphernalia of lights and couches and curtains.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>That's childish, Rolly. Just because he has taste in matters that you don't care about.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>It's not taste, it's a trademark.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Of course, if you insist on being wilful.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I insist only on things going no further.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What do you mean?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't wish you to go to&hyphen;morrow.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Because you don't trust me?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't trust Constantine.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>It is the same thing. You must see that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="34">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>As you will. I don't wish it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>And what satisfaction will it be to you if I don't go? Won't you then have to say to yourself, &lsquo;I daren't let her&rsquo;? Would that be a possible position for either of us? If you have no faith in me, do you suppose that you can tie me up for the rest of our lives so that I may have no opportunity for betraying the faith that you haven't got?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Why generalise about it? Here is a specific thing that I don't want you to do, and for a very good reason. There's no sense in a young married woman going off alone to the flat of a man like Constantine. Everybody would tell you the same thing.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Everybody. And you talk about generalising. For that matter, everybody would tell me nothing of the sort. It takes more than an afternoon call in these days to make a scandal, even in the best City circles, Rolly. But in any case, we have to deal with ourselves, not with everybody. Are you afraid of my going?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I've told you&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No&mdash;are you afraid?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Very well, I am.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Then I must go.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Against my wishes?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Because of that. There could be no peace for either of us if I did not go now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Then, I will put it another way. I forbid it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="35">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, Rolly, it's no use doing that. Good&hyphen;night.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">She goes out</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Benson</hi> <hi r="italic">does not move for a moment. Then he mixes a whiskey and soda and drinks it. He takes up a book, opens it, and sits in front of the fire. He closes it again, places it on his knee, and sits motionless as</hi></stage>
<trailer><hi r="smcap">The Curtain Falls</hi>.</trailer>
</div3>
<pb n="36">
<div3>
<comhd3><idref>Z300767002</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
ACT II <attbytes>43Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767002</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Laying the Devil. A Play in Three Acts</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1933</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The following afternoon, shortly before half&hyphen;past four. A room in Constantine's flat</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The room is characteristic of an opulent connoisseur of the finest taste. It contains little, but everything is a choice example of its kind. A luxurious divan dominates the furnishing, and sets the note of beauty combined with comfort that is generally observable</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">In a prominent place stands a china cabinet, filled with collectors' pieces of early Chinese porcelain</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi>, <hi r="italic">perfectly dressed in a lounge suit, is fastidiously arranging flowers in a vase. This employment is interrupted by little feverish movements of physical apprehension; once he goes to a small cabinet for smelling&hyphen;salts</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">A Chinese</hi> <hi r="smcap">Manservant</hi> <hi r="italic">enters with a lacquer tray, on which are tea&hyphen;things. He places it on a table in the centre of the room</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Mrs. Benson is calling shortly. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Looking at his watch</hi>)</stage> Show her in. When I ring, bring in the tea. Otherwise I am not at home, and am not to be disturbed.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">The Servant</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He goes out</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="r"><hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi> <hi r="italic">takes a cigarette from a box. As he does so he coughs; he replaces the cigarette</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="r"><hi r="italic">It is still broad daylight, but he goes to the <pb n="37">window, and draws the curtains, then switches on the lights. The room is suffused with a warm glow of mellow and carefully distributed tones. He goes to the fire, and warms his hands, and again he coughs, as he continues to do at intervals</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">After a few moments the</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">opens the door, announces</hi> &lsquo;Mrs. Benson,&rsquo; <hi r="italic">and retires</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi> <hi r="italic">crosses to meet her</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>How charming of you. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Looking at her frock</hi>)</stage> And, how charming.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm glad you like it. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Crossing to the fire</hi>, <hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi> <hi r="italic">placing a chair for her</hi>.)</stage> You believe in early closing.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>The curtains? My treasures look so much better in this light. But if you prefer it&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">moving towards the window</hi>)</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh no, please don't. I'm sure you know best.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>We collectors like to make the most of our prizes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>There's real winter in the air to&hyphen;day.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Ah, tea. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He rings the bell</hi>.)</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You are coughing&mdash;not another chill, I hope.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>How tiresome of me. Indeed no, it is nothing. It was also rather cold last night.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You got Betty to her club all right?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. An intelligent girl.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I often wonder whether these intellectual women don't deprive themselves of more than they gain.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="38">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>These intellectual women&mdash;from you. Miss Lingard&mdash;yes&mdash;but it would compliment her to say that she has one half your intelligence, Hilda. And of what do you deprive yourself?</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">brings in the tea&hyphen;pot, which he places on the table</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You will find this welcome&mdash;there is nothing so genial as tea.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">moving to the table</hi>):</stage> <p>Where is the treasure? I'm so anxious to see it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>No&mdash;allow me&mdash;please stay by the fire. After you have had your tea. I must not bore you with my trifles.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">goes out</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi> <hi r="italic">pours out tea, takes a cup to</hi> <hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi>, <hi r="italic">then hands her bread&hyphen;and&hyphen;butter and so on as they talk</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>It could not bore me. I never tire of looking at beautiful things.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking a small bowl from the mantelpiece</hi>):</stage> <p>That is rather out of my period, but it was so fine I could not resist it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking the bowl</hi>):</stage> <p>It is good, isn't it? But I agree&mdash;nothing can equal the undecorated work for real quality.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">replacing it</hi>):</stage> <p>No, that is incomparable. You did not answer my question.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What question?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Of what do you find your intelligence deprives you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You attribute to me something that I don't claim.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="39">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>But why this diffidence? You know. Among your friends, for example, last night.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Last night? Oh yes, George and the others. I only said what I felt.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Precisely. But how few people are able to say what they feel&mdash;to say that, neither more nor less. It is the distinguishing mark of intellect. More tea?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, thank you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking her cup</hi>):</stage> <p>Will you smoke?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Thank you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Your husband, I fear, was a little displeased with me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I have been wondering about that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>How wondering?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I thought you must feel it. I wondered whether&mdash;well, whether you ought then to have renewed your invitation.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>But would you not then also reproach yourself for confirming your acceptance?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You see I didn't know at the time of things that had been said while I was out of the room. Also, at the time, I thought he was genuinely mistaken about my having an engagement for to&hyphen;day. I only learnt afterwards.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>That he looked upon me as an unsuitable host?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm afraid so.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>But that was a view which I was sure he held. I could not be expected to share it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Nor even, I being his wife, to respect it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>My dear Hilda, if I have learnt one <pb n="40">thing, it is not to waste energy in accommodating my mind to others that it finds&mdash;unsympathetic.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Do you resist them always, then?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>No. They do not exist for me. In their company I behave as an automaton.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I see, you despise them.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Indeed, no. I do not consider them. They may be more or less admirable than my own. I am not curious to decide.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Rolly has a strangely honest mind.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Ah, honest. I am sure of it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But he does not always see things very&mdash;very&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Comprehensively? I suspected that also.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>And yet, he should be able to. He is very considerate.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>The difference, you observe. You seek to enlighten&mdash;I disregard the darkness.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>He thinks the darkness is mine.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>But you know that it is his. Tell me, learning what you did after I had gone, why did you still come?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>It was necessary.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Your self&hyphen;respect?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No&mdash;his.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not that you wished&mdash;to see the Sung bottle?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>That too. May I?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>When you have answered my question.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>My intelligence, as you term it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. Of what does it deprive you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="41">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Of the right to neglect responsibilities. Or, rather, of an easy conscience in neglecting them.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>And yet you disregarded your husband's wishes, because it pleased you to do so.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I disregarded them because to have obeyed them would have been to neglect my responsibilities. It was just that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Am I to understand that in some obscure way you are using me as a moral occasion?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No. Please don't talk like that. I cherish your friendship&mdash;you should know that. It is Rolly's inability to realise what it means that troubles me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>His misconstruction of it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I wonder, is it that? Yes, I suppose so.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You mean, is it a misconstruction?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, no&mdash;we know it's that. But do I truly want to clear his mind for him, or do I merely resent his&mdash;lack of faith in me? Which is it really that troubles me?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Why engage yourself in such speculation? Does it matter?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I think so. To be right is so much finer than the desire to convince other people that we are right, isn't it? And yet how rarely are we content in our own satisfaction.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Might you not plead with yourself that there is virtue in satisfaction shared?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>That would be an easy plausibility, no more.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I hoped you might answer so. A <pb n="42">mind so incisive is a rare delight, Hilda, to an amateur of philosophy like myself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You quicken it for me, Louis. I really do think after all that I want his enlightenment more than I want any vindication for myself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>The misconstruction&mdash;are you so entirely confident that it is that?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What do you mean?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Suppose it not to be&mdash;we should hardly consider his claims to control us, should we? You said yourself that one could not blame the plumber or the rival poet.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>If we could suppose it not to be&mdash;then no. But as we cannot suppose it&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Might I not, in this atmosphere of propriety, indulge my fancy by supposing it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>After all, the propriety could, perhaps, be questioned?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Tea, at four&hyphen;thirty?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Malice would not be discouraged by that. But I do not question it myself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>And yet, who knows but that you should?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You are a little mysterious, aren't you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>The degrees of intelligence are infinite. I may assure myself that mine distinguishes me from&mdash;from whom you will, as yours does you. But one degree is no more proof than another against beauty. Though it may be able more fully to perceive it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Louis&mdash;I don't think&mdash;may I see the masterpiece, please?</p></speech></pdiv><pb n="43">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>By all means.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">He goes to the cabinet and turns on an interior light, which reveals the contents in their full beauty against a black background. In the place of honour stands a superb Sung bottle, nearly eighteen inches high</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi> <hi r="italic">follows him</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, that is magnificent.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>It can never have been excelled in plastic art.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Now, where is your intellect&mdash;its distinguishing mark? To say what one feels. How can we ever get near to saying what we feel about that?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>No. The subtle beauty escapes us always; it is indefinable. We can but be aware of it. And how many can do that? Hilda, I would ransack the world for such perfections, if I could but bring them to you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Enough of your gallantries, Louis.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I have employed gallantry, yes, often. I employ none now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You know its history?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Almost certainly loot. Old Sir James has had it more than twenty years. Even the income tax has its uses you see. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He unlocks the cabinet and opens a door</hi>.)</stage> One moment. You see those little metal lips along the shelves? To touch one of those would be to receive a rather less than fatal warning. You remember I cautioned your sporting brother. There <stage>(<hi r="italic">he turns off a switch behind the cabinet</hi>),</stage> now all's safe. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He takes out the bottle</hi>.)</stage> Divine, is it not? Feel the enchanted quality of that surface. <stage>(<hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi> <hi r="italic">places her fingers on it</hi>.)</stage> The <pb n="44">most delicate, the most mysterious of all sensations, touch&mdash;and here it is perfectly satisfied.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>It is exquisite.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Hold it. It is worthy of the caresses of even such hands.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, it is too precious. I should be frightened.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Why should you fear? You are so sure.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">He brings the bottle down to the table, holding it under a light standing there</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You see what I meant by the line of the base? That curve&mdash;the slight unexpectedness that avoids any touch of eccentricity. A consummate master guided that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>It is a joy to be able to share that fleeting moment of inspiration after two thousand years.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>It is the most satisfying vanity of all. It was so proudly done. He knew that just one here and there would recognise it. And now we together pay our homage.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Put it back. Lock it up again in its security.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">placing the bottle carefully on the table beside him, and moving a step towards her</hi>):</stage> <p>Hilda, why do we pretend in this way? You know that my love for you is&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Louis, Louis&mdash;you are spoiling it all.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You don't mean that&mdash;you know you don't mean it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Louis&mdash;I beg you. I would never have come if I had known.</p></speech></pdiv><pb n="45">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>If you had known&mdash;why even he, with so infinitesimal a mind, knew. Do you think that I can adore the wonder of a porcelain shape and be unmoved by&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">coming to the table</hi>):</stage> <p>Louis, Louis&mdash;why have you done this?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Why&mdash;why&mdash;why? Have you waited so long to learn? Has no one in this world's long history known you till now? Why have I done this? Because I have discovered you&mdash;I have made you&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Louis, listen. I am not made of stone. But you are pressing us both to the edge of ruin&mdash;blank, irretrievable ruin. It's not the world, not the opinion of the world, but ourselves. Should I be but one of twenty of your victories, I am not&mdash;you have shown that I could not be&mdash;as the others. If you had never known remorse, you would now. And for me, I should wake to&hyphen;morrow with all my foundations gone for ever. If I have been blind, forgive me, but at least, for both our sakes, believe that I am not blind now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I have known, I thought, all that is to be known&mdash;and now for the first time&mdash;Hilda&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">He makes a move towards her. She moves from him, and the Sung bottle is dislodged from the table, and lies in fragments on the floor. The incident arrests his mind for a moment, and in that moment the force of</hi> <hi r="smcap">Hilda's</hi> <hi r="italic">appeal makes its impact upon him. And at the same moment <pb n="46">the distress of an ill man makes itself evident; he at once controls it</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, Louis&mdash;how terrible.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>It is nothing&mdash;it was careless of me to leave it there.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">He picks up the shattered pieces, and puts them on the table</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But how dreadful&mdash;Louis, I am so sorry.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You should not be sorry. We have seen it. We shall remember. Do you wish now to go?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But what can I&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Whatever you have to say, let it be no word more about that. I shall keep the fragments as a token. Good&hyphen;bye.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Please, not yet. Perhaps we both have learnt&mdash;who knows how much? May I wait&mdash;a little?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>But of course. I think, perhaps, another cup of tea?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Could you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">ringing the bell</hi>):</stage> <p>I should enjoy one myself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">He collects the broken pieces from the table, and places them in a bureau drawer. He closes the cabinet and turns off the interior light</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">comes in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>More tea, please. Quickly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking the tea&hyphen;pot</hi>):</stage> <p>Yes, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Louis, may we talk as old friends?</p></speech></pdiv><pb n="47">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>As the oldest friends in the world.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Rolly told me that if I came here you would&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Endeavour to seduce you. How true to his kind.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But he was right, you see.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You did not believe him?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I thought it was despicable of him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You had so much faith in me?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>And so you were wrong. But your husband was wrong also.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>How?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Benson supposed that I should&mdash;how do you English put it?&mdash;attempt your virtue. How well he knew me. And he supposed that your virtue would be defeated. How little he knew you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">brings in the tea and, placing it on the table, goes out again</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi> <hi r="italic">moves to pour out the tea</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">taking the tea&hyphen;pot from him</hi>):</stage> <p>No, do let me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>If you please. As it might be after a long career of matrimony.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">pouring out tea for both</hi>):</stage> <p>Louis, will you let the past half&hyphen;hour be forgotten?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Forgotten? You do not believe that it can be that. But it shall be sealed in silence if you will. What then?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>In many things we understand each other. I am happy it should be so. But one thing I don't <pb n="48">expect you to understand. I love Rolly, and I don't think anything could destroy that love.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, I understand even that. I find it difficult to believe, but of you I will believe anything.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, there's more in it than that. Rolly couldn't see the loveliness of our poor Sung bottle, and he couldn't see that my love for him was his only security. But he does things, he plays straight, he gives me all he has, he supplies my needs&mdash;all but very few of my needs, Louis&mdash;more, shall I say, than you could. I share his devotion, even his thoughts, with no one. I give all I can in return, happily, with no sense of a bargain, because I love him. I am glad of this afternoon, since now I know how securely I love him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Glad only for that? Then, after all, I have served as the moral occasion.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Less that now than ever.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You may say that&mdash;but it seems so to me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But don't you see that this would have proved nothing to me if&mdash;if&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>If&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>If I had been indifferent to you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>You say that, and yet you will deny us both.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>To do otherwise would be to deny something far greater than a moment.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Heresy. What should life be, ever, but the moment?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>It is your view. It is an intelligible view, <pb n="49">I even respect you none the less for it, Louis. But it is not, it never could be, mine. If I should ever take such a moment, it could only be if I knew that I should never regret it afterwards. You may call that cold, or cowardly, but there it is.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not that. Unusual.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You do see, don't you, that it's not any fear of consequences&mdash;of opinion? I would face those if I were sure of myself. But this afternoon I know that I am as far as possible from being sure of myself&mdash;indeed, that I should lay up a life&hyphen;time of self&hyphen;reproach. I am not willing to do that. I like you, Louis. I think that perhaps&mdash;But I know that it would mean disaster.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>And so still your lesson is my loss.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Must it be that? Should I not inevitably have become a commonplace to add to your&mdash;successes? Shall I not now be instead your grateful, your affectionate, debtor?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>A new experience for me, eh?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Our experience, together.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Do you not suppose that I might yet persuade you, if I persevered?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I do not think that you will persevere.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>The reward is a very desirable one. But I forego it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Thank you, Louis.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>That is fantastic of you. And yet you shall thank me if you will. But, your husband, whom as you say you now know you so securely love. After this&mdash;escapade will he not call it&mdash;can you convince him of that?</p></speech></pdiv><pb n="50">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>That I cannot tell. But I have the knowledge myself to fortify me. You do not still regret it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>That I did not succeed? Eternally. That I have been of this service to you, so undesignedly? No&mdash;I could even send my ungrudging compliments to Benson himself. But will you now let me make my confession to you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Please.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>It is this. I am forty. At eighteen I was an accomplished graduate of intrigues. I have not been lacking in good fortune since. And until this afternoon I have never found a woman of this unfeigned virtue. Women who have made capital of their chastity&mdash;yes, many of them&mdash;it is even commoner than acquiescence. But you have shown me something that I never expected to see. I have passed the age of moral fervours&mdash;indeed, I never reached it. But I bow to you, humbly, as to the lady whom I took to be no more than a figure of romance.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>That should shame me. But it doesn't. I thank you. Now I must go. We shall meet still, I hope, and often.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Who knows?</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He rings the bell</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>And please be careful&mdash;your cough worries me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>It is kind of you. But I have no anxieties for myself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Don't say that. The oldest friends in the world, remember.</p></speech></pdiv><pb n="51">
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">comes in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Is there a taxi outside?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Show Mrs. Benson down. And then fetch the tea&hyphen;things.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He goes out</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">kissing her hand</hi>):</stage> <p>Good&hyphen;bye.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not good&hyphen;bye. I am so very sorry about&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">indicating the bureau</hi>).</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Please&mdash;not a word.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">She goes</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi>, <hi r="italic">increasingly troubled by the cough and a general malaise, goes again to the smelling salts; then he lights a cigarette. The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">comes back, and clears the table</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Did anyone call?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, sir. A Mr. Fleming.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Fleming?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>What did you say?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>:</speaker> <p>That you were not at home, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">consulting a telephone directory</hi>):</stage> <p>Mayfair 2096. Ring that number. Ask if Mr. Fleming is in. If so, put me through.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>And afterwards go upstairs and see if Dr. Gosforth is in. If so, could he come down to see me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, sir.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He goes out with the tray</hi>.</stage><pb n="52">
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi>, <hi r="italic">coughing with growing signs of distress, leans wearily with his arms on the mantelpiece. The telephone bell rings, and he takes up the receiver</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Is that you, Fleming? Yes, this is Constantine. I hear that you called on me. There was some foolish mistake&mdash;my servant misunderstood me. I merely said that I was not at home if a certain dealer called. I am sorry. What? To see the bottle? I should have been enchanted to show it to you, but alas, there has been an accident. Yes, broken. I'm afraid so. Yes, that was it, eight hundred and fifty. Your sister has just left. I'm so sorry we missed your company. It would have been delightful. Pray accept my apologies&mdash;I rang up as soon as I heard. Good&hyphen;bye.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He puts the receiver up</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">comes in, announcing</hi> &lsquo;Dr. Gosforth.&rsquo;</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Good evening, Gosforth. I hope I haven't inconvenienced you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Gosforth</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not at all.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I thought I had better see you. I'm afraid I've picked up a chill again.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Gosforth</hi>:</speaker> <p>So soon&mdash;but, my dear fellow, how unfortunate. Let me see.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He examines</hi> <hi r="smcap">Constantine's</hi> <hi r="italic">pulse</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not too good, eh? I feel cheap enough.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Gosforth</hi>:</speaker> <p>If you please. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Handing him a clinical thermometer, which</hi> <hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi> <hi r="italic">puts in his mouth</hi>.)</stage></p></speech></pdiv><pb n="53">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Gosforth</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, don't talk, please.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">He takes</hi> <hi r="smcap">Constantine's</hi> <hi r="italic">pulse again, watch in hand. Putting the watch away, he takes out the thermometer and reads it</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Gosforth</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. It's bed at once.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I expected it. May be pretty serious, I suppose?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Gosforth</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, we must be careful. After the time you've had. You ought to be building up now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi> <hi r="italic">gets a sheet of notepaper, and proceeds to write on it</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I want just to do this. I may as well do it before I turn in. Would you mind ringing the bell, Gosforth? It's my will. I want you to witness it for me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Gosforth</hi>:</speaker> <p>But, my dear fellow&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">laughing</hi>):</stage> <p>A precaution merely. Don't be alarmed. I have every confidence in you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">comes in</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>I want you to witness my signing this paper. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He signs</hi>.)</stage> Will you, Gosforth? <stage>(<hi r="smcap">Gosforth</hi> <hi r="italic">signs. To the</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi>)</stage> You write your name and this address just there. <stage>(<hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">signs</hi>.)</stage> Thank you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">goes out</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi> <hi r="italic">places the will in an envelope, directs it, and speaks as he locks it in a small cabinet</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>If anything should happen, tell Rigby and Spiller they'll find it in there, will you, Gosforth, there's a good fellow. And now?</p></speech></pdiv><pb n="54">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Gosforth</hi>:</speaker> <p>If you'll get into bed, I'll come down again in half an hour and look you over thoroughly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Constantine</hi>:</speaker> <p>Very well.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="smcap">Gosforth</hi> <hi r="italic">goes</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Constantine</hi> <hi r="italic">goes to the cabinet, turns on the light, looks at his china for a few moments, and turns off the light again. Then he takes a few pieces of the broken bottle from the drawer, and places them in a small enamelled box, and takes it with him into his bedroom</hi>.</stage>
<trailer><hi r="smcap">The Curtain Falls</hi>.</trailer>
</div3>
<pb n="55">
<div3>
<comhd3><idref>Z300767003</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
ACT III <attbytes>65Kb</attbytes><display>1</display><reflink></reflink><comcitn><ty>BOOK</ty><id>Z300767003</id><a1>Drinkwater, John, 1882&ndash;1937</a1><t1>Laying the Devil. A Play in Three Acts</t1><pbl>Sidgwick &amp; Jackson, Ltd.</pbl><y1>1933</y1><t2>Literature Online</t2></comcitn></comhd3>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The same as Act I</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">Five o'clock in the afternoon, two days later</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi> <hi r="italic">is writing at her desk</hi>.</stage>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">comes in, announcing</hi> &lsquo;Mr. Fleming,&rsquo; <hi r="italic">by whom he is immediately followed</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Fleming</hi> <hi r="italic">kisses his sister</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Hullo, old girl.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Good&hyphen;afternoon, George.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Just passing; thought I might as well drop in, get a cup of tea, you know. A bit late, though.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Would you like something else?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, I don't so awfully much mind if I do. Bit nippy outside.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Help yourself. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He does so</hi>.)</stage></p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Thanks. Not a habit, you know, in the afternoon. But it is nippy, isn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Quite sharp.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. Cheers you up, don't it? You look as though a peg would do you no harm, old girl. Anything wrong?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm very anxious.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Quite so. Anxious bally old world. Could I telephone?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Certainly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">at the telephone</hi>):</stage> <p>Park 9821. Yes. Hullo<pb n="56">&mdash;that you? George speaking. What's won the three&hyphen;thirty? What? <stage>(<hi r="italic">Replacing the receiver</hi>)</stage> Damn. What's the trouble?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Louis Constantine is very ill.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh? What's up?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Pneumonia.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>By Jove, that's rough. Third time of asking, what? Will he be able to stand that?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>They are afraid not.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>When was he taken ill?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>On Tuesday night.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>After you left?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>By the way, how did Rolly take it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Your going.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>He hasn't mentioned it since.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>H'm. And now it's Thursday. What do you make of that?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>He's angry about it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Does he know about the illness?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Have you&mdash;called?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No. I've rung up. They won't let anyone see him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Queer, lonely sort of a beggar, isn't he, for all his money?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Very, I should think.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>What are his people? Has he got any?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I never heard him mention them.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Are you going to speak to Rolly, or leave it at that?</p></speech></pdiv><pb n="57">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>We shall have to deal with it, of course.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Good fellow, Rolly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>It's all right, George, I know that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Quite&mdash;quite. But I'd hate it if you and he fell out.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't think we shall, really.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm no one to come the moral stuff. But I've always thought of you as just the best that ever happened, and I like old Rolly&mdash;real white man. It's always seemed to me that you two were safe. I'm a bit of a hop&hyphen;skip myself&mdash;nothing much you know&mdash;but never feel too sure of myself, and somehow you and Rolly seemed dead certs and&mdash;well, it gave me a lot of comfort.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I think we shall go on being&mdash;safe.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Look here, old girl, you're my sister, and all that sort of thing, but I don't want to interfere. But I've got this thing on my chest. I couldn't tell one horse from another at Newmarket yesterday because of it. What are you going to tell Rolly?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What do you mean? The truth, of course.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Do you think that's best? You'll never get a fellow like Rolly to see it&mdash;I shouldn't see it myself. He's lengths in front of my class, I know, but we feel pretty much the same about that sort of thing. I wouldn't risk it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What are you talking about, George?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, I may as well out with it. I called at Constantine's place on Tuesday afternoon.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You did? When?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>About four&hyphen;forty&hyphen;five.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But I don't understand&mdash;I was there then.</p></speech></pdiv><pb n="58">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I know. His servant, that Chink fellow, told me that his master was not at home.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But that was absurd&mdash;there must have been some mistake.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>So Constantine tried to explain. But I don't think there was any mistake.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>George, what are you saying? How do you mean, explained?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>When you left he must have heard from the Chink what had happened. Anyway, directly I got back home he rang me up. Said his servant had misunderstood his orders. Bland as old Nick about it, he was. But that won't do for a story.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But you don't mean to suggest&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I only suggest that when a fellow like Constantine with a woman in his flat gives instructions that he is not at home to callers, it's difficult to put it in a way that will satisfy&mdash;well, a fellow like Rolly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>This is monstrous of you, George.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>It's no use talking like that, old thing. You've got to be reasonable.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What made you call?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>My intention was a good one, honest. I knew on Monday night that Rolly was upset about your going. I thought it was rash of you myself, but I backed you to come through all right. I decided I would call while you were there&mdash;I was going to say I wanted to have a look at that bally old bottle. I was pretty sure I should find everything all right, and then if Rolly made a fuss I could put in a word that would ease things up. But now <pb n="59">the devil of it is, you see, that I found everything all wrong.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Are you going to tell Rolly about this&mdash;about your calling?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't want to tell him. Whatever happened, I'd never let you down. But I wish to God I'd never been near the place.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Do you believe that I gave myself&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Look here, don't say things point blank like that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But do you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, it does look jolly difficult, doesn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Perhaps it does.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I mean, Constantine giving those orders makes it clear what his intention was, at any rate. Well, if you turned him down, I don't see you being very anxious about him afterwards. And yet you say you are. You've been ringing up. Can you expect me to make anything else of it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, I suppose not.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, don't cut me off like that, old girl, I'd give anything to see I've lost the line.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I can't tell you what happened on Tuesday. And if I could, you wouldn't understand. I don't mean that unkindly, George, but it's just a plain fact. Very few people could understand it. But I don't want to lose your faith in me. We're less like each other, I suppose, even than most brothers and sisters. But I'm very fond of you, and I know you're fond of me. Have you ever had reason to doubt my word?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, I'd risk my last shot on that.</p></speech></pdiv><pb n="60">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Then I can't explain, but if you will take it, I will give you my word that I've never been unfaithful to Rolly in act or thought.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Good enough. I'm satisfied. Rock of ages. But now, what about Rolly?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I've got to try and make him take my word, too.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, good luck, my dear. I hope you won't take a spill. If you want my tip you'll tell him&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Benson</hi> <hi r="italic">comes in, carrying some papers which he puts on his own desk</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi> <hi r="italic">rises to meet him. She kisses him; he responds, with constraint</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Fleming</hi> <hi r="italic">man&oelig;uvres himself across the room uneasily</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Hullo, Hilda.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You're early, Rolly. Would you like some tea?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, thank you. Good afternoon, George.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Afternoon, Rolly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Have I interrupted&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Rather not. Oh no, old chap, not a bit of it. Has he, Hilda?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">going back to her desk</hi>):</stage> <p>What could there be to interrupt?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">at the fire&hyphen;place</hi>):</stage> <p>No&mdash;I just thought&mdash;well, it's no matter.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What brought you home so early, Rolly?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I wanted to talk to you before we go out.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, I'd better be off.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, don't go, George. I would rather you stayed, if you can.</p></speech></pdiv><pb n="61">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Of course, if&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Please, George, if Rolly wishes it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I thought you were going to the matin&eacute;e.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. I changed my mind.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I see. Any particular reason?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I didn't feel like it. Louis Constantine is worse. It's critical.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>That is candid of you, at least.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Did you expect me not to be?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>How could I tell?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>If you haven't learnt after five years, Rolly&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Things have been known to change, even after five years.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>It isn't a good moment for irony.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, rotten, if you don't mind my saying so.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You may say anything you like, George, if you'll say nothing but the truth.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I say, what have I done wrong?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Nothing, I hope.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Quite right, of course I haven't. I'ld own up like anything if I had.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Perhaps, in view of your anxiety, Hilda, you don't feel equal to discussing the matter just now?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>The matter?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>The matter?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>The matter.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You mean&mdash;yes, I have been waiting. I would rather wait no longer.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I didn't speak on Tuesday night or yesterday, <pb n="62">because I wanted to give myself time. I thought that perhaps I might see it differently. I don't.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You went to Constantine's flat against my wishes, against my orders. What happened there?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I had tea. I saw the Sung bottle. I came away.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>No more?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>We talked.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>About porcelain?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>And what else?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Rolly, we all know perfectly well what your questions mean. You are mistaken.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Are you sure of that?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You are mistaken.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Constantine made no attempt&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>There was nothing&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Please answer my question. Did Constantine&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Rolly, can't you take my word?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't think I can.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I think you ought to, Rolly, you know. Hilda's is a pretty good word.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>There was nothing that you wouldn't wish me to know?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I have told you the truth.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Then why was George told when he called that Constantine wasn't at home?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Here, I say, what's that? <stage>(<hi r="italic">To</hi> <hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi>)</stage> I say, old thing, I never said a blessed word to a soul.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Hilda knows about it, then?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="63">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>That's what George was here for.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>But Hilda convinced me about it, you know. Oh yes, absolutely. <stage>(<hi r="italic">To</hi> <hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi>)</stage> Honest, I never told anybody. Not even Louise.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You needn't assure her of that, George. I found out for myself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>By Jove.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>On Tuesday afternoon I couldn't stand it. I determined to go and make certain about it one way or the other, or as certain as I could. I took a taxi. About twenty yards from the door, I saw George ringing the bell. I stopped the driver, and watched. A Chinese servant came to the door. I couldn't hear, but what happened was plain enough. You asked if Mr. Constantine was at home, George, and you were told he was not; you asked again, and then you went away. My first impulse was to have it out there and then, but I saw that it would mean a futile scene at best, even if I could have got in, which was unlikely. Besides, by then I had prepared myself for the truth, whatever it might be. I was only fixed on finding out what it was. And then I knew.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, you see&mdash;I mean to say&mdash;it's as clear as daylight, isn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm afraid it is.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, not that sort of daylight, not at all. I mean the other kind, you know. Now Hilda assures me&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Be quiet, George, there's a dear. Rolly, is there anything that could convince you that you're wrong?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="64">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I've been asking myself that for forty&hyphen;eight hours. And, frankly, I don't see what could.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You must allow that there is some chance, however small, that in fact you are wrong. Well, suppose that chance, in fact, to come off. You mean to say that nothing could save you&mdash;us&mdash;from this mistake which there would be no mending, ever?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Do you think I don't see how ghastly it is?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Why won't you simply take my word?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Because I have a common power of reasoning.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Don't trust it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>What else is there to trust?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>That's the tip, Rolly, right enough.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Will you answer any questions I ask?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>If I can.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You can if you will. Why did Constantine give orders that he was not at home?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>He did explain that to you, George, didn't he?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes&mdash;the Chink fellow misunderstood what he said. Some touting dealer he wanted to keep out.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You don't believe that, do you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, rather.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Of course you don't.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Have it your own way. Only don't say I didn't tell you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Why did he give those orders?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I didn't know he had given them.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>That makes no difference. He did. Why?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="65">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>He said nothing to me about it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>But didn't he do anything that might lead you to suppose why he gave the orders?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I tell you&mdash;Rolly&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Of course he did&mdash;you know he did.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I say, you know, I really think I ought to go.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, Rolly wanted you to stay&mdash;now I would rather you stayed&mdash;I've nothing to hide&mdash;nothing for myself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You admit it then&mdash;that he did make it clear why he should not wish to be disturbed, and you suggest that he wasn't successful&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I did not say that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You have nothing to hide, for yourself. What else does that mean? And if it does mean that, Hilda, it doesn't sound too pretty. Because if that were the case, you would feel, shall we say, a little distant towards him afterwards. But you don't. You confess your anxiety. Doesn't it almost look as though you were not being quite loyal to your partner in&mdash;indiscretion?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I told you, old girl. That's where the wire is.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You don't think it possible that there might be a loyalty due to Louis consistent with my loyalty to you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't propose to consider that. Accommodation is not part of my code.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Rolly, once for all, if you insist on talking or thinking like that, you'll wreck us both. I've <pb n="66">given you my word that your suspicion of me is utterly groundless. You might at least know that if I wanted to go elsewhere, I should, without lying to you about it. But I don't, because I have found no one who could take my love from you, even a share of it. Nothing could send me away from you but your own folly. Are you going to let it do that?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Is it folly to know black from white?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>It is folly to think you can tell black from white in the dark. You are in the dark, and you won't let me light it for you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">suddenly losing his bearings</hi>):</stage> <p>George, old man, what am I to do?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Good. Now that's talking. Why, believe her, of course.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>If I could&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Will this help you? If I knew all I know now, and could foresee just this pitiable breach between us, and had to make again the decision that I made on Tuesday night, I would make it as I made it then.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh no, that's aiming at the bunkers.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Hilda, you wouldn't let me down, not like this, would you? And yet&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Rolly, you've got to know that I'm right with you, know it in your heart&mdash;know I'm that because I want to be and not because I'm afraid not to be&mdash;you've got to know that, or our life together is ended.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes&mdash;yes&mdash;I'll try to see it so. I will try. Help me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Splendid fellow. So that's all right.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="67">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>And yet, how can I get clear&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Steady, son, give yourself a chance.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Please&mdash;let us help each other.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>All right. It's a deal. There's this about it, anyway&mdash;I care for nothing but you in it all, Hilda. A break up would queer things for me in the city&mdash;I mean my mastership and all that. But I've never given it a thought. I'ld never have supposed it could mean so little. I want peace in my mind about you, and nothing else seems to matter. I'll believe anything to believe you&mdash;there.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">comes in, and announces</hi> &lsquo;Mrs. Fleming. Miss Lingard.&rsquo; <hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Hilda dear, have you heard?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Tell her, Betty.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Mr. Constantine. He is dead.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Dead?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. I called to enquire on the way from the theatre. He was so kind to me the other night, and when I heard that he was ill, I&mdash;it doesn't seem possible, does it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Louis Constantine.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm sorry.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>And only two nights ago&mdash;poor blighter. It's enough to scare a fellow.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>When?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>About two this afternoon.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Who was there?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>I saw a Chinaman. He said the doctor and a lawyer were there, I think.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="68">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Could I&mdash;I wonder if I could do anything. No, of course not.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Thank you, Rolly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, they can say what they will, I liked him. And whatever he was, he has paid for it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Whatever he was&mdash;how?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, you know how people talk.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Had he many friends?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't think I've met his friends&mdash;except here, of course. But I liked him.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>After all, a man as attractive as that doesn't need to justify himself, does he? He gives value by being what he is&mdash;different. Bad reputations don't often bear scrutiny any more than good ones.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>I liked him. I was to have gone to lunch with him on Sunday. The day after the day after to&hyphen;morrow. I wouldn't have cared what anybody said. Here, what am I talking about? It has upset me, this, dreadfully.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Hospitable sort of fellow.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Why not?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, of course&mdash;first rate thing to be.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>You didn't really like him, Rolly, did you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not quite my sort, perhaps. A good mind, though.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>A good heart. A very chivalrous man.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>You got on all right with him, Hilda. Anyone could see that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, Betty, I liked him too.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, I said some things about him that weren't any too good. Can't say I love myself for that now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="69">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Death doesn't deal very fairly by our prejudices, George. It blunts the argument. <hi r="italic">De mortuis</hi>&mdash;and so we have to forget.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You were being so generous, Rolly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Was I? Yes, I must remember. I mean to&mdash;truly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Betty</hi>:</speaker> <p>Good&hyphen;bye, everyone.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r"><hi r="italic">With no more than that she goes out, unable to conceal an emotion that she does not wish to show</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>That was a sudden intimacy, wasn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>If it comes to that, I don't know why a bachelor should be expected to be a monk. If monks were bachelors&mdash;so to speak.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Betty's independence takes her the common way of servitude. No sentiment for her, and she thinks of nothing else. Poor girl, she lost her heart to him at sight. She ought to marry some steady, vigorous nonentity.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Like me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>I wouldn't call you altogether steady.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>But otherwise, like me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">The telephone bell rings</hi>. <hi r="smcap">Benson</hi> <hi r="italic">answers it</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Hullo. Yes. This is Mr. Benson speaking. Mrs. Benson? Yes, who is it? What, the solicitors? Just a moment. <stage>(<hi r="italic">To Hilda</hi>)</stage> Rigby and Spiller want to speak to you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>To me?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But who are they? <stage>(<hi r="italic">She takes the receiver</hi>.)</stage> Yes. Yes, this is Mrs. Benson speaking. Yes, Hilda Benson. To see me&mdash;what is it about? Mr. Constantine? Who is it speaking? Can't you tell me on the telephone? I see. Yes, I could, if you <pb n="70">think it necessary. How long shall you be? Oh, you're there now&mdash;well, it's only a few minutes by car. Very well.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">She puts the receiver up</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>What is it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Louis Constantine's lawyer. He said he wanted to see me at once. What was the show like?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>Poor production. Ducarel seems to be losing his touch. Interesting, though. You didn't turn up.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>I've got a meeting of the I.P.s. at six o'clock. You're dining at the club, aren't you, George?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, I meant to. Anything I can do?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Louise</hi>:</speaker> <p>No. If you see Basil, ask him to tell Joan I'm putting her name up this evening. Good&hyphen;day, Rolly. Sorry, Hilda, about this. <stage>(<hi r="italic">As</hi> <hi r="smcap">Benson</hi> <hi r="italic">goes to the bell</hi>)</stage> No, don't trouble. I can let myself out.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">She goes</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I shan't remember, you know. That's why she told me. Handing me my daily bad deed.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>What are the I.P.s?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>The Independent Poets. Funny sort of stuff they write&mdash;not that I ever read it&mdash;Louise doesn't think I'm up to it. I must say they don't get it printed&mdash;that's what they're independent of, I suppose.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>By the way, George, I've got those certificates for you. They're in the safe&mdash;I'll fetch them.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He goes out</hi>.</stage>
<pb n="71">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I think he's all right now, don't you?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>He's trying very hard.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I know.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You do believe me, don't you, George?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>All the way. I think Rolly does.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not quite&mdash;yet. But he's going to.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I'm damned sorry about Constantine&mdash;I mean if you are. I suppose if I had been told it was going to happen I should have said it would be the best way out, but somehow I don't feel that about it after all. Must be because I do believe you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, it doesn't settle anything.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Don't let it cut you up.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I shall miss him very much.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>What does the lawyer fellow want?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>He didn't say. I think it must be about Louis' catalogue. He told me the other day that proofs were coming and asked me if I would read over them. He was spending about three thousand pounds on it. It was to be the best ever printed in Europe. Poor fellow.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>The old bottle got broken&mdash;he told me on the telephone that day.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. What did he say?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, only that. When I said I'd thought I should like to see it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Benson</hi> <hi r="italic">comes back. He hands an envelope to</hi> <hi r="smcap">Fleming</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>There they are.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Thanks. Two bob down already, I see. My luck is out this year.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>They'll be all right. I don't think anything can stop them.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="72">
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">enters</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">handing a card to</hi> <hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi>):</stage> <p>Gentleman says you wish to see him, Madam.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Show Mr. Spiller up.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Servant</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, Madam.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He goes</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I mustn't hang about any longer.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>No, stay and see what it is, George. You'll only be wondering if you don't.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Honour bright, I don't want to nose about&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">announces</hi> &lsquo;Mr. Spiller&rsquo; <hi r="italic">and goes</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>Mrs. Benson? How do you do. Kind of you to see me at such short notice.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>My husband. This is my brother, Mr. Fleming.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">to</hi> <hi r="smcap">Benson</hi>):</stage> <p>How do you do. <stage>(<hi r="italic">To</hi> <hi r="smcap">Fleming</hi>)</stage> How do you do.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Do sit down, please.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He does so at the table</hi>, <hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi> <hi r="italic">by him</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I shall be in the way&mdash;?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>Just as you wish, Mrs. Benson.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Please. What is it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>You have, perhaps, heard of the death of my client, Mr. Louis Constantine?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. A friend who called came on to tell us.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>Quite so. Very sudden, very sad, very sad indeed. A charming and accomplished gentleman. I was summoned by his doctor this afternoon. The end came about two o'clock, it seems. Mr. Constantine's affairs appear to be in perfect order. <pb n="73">I found no will, but this envelope addressed to you, with, as you see, instructions for immediate delivery in case of my client's death. Hence my somewhat, I fear, unceremonious telephone message.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">He hands the envelope to</hi> <hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi>, <hi r="italic">who opens it, and takes out two other envelopes</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">from one envelope</hi>):</stage> <p>&lsquo;Will.&rsquo; <stage>(<hi r="italic">From the other</hi>)</stage> &lsquo;Hilda Benson. To be opened before inspection of my will.&rsquo;</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">She opens the second envelope, takes out a letter and reads it</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>How strange. <stage>(<hi r="italic">To</hi> <hi r="smcap">Spiller</hi>)</stage> You must see this.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="smcap">Spiller</hi> <hi r="italic">takes the letter, and begins to read</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>My husband had better hear it, please. It's all right, George; you can stay.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">reading</hi>):</stage> <p>&lsquo;Hilda Benson. I know it is nearly all over with me. With this you will find a will. When you have read it you are free to decide whether you burn it or put it into operation. If the latter, old Spiller will act as executor. If the former, my money will lapse to a ruffian of a cousin who makes bad cigarettes somewhere in the Balkans, if they can find him. The option is unconditionally yours. In either case I want you to know that I do this because you alone in my acquaintance with women have shown yourself to be at once beautiful, passionate, and chaste.&mdash;Louis Constantine.&rsquo; It is dated Wednesday&mdash;yesterday morning.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">handing him the will</hi>):</stage> <p>Please read that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">opening it</hi>):</stage> <p>&lsquo;I wish Hilda Benson, of Melton Square, London, W., to supervise the <pb n="74">publication of my porcelain catalogue should I not have done so at the time of my death. And I bequeath my entire estate to the said Hilda Benson.&rsquo; He names me as executor. The will is duly signed and witnessed, and dated as recently as Tuesday last.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">slowly and quietly</hi>):</stage> <p>My God!</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>A remarkable case. Very remarkable. But that is not my concern, which is merely a professional one.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>The decision rests with me?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>Clearly. <stage>(<hi r="italic">Glancing over the papers</hi>)</stage> Yes&mdash;it is quite regular.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>What&mdash;er&mdash;I beg your pardon.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, George, what is it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>I mean&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh yes. Do you know anything about the estate, Mr. Spiller?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>From a rough calculation I should say that, after death duties and outstanding liabilities have been paid, it will amount to something like two hundred and twenty thousand pounds.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>What! Oh, my Lord&mdash;two hund&mdash;<stage>(<hi r="italic">He takes another whiskey and soda</hi>.)</stage> Well, if that doesn't beat the band.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I don't know anything about the procedure in these things. This is an entire, almost an overwhelming surprise to me, Mr. Spiller. I must have a little time before I decide anything.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>Very natural. I will telephone in the morning. I could then come to see you, or you might prefer to call at our office. The address is on my card.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="75">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But I may say that I don't think I shall wish to take the money.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Hilda! I mean&mdash;yes&mdash;no&mdash;but I say&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>Of course, Mrs. Benson, it is not for me to express an opinion. If you allow the will to stand, I shall at once proceed with the necessary formalities as executor.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>The will would be published&mdash;in the papers, I mean?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>Probably. It has the elements of sensation in it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>And if I burn it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>Enquiries will be instituted for the next of kin, if any. I understand that Mr. Constantine had no relatives in England.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I see.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>And I will ring up in the morning. Would ten&hyphen;thirty be convenient?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. You leave the will with me, I take it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>In the circumstances, it is in order to do so. Then I need trouble you no further now. Good evening, Mrs. Benson.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="smcap">Benson</hi> <hi r="italic">rings the bell</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Good evening. Thank you for coming.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Spiller</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not at all. Professional duty. Good evening, gentlemen.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="italic">The</hi> <hi r="smcap">Servant</hi> <hi r="italic">comes to the door, and they go out together</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>What in heaven's name does this mean Hilda?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="76">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>The jolly old letter makes it plain, doesn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Who can be expected to believe that? Constantine must have been simple if he supposed juggling like that would deceive anyone.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Astonishing business&mdash;but I don't see why we can't believe what he says&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Be quiet, George.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, all right&mdash;I'll go.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You will not. You will hear this out. Rolly, here and now we are going to make a decision terribly important to us both.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>A cool quarter of a million.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>It's much more than that. Until this happened, Rolly, you said you were going to believe me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I meant to. I meant to smother my reason and take your word.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But why not still?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Even my smothered reason isn't extinct. A man doesn't leave a quarter of a million to a woman for nothing.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But he tells us why.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>He tells me what isn't sense.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Rolly, the decision is going to be made now. For me, it's a choice. Between this money and you. I want it to be you, but it is on you that it depends. If I have your faith, wholly, without reservation, then my choice is you, and the money will go. Of course, it would have to go. Without that faith, I want no more of you, Rolly, and then I may as well keep the money that, rightly or wrongly, has destroyed it.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="77">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>I am being destroyed.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Now, ask all your questions. There's no longer anything to hide.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>No longer? There was then?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>In a way, yes.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>And why no longer?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Because now Louis has given me leave to speak.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Then answer that. Why has he left you this money?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I tell you&mdash;he says&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>But why repeat that&mdash;why?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You think the explanation impossible?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, isn't it?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Then you think such a reward for virtue, for chastity, would be a miracle? That adultery only could deserve so great a price?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">after a moment's pause</hi>):</stage> <p>Yes. Straight down the fairway, Rolly my boy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">to</hi> <hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi>):</stage> <p>I shouldn't have thought of putting it that way.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But I do. What is your answer?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>It doesn't commonly happen like that.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not commonly&mdash;but any the less reasonably? Louis made this will when he knew his danger; he confirmed it when he knew he was dying. At worst, you can't believe that our intimacy was a long one, even that it began before last Tuesday. Would he, or any man, facing death, leave his fortune to the partner in one of many such occasions? If I was his mistress, of so short standing, do you suppose there were no others to share his liberality?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="78">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>On the green in two.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>What other motive could there be?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Then it is for that, and that alone, that you would have given all you had?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Holed out in three. The form's too good.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Questions like that don't help us.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>But they do, because you know you can't answer them. There is no answer.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Well, answer mine. If that wasn't his inducement, what was?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>You heard his letter.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You seriously stand by that?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Every word of it. If you love me, Rolly, and will be candid in your own heart, you cannot but see that there is the truth&mdash;that it could be nothing else. What do you suppose a moment's possession was worth to Louis Constantine? Wouldn't he have paid for that at his common rate, if he had wished to humiliate me at all? Dying, would he remember such a moment, even the latest of them, above all else? Would that have commanded the full, the undivided bounty of his gratitude? Would it not, must it not have been something more, something rarer than that? Can't you see that his letter is a last testament?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You speak as though I were just a blind obstinacy.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Not so blind now as you have been, Rolly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>You speak so surely.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>I am sure.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>May I see the letter? <stage>(<hi r="italic">She gives it to him, and he reads</hi>.)</stage> Yes&mdash;I begin&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pb n="79">
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>You remember that night, Rolly? What was it he said? &lsquo;I respect women. So much, that I cherish a hope that one day I shall find a chaste one.&rsquo;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>He said that?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes, that was it. Stuck in my mind somehow.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>George, I want to talk to Rolly alone, now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Rather.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Will you speak of this to nobody, not even to Louise, until I see you again?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Absolutely. Oh, absolutely not a word. Good&hyphen;night, Rolly.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">shaking hands</hi>):</stage> <p>Good&hyphen;night, George. Don't make up your mind about me yet.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Fleming</hi>:</speaker> <p>Oh, my mind is made up. Absolutely. Good&hyphen;night, old thing. Bless you.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="c"><hi r="italic">He kisses</hi> <hi r="smcap">Hilda</hi> <hi r="italic">and goes out</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Tell me, how could Constantine know that about you if&mdash;if&mdash;</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>If he hadn't proved it? That is what I meant when I said that he had now given me leave to speak. You remember I told you I had nothing to conceal for myself. But there was then something, that, to conceal for him. That was why it was difficult for me to answer your questions quite frankly. Now he has spoken for himself.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Then he did&mdash;as I told you to expect?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Yes. You were right to warn me. But I was right not to take your warning. I couldn't have spoiled our lives together, Rolly, more surely <pb n="80">by yielding to his entreaty than by yielding to your suspicion. I had to go. There was no other way in which you could learn what faith is. I know now that there was no way in which I could so fully learn what my love for you is. And he learnt also. I am glad to think that I was perhaps a little able to help him too&mdash;I wonder. Poor Louis.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>Poor devil.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>He was lovely about it, when he realised.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>My dear, I do see. I do.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Clearly&mdash;wholly?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>As I have never seen before. As I shall always see now.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>Then the choice is made.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="r"><hi r="italic">She tears the will in two pieces, and burns it</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi></speaker> <stage>(<hi r="italic">speaking as she does so</hi>):</stage> <p>I shall ask them to let me do the proofs.</p></speech></pdiv>
<stage align="l"><hi r="smcap">Benson</hi> <hi r="italic">watches her until she has finished.
Then she takes the letter, with the same purpose</hi>.</stage>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>May I keep that?</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>If you wish. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He takes it</hi>.)</stage> Rolly, I don't want to go out to&hyphen;night.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Benson</hi>:</speaker> <p>No&mdash;no&mdash;of course not. I'll ring them up. <stage>(<hi r="italic">He kneels on a chair beside her</hi>.)</stage> My dear, my dear, forgive me.</p></speech></pdiv>
<pdiv><speech><speaker><hi r="italic">Hilda</hi>:</speaker> <p>What is there to forgive?</p></speech></pdiv>
</div3>
