<preface>
<p>NOTE</p>
<p><hi r="smcapit">I would</hi> ask Scotch readers to remember that a writer
must use his own native idiom. For me to attempt a
Scotch speech of 1780 for Burns would be as much a
mistake&mdash;not merely in expedience, but in essential fitness&mdash;as it
would have been for me to use the American speech of 1860
for Lincoln or the English speech of 1650 for Cromwell; or
for Mr. Shaw to have written &ldquo;Joan of Arc&rdquo; in medi&aelig;val
French. A writer has, so far as he can, to present the truth
of his subject in the language to which he is bred; that is
all. The purpose of this play is to set down the truth about
Burns as I see it, in my own tongue.</p>
<p>Incidentally, and not affecting this general principle, it may
be observed that Burns in his prose commonly used plain
English; and in the performance of this play the addition of
local colour to the speech can safely be left to the actors.</p>
<signed>J. D.</signed></preface>
